Name: La Fourmigue C
Reference: DRASM, Archéologie Sous-marine, Arles 83, (1983), nos. 277-304; G. Amar and B. Liou,  Archaeonautica 4 (1984), 154; M.-B. Carre and M.-P. Jezegou, Archaeonautica 4 (1984), 134; A. Pollino, Objets Métalliques sur les épaves antiques, (1984), 35-49; B. Liou and P. Pomey, Gallia 43 (1985), 574-5; F. Braemer, L’Exploitation de la Mer. La mer, moyen d’échange et de communication (1986), 149-50; A. Hesnard et al., Archaeonautica 8 (1988), 92 ; Parker (1992), 425; C. Baudoin, B. Liou and L. Long, Une Cargaison de Bronzes Hellénistiques, Archaeonautica 12 (1994).
Comments: A well-preserved tumulus, in spite of looting, of Dr. 1B, stamped on the lip with PAP or ANT. Lamboglia  2 stamped with TERE on the lip and Dr. 1A.
Other cargo:
A fine collection of furniture and sculptural appliques, mostly belonging to bronze couches inlaid with silver and copper; an inscription indicated Greek manufacture.
Also a large dish, a bucket, decorated with a fine Bacchic mask, a candelabrum foot and other pieces of bronze furniture.
Hull remains: Proposed length of about 15m capable of carrying 300 amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia:
A stone mortar and pestle of Cycladic marble, two touch-stones, a tin oil lamp, Campanian B dishes and coarse ware jugs and jars.
Five small pieces of marble (for a merchant to show to clients?).
Ship equipment: Some wooden discs probably belonging to the ship's pumps.

Name: Le Grotticelle
Region: Between Ventotene and S. Stefano, Pontine Islands
Reference: M. Cecchini, Sesto Continente 2  (1980), p. 43 and 46; C. Mocchegiani, Archeologia Subacquea. Note di viaggio nell'italia Sommersa (1986), 178-9; P. Gianfrotta, Le Isole Pontine attraverso I Tempi,  (1986), 214-6; Parker (1992), 486.
Comments: Amphorae of Dr. 1 form marked a much-looted wreck.
Other cargo:
About four hundred pieces belonging to couches, bronze fittings from the legs and carved bone decoration (including female figures and animal heads)  from the bed and back of the couch. 
Other items include bronze fittings from chests and boxes. 
Also a marble base (for a statue), a marble basin, a wooden marline-spike. 
Coarse ware and fineware.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A set of surgical equipment; if 4 probe-like instruments are surgical then they are amongst the oldest examples from antiquity. Some coins, two bronze rings and two small wooden sandals (a child's?).

Name: Koromasna  Cove
Reference: J. Mesi?, Obavijesti HAD-a XXX1/2 (1999), 76; M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 30; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: Intact cargo of Greek amphorae, Cretan AC4 and Aegean ER1. More than 100 each of AC4 and ER1 amphorae now preserved under an iron cage.

Name: Ognina A
Region: Near Syracuse, east coast of Sicily
Reference: G. Käpitan, Recherches sur les Amphores Romaines, (1972), 243-52 and Mariner's Mirror 59  (1973), 229-30; G. Kapitän and M. Price, IJNA 3 (1974), 150-53; P. Gargallo, Mariner's Mirror 58 (1972), 443-6 and pls 12-13; H. Frost, Mariner's Mirror 59 (1973), 334
Comments: 'A substantial amphora wreck'.: Mostly Africano 1, with Dr.20, Beltran 2B and Käpitan 1 and 2 and other forms. One amphora contained 13kg of blue frit used for colouring glass.
Hull remains: The ship was luxuriously furnished: innumerable fragments of mosaic still embedded in cement showed that the floor was decorated with a coloured, figurative design, surrounded by a black and white geometric border. Small marble columns probably flanked a doorway.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Statuettes of bronze (notably a satyr) and blue glass, glass vessels and other luxury items. The wreck is dated by 18 or 19 coins, including issues of Perinthos, Smyrna and Byzantium of AD 210-215. A ceramic hip bath.
Ship equipment: Lead tubing and a group of four bronze pulley wheels.

Name: Kizil Burun Column
Reference:
http://ina.tamu.edu/kizilburun/index.htm
D. Carlson, INA Quarterly 31.1 (2004), 3-9; J. Daniel, INA Quarterly 31.1 (2004), 13-14; K. Trego, INA Quarterly 31.1 (2004), 11-12; D. Carlson,  INA Quarterly 33.1(2006), 1-10; J. Daniel,  INA Quarterly 33.1 (2006), 13-14; K. Trego,  INA Quarterly 33.1 (2006), 11-12; D. Carlson, INA Quarterly 34.1 (2007), 3-10;  D. Hamilton and D. Carlson, The INA Annual 2008 Projects (2009), 11-14.
Comments: Discovered in 1993 and excavated between 2005 and 2009, this is the wreck of a navis lapidaria which carried a cargo of newly quarried Proconnesian marble columns seemingly destined for the Temple of Apollo in Claros, Turkey.
Marble type: Eight Proconnesian marble column drums averaging about 3 feet tall and ranging in diameter from 5 to 5.5 feet. This incremental graduation suggests that the eight drums and one capital comprise a single column over 30 feet tall. Newly quarried stone as the drums are not fluted and still preserve traces of corkscrew-shaped hoisting grooves. A group of large rectangular marble blocks which probably represent architectural elements associated with the column. This area also yielded an interesting array of newly-quarried, roughly-finished marble objects such as a small hand basin, the pedestal for one of two larger basins, and at least 6 uninscribed grave stones or stele. More than a dozen marble blocks.
Other cargo: Undecorated, utilitarian cookware (plates, casseroles). Numerous Italian ceramics including cooking pans. Several types of typical Hellenistic fineware (moldmade bowls, grey ware, and black glaze cups, bowls, and salt cellars).Nine bronze handles.
Hull remains: More than 250 fasteners, most of them copper (or copper alloy?) nails and enough small but well-preserved wood fragments to suggest that some hull remains have survived beneath one or more of the drums. At least 24 timbers have been sent for analysis and some of the transverse timbers were made of ash.
Shipboard paraphernalia: The head of a double axe, an axe-adze, a tool for removing nails, a chisel, (all in concretion). The remains of a large metal cauldron, an intact ceramic jug and a terracotta herm figurine. A worn and corroded bronze coin, probably Greek.
Ship equipment: An anchor (in concretion, which with two lead anchor collars shows the transition from the use of wooden anchors to the introduction of iron anchors), a lead sounding weight, and an elaborate iron concretion that probably represents an important part of the ship's equipment.

Name: Vele Orjule/Lussino
Reference:
M. Jurisi?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.80; M.-E. Stenuit et al, IJNA 30 (2001)196-210; G. Purpura, archeologia Viva 119 (2005), 60-61.
http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/lussino.htm
Comments: A solitary statue was discovered in several pieces in 1997 and has now been fully restored.
Other cargo: A life-size bronze statue of 'Apoxyomenos' was found as a solitary find. Supposedly a Hellenistic or Roman copy of the famous Greek C4th original. Dated by organic material found inside the statue.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A few sherds of Lam. 2 and two solitary Forl. type amphorae found at a distance.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock nearby and another smaller one at a distance.

Name: Mazara del vallo
Region: Between Sicily and Cap Bon, Tunisia
Reference:
http://www.ancientworlds.net/aw/Article/740225             http://www.uciim.sicilia.it/SATIRO/raccolta_foto_SATIRO.htm
http://www.museicapitolini.org/en/eventi/mostra_satiro.htm
G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 120-121; R. Petriaggi, Archaeologia Mediterranea maritima 2007, 193-198
Comments: Discovered in 1998
Other cargo:
A bronze satyr was retrieved on two different occasions: the discovery of the left leg, caught up in the nets of a fishing boat from Mazara in 1997, was followed by the discovery of the body in March 1998,  missing the other leg and the arms, however. The figure had larger than lifesize dimensions and was more than two metres tall. The overall weight of the preserved parts is around 108 kilograms (96 for the body, 12 the detached leg). The young Satyr is caught in the act of dancing, with his arms outspread, possibly holding a cup and a thyrsus, the left leg slightly raised and the head turned to one side with hair flowing around.
His semi-feral nature is shown by his pointed ears.
Hull remains: The remains of the ship were identified by a lateral scansion sonar analysis of the relative stretch of sea.

Name: Aghios Eustratios(?)
Reference: National Museum of Athens.
Other cargo: Bronze statue of Augustus riding a horse.Tthis is the only preserved life-size equestrian statue of him. He wears a heavy chiton and a mantle and holds the reins with his left hand.

Name: Tyre F
Region: On the south side of Tyre
Reference: Summary reports, R. Marx, IJNA 3 (1974), 332; Parker (1992), 1189.
Comments: Presumably amphorae were found at this looted site dated to the C3rd and C2nd BC.

Name: Marmaris B
Reference: G. Kapitän, Tropis 1 (1989),147-62; Parker (1992), 658.
Marble type: Louteria, similar in shape and concretion to those  in the Bodrum Museum.

Name: Kizil Burun
Shipboard paraphernalia: A lagynos.

Name: Serçe Limani B
Reference:
G. Bass, IJNA 3 (1974), 335-38; Türk Arkeoloji Dergisi 22.2 (1975), 33-38; V. Grace, BCH Supp 13 (1986), 551-65; C. Pulak and Townsend, AJA 91 (1987), 31-57; J-Y. Empereur and N. Tuma, BCH 112 (1988), 341-59; Parker (1992), 1071; D. Gibbins, in Z. Archibald et al (eds.), Hellenistic Economies (2001), 273-312.
http://ina.tamu.edu/
Comments: Although many amphorae had been looted before excavation, hundreds remained buried in sand.
Other cargo:
Minor cargo of small handle-less pots possibly for unguents, courseware jugs and black gloss ware. Twenty seven jars of uniform size and shape were found (heights vary between 8.2 and 9.3 cm.).  They may have originally contained unguents as the narrow mouth and carefully formed rim indicate their use for such valuable liquids. The jars may originate in Egypt.
This globular amphora has comparable parallels to ones from Pergamun and Tarsus, but enough differences exist to mark this one as unusual.
Millstones.
Hull remains: Hull timbers with lead sheathing; woven fabric between the two.
Shipboard paraphernalia: It is  known that the ship sank in early summer as the amphorae were packed with freshly-cut brushwood. One stamped amphora from Thasos. A pair of lever-mill stones.
Ship equipment: Lead piping, lead rings and wooden toggles.

Name: Mandalya Gulf B
Reference: G. Bass, Anatolian Studies 36 (1986), 214-16; Parker (1992), 643.

Name: Sigacek

Name: ?ile

Marble type:
Two 10 foot columns, finished state; large verde antico block from Thessaly; five Ionic capitals, a column base, two blocks and a plaque from Proconnesus, some roughly quarried, some half finished. 
Huge unfinished statue of an emperor (4.5m), a  large female bust that may date to the early C2nd AD. A sarcophagus lid, a stele and two bowls. 
There may be more marble buried in the sand.
Hull remains: Hull timbers and metal objects.

Name: Bozukkale
Shipboard paraphernalia: 2 coarse ware bowls and a jug.

Name: Sinope deep wreck A
Reference:
http://archives.cnn.com/2000/NATURE/11/02/ancient.shipwreck/index.html
R. Ballard et al., AJA 105 (2001), 607-23, at p. 616;  C. Ward and B. Ballard, IJNA 33 (2004), 2-13; C. Ward and R. Horlings, The remote exploration and archaeological survey of four Byzantine ships in the Black Sea, in R. Ballard, ed., Archaeological Oceanography (2008, Princeton University Press), pp. 148-173
Comments: A deep-water archaological survey conducted during 2000 about 15-30km west of Sinope revealed 4 of the best-preserved ships from antiquity. This wreck consists of two mounds of pottery, one 23 x 10 m and the other 4 x 4 m, with protruding ship timbers. Amphorae are carrot-shaped, typical of Sinope.
Hull remains: Timbers can be seen but it's not definite that they belong to this wreck. However the ship 's estimated length is 18m.

Name: no name
Reference: http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2003/01/0110_030113_blacksea.html (2002)
Comments: Discovered in 2002 and investigated by a submersible, the ship had been carrying amphora types typical of Sinope, including one very large one, 1m tall x 5m wide. This was the only one brought up to the surface in which there was evidence of bones of freshwater catfish, with cut marks visible on the fish bones. Strangely, several olive pits and resin were also found in the same amphora.

Name: Piadha
Reference: G. Papathanassopoulos, IJNA 9 (1980), 164-67; Parker (1992), 810.
Other cargo: Laconian tiles

Name: Preveza B
Reference: G. Kapitän, IJNA 2 (1973), 185-6; C. Koehler, Archaeological News 8 (1979), 55-61; Parker (1992), 905.
Comments: Corinthian A and B forms, now in the British Museum.

Name: Methone A
Reference: P. Throckmorton and J. Bullitt, Expedition 5 (1963), 16-23; Parker (1992), 693.
Comments: A badly broken-up wreck, presumably with amphorae that are not described.

Name: Marathon
Reference: K. Rhomaios, Arkhailogikon Deltion 9 (1924-5), 145-87; G. Bass, Archaeology Underwater (1966), 79; Parker (1992), 650.
Other cargo: Famous bronze statue of a boy, perhaps the god Hermes. It is the work of the school of Praxiteles and is dated to 325-300 BC.
Hull remains: Wood fragments.

Name: Preveza A
Reference: Brief report only,  I. Vokotopoulou, Arkhailogikon Deltion 24 (1970), 253 and pl.257 b; Parker (1992), 904.
Comments: Graeco-Italic, perhaps Will Type D. Large numbers

Name: Dhrapi
Reference: G. Papathanassopoulos, IJNA 9 (1980), 164-67; Parker (1992), 363.
Ship equipment: Lead anchor stock.

Name: Artemision
Reference: V. Kallipolitis, Athens Annals of Archaeology 5 (1972), 419-26; R. Wünsche, Jahrbuch des Deutschen Archäologischen Instituts 94 (1979), 77-111; Parker (1992), 57; S. Hemingway, The Horse and Jockey from Artemision: A Bronze Equestrian Monument of the Hellenistic Period   (Berkeley:  University of California Press, 2004).
Other cargo: Bronze works of art, including C5th male statue of Poseidon/Zeus brandishing a trident with his raised right hand. It is an original work of a great sculptor, possibly  Kalamis, and a C2nd horse and jockey. The Jockey's physiognomy and original black skin are those of an Ethiopian, but his hairstyle is Greek, which implies that he is of mixed heritage. He is most likely a professional jockey. The best interpretation is that the group was set up in a sanctuary to honour one or more victories in horse races. The large size of the monument and the high quality of the sculpture suggest commission by a royal or wealthy Greek aristocratic. Lots of pottery, two cups and a lamp (perhaps dating the site to ca.150 BC).
Hull remains: Timbers lie in situ.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Stone pestle.
Ship equipment: Lead anchor stock and grinding stones.

Name: Limeni
Reference: G. Touchais, BCH 102 (1978), 678;  Parker (1992), 597.
Hull remains: A large merchant ship?

Name: Rhaphina
Reference: H Hoffman, Ten Centuries that Shaped the West: Greek and Roman Art in the Texas Collections (1971), nos. 206-7; Parker (1992), 982.

Name: Areopolis

Comments: Scattered Lamboglia  2.
Hull remains: Possibly a 30m ship?

Name: Ai-Strate (?)

Name: Palairos (?)

Name: Arwad C

Name: Tyre B
Region: On the south side of Tyre
Reference: Summary reports, R. Marx, IJNA 3 (1974), 332; Parker (1992), 1185.
Comments: Amphorae of the C 1st AD substantially looted.

Name: Tyre C
Region: On the south side of Tyre
Reference: Summary reports, R. Marx, IJNA 3 (1974), 332; Parker (1992), 1186.
Comments: Presumably amphorae were found at this looted site.

Name: Haifa (?)
Reference: International Numismatic Newsletter, 1995, 25.
Other cargo: 40 kg silver coins, tetradrachms of Ptolemy VI, 20kg stuck together and 1,800 coins.
Hull remains: Presumably timbers as the coins were said to be discovered ‘in the wreck of an Egyptian ship’.

Name: Megadim A
Reference: D.M. Wardle, Diver 29.9 (1984), 24-5; A. Raban and E. Galili, IJNA 14 (1985), 353-5; Parker (1992), 689.
Other cargo:
Scattered over an area 100m x 50m -  jewellery; copper bar ingots marked with Greek letters and two circular tin ingots approximately 18cm across.
Many fragments of life-size bronze statues, both human and animal.
Other decorative items of bronze and silver.
Two neck-less amphorae used as containers for miscellaneous items, including bronze bracelets in various stages of manufacture, arrowheads, gilded balance plates, gold diadem leaves and silversmith’s tools.
Hull remains: Copper nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia:
A basalt bowl.
Seleucid and Ptolemaic (Cyprus) coins dating to the 130s BC.
Some cinnabar.
Ship equipment: A sounding lead.

Name: Straton’s Tower
Region: Just to the north of Caesarea
Reference: A. Raban, Centre for Maritime Studies, Report 6 (1981), Centre for Maritime Studies, Report 10, (1984), Results of Caesarea Ancient Harbour Project Vol. I (1989), 184-98; Parker (1992), 1115.
Comments: A significantly-sized ship, possibly c 40m long, that carried dolia set in mud packing with straw, twigs and pine needles. Bulk cargoes contained in dolia transshipped from Sebastos have historically been either salt from the Dead Sea or spices from India. If the ship could be dated earlier, then it could have been bringing building materials such as pozzolana for Herod’s harbour.
Hull remains: Hull of a heavy framed ship, 40-45m long, 9m wide. Shell-first construction of pine with poplar and oak tenons. A unique feature of this ship lies in the use of bolts inserted through the planking and frames from the outside. Pieces of lead sheathing. Numerous iron nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Ivory dice.Three legs from a folding bronze table. A bronze rod of a balance scale.
Ship equipment: Bilge pump. Eight lead rings, possibly brailing rings from the sails. Three ropes made from Esparto grass.

Name: Caesarea Maritima
Reference: www.abyssoblu.com
Comments: Wreck sank on N. breakwater of harbour.
Other cargo: Lead ingots with stamp of Domitian; title GER indicates a date in or after AD 84.
Hull remains: Hull remains.

Name: Hof Hacarmel  A
Reference: A. Raban, Sefunim 3 (1969-71), fig. 3, Science Diving International (1973), 31.
Comments: One pear-shaped amphora but there may have been more.
Other cargo: Bronze statuettes of Venus, Diana and the Dioscuri; Roman coins of Trajan, Hadrian, Antoninus Pius and Faustina the Younger.
Hull remains: Copper nails.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock.

Name: Alexandria A
Reference: B. Vailiti and P. Curto, Mondo Sommerso 22 (1980), 53.
Comments: Probably Dr. 6 amphorae. Large quantities.

Name: Qaitbay 1
Reference: http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/archeosm/fr/fr-alex-rub7.htm
Comments: A  mass of amphorae was found but there was no sign of the ship's hull, which was probably destroyed on the rocky seabed.
Other cargo: Some plain pottery,  fine pottery and lamps.
Ship equipment: Stone anchors.

Name: Deep Tow Site
Reference: F. Spiess and J. Orzech, ‘Location of ancient amphorae in Deep Waters of the Eastern Mediterranean by the Deep Tow Vehicle’, In the Realms of Gold: X Conference on Underwater Archaeology, San Marino, California (ed, W. Cockrell) 1981, 149-159.
Comments: One Rhodian and one Coan.

Name: Callatis B
Region: Off 2 Mai village, near border with Bulgaria
Reference: V. Cosma, IJNA 2 (1973), 54-8; C. Scarlet, Acta Musei Napocensis10 (1973), 529-40 (cf. fig. 3); Parker (1992), 160.
Comments: A cargo of small sized Thasian amphorae deeply buried in sediment. Some of the amphorae bear impressed stamps on the neck with various representations of fruit and leaves, most often a cluster of grapes. Many (?).
Hull remains: Some timbers, apparently substantially preserved.

Name: Shab Rumi
Reference: F. Dumas, Trente Siècles sous La Mer (1972), 187-91; Parker (1992), 1077.
Comments: Coan type, Roman period. A number (?)

Name: Antikythera A
Reference: Weinberg et al TAPA 55.3 (1965); P. Throckmorton Shipwrecks and Archaeology (1970);  www.abyssoblu.com.
Comments: One of the earliest wrwcks to be excavated in 1900. Rhodian, Coan and Lamboglia  2 amphorae were found, about half of which remain on the seabed. Between 70 and 80 amphorae in total. Works of art, pottery and glass ware also formed part of the wreck.
Marble type: 36 marble statues, many of which are copies of bronze originals that are unknown. Fragments of more statues.
Other cargo:
Contemporary works of art and old masters from C 4th-2nd BC, including the bronze Antikythera Youth, a bearded head, a pair of statuettes and a bronze bed.
A large amount of fine and coarse pottery. 
A dozen glass vessels, possibly Alexandrian?
Piles of coins from Pergamum 88-86 BC and gold bars. 
A necklace, a ring and other jewellery. 
Ingots and lead items.
An astronomical computer by which the wreck is dated.
Hull remains: Lead-sheathed hull, part of which has been raised. Elm planks fastened with oak tenons and treenails and bronze nails.
Ship equipment: Anchors and rigging.

Name: Bay of Paroikia
Reference: E. Hatzidaki and G Papathanassopoulos  IJNA 9 (1981); AR 47 (2000-01), 121
Marble type: Two hundred and seven marble objects including unfluted columns and architectural blocks; cinerary urns, some complete and inscribed, the pediment crowning a funerary stele, a lion’s foot, sarcophagus lids; two Doric capitals; the head of a marble statue and the torso of a small statue of Artemis.

Name: Agios Petros Bay(?)
Comments: Two amphora types, unidentified.

Name: Le Grand Congloué A
Reference: J-Y Cousteau, National Geographic Magazine 105 (1952), 1-36; F. Benoit, Gallia Supplement 14 (1961); G. Bass, Archaeology Underwater (1966), 96 and 126; L. Long, Archaeonautica 7 (1987), 9-36; Parker (1992), 474
Comments: Graeco-Italic;  Rhodian, with stamps datable to c. 200 BC; also several other Greek amphoras from Cnidus, Chios etc. Over 400 Graeco-Italian and 30 Rhodian.
Other cargo:
7000 pieces of Campanian A pottery datable to c. 190 BC. 
Some ungentaria, 3 lamps and some Ampuritan Grey pottery.
Hull remains: Lead sheathing.Some half frame timbers.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Weapons.
Ship equipment: Tools, pieces of rigging and of a pump, nails and weights, although these could also belong to Le Grand Congloué B.

Name: Cassidaigne
Comments:
Several Coan amphoras with Greek stamps of ACKA ... ,  ???? ...    ????...
possibly part of the same wreck as Dr 1B and Dr. 43 and 44-45.

Name: Rhône Delta
Reference: D. Brentchaloff and F. Salviat,  Archéologia 245 (1989), 18-22; Parker (1992), 984
Comments: Dr. 2-4 and fragments of dolia.
Marble type: A colossal head of Augustus in Luna marble, 0.7m high belonging to a statue at least 3-4m tall. The marble head was new at the time of loss and belongs stylistically with representations of Augustus from the 20s BC. Also granite blocks.

Name: La Tradelière
Reference: P. Fiori, Cahiers d’Archéologie Subaquatique 1 (1972), 115-17, IJNA 3 (1974), 328-9; B. Liou Gallia 31 (1973), 603-4; J-P. Joncheray, IJNA 5 (1976), 259-60; A. Hesnard, MEFRA 89 (1977), 163; Hesnard et al., Archaeonautica 8 (1988), 55-6; P. Pomey et al., Gallia Informations 1 (1989), 48-9; Parker (1992), 1174; P. Pomey and F. Guibal, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (1999), 66-67.
Comments: A tumulus of twelve types of amphorae (altogether 300-400), the top two layers of which were Rhodian and Chian, Dr. 2-4 (probably Coan), making up 50% of the cargo and Dr. 6.
Other cargo: Tens of thousands of hazelnuts, which formed a layer up to a metre thick. Pottery including Pompeian red plates, rimless platters, fine-wall goblets and two-handled and four-handled cups, as well as two pieces of eastern pottery. Glass cups, stacked in piles of 8 or 10, in six different colours.
Hull remains: A well preserved hull 25m longand 6m wide with a single layer of planking. Portions of the keel, the stempost, strakes, half frames and ribs - typical shell-first construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A 'guttus' or flask with one handle and a relief head of an antelope forming the spout. Some miniature amphorae, possibly a merchant's samples(?).
Ship equipment: Some discs and a bearing from the pump.

Name: Porto Novo
Reference:
H. Bernard et al JRA 11 (1998), 53-81;  J. Chiapetti and H. Bernard, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 63; R. Mazeran in E. Rieth (ed.), Méditerranée antique (1998), 135-138.
http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/archeosm/fr/
Comments: A cargo of unfinished marble and stone-working tools.
Marble type: Over an area of 15m x 7m, four column fragments between 2.2m and 4.8m long with a diameter of 1.5m; five blocks, one of which is large at 23.3 tons, all in an unfinished state from Luna . A total weight is estimated at 138 tons. Some badly finished slabs of veneer of coloured marble, from a variety of sources, Chemtou, Teos, Chios and Carystos,  possibly left over from previous journeys. Black and white quartz from Egypt. A large number of sets of stone-working tools.
Hull remains: A few iron nails, bronze tubing and four bronze nails. Estimated length of ship 25m from the lay out of the marble. Lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Fragments of pottery; 110 fishing weights; at least 3 mirrors, a bronze strigil; bronze vases; a decorated sword and buckle. These suggest the presence of military or official (including female) personnel. A coin of Tiberius AD 27.

Name: Kyrenia
Reference: M.L. Katzev, Expedition 11.2 (1968), 55-9, Expedition 12.4 (1969), 6-14, AJA 73 (1969), 238; R.F.Tylecote, IJNA 6, (1977), 269-283; B. Booth, IJNA 13 (1984), 189-204; R. Steffy, AJA 89 (1985), 71-101; P. Throckmorton, History From the Sea (1987); Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 122-126; M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Comments: A tumulus 10 x 19m of amphorae from Rhodes and possibly Samos, Crete, Paros and Palestine, 404 in total. The ship was old but may also have been attacked by pirates as iron spears were found under the hul and stuck in its sides.
Other cargo:
10,000 almonds, lying in clusters, indicating that they were carried in sacks. 
29 millstones with mason's marks including single Greek letters, but a great variety of size and types of finish, possibly from Cos.
Hull remains: Well-preserved hull, 13.6m long and 4.4m wide of Aleppo pine, sheathed in lead. Traces of woven agave leaves with red-brown resinous pitch between the hull and lead. Major repairs had been carried out. A full-scale replica was successfully sailed in 1987.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Various cooking utensils in sets of 4, iron ingots, a louterion and remains of food. Over 300 lead fishing weights. Ballast of grey volcanic stone. A few coins 316-301 BC and 306-294 BC, one of which comes from Cyprus.
Ship equipment: Tools, 12 unhewn tree limbs, 2 rolls of lead sheathing and 150 lead brail-rings, rigging pieces, including 10 wooden bobbin toggles.

Name: Xerolimini
Reference: C. Giangrande et al, RDAC (1987), 192; Parker (1992), 1233.
Comments: Dense concentration of shattered amphorae, 25 x 10m, and 30cm deep, concreted to the sea bed.

Name: Cyprus
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 350.

Name: Ayios Georghios
Reference: C. Giangrande et al, RDAC  (1987), 192; Parker (1992), 69.
Comments: Rhodian amphorae, 3rd c. BC? (seen by AIW)

Name: Koppo
Reference: G. Bass and M. Katzev Archaeology 21 (1968), 170-1; Parker (1992), 554.
Comments: A badly broken-up cargo of four types  of amphorae, the majority Rhodian, also the rim of a pithos.
Other cargo: Pottery and part of moulded glass bowl.

Name: Cape Kiti B
Reference: O. Engvig and M. Beichmann, Opuscula Athiensia 15 (1984), no. S-130 c; Parker (1992), 213.
Comments: 'A big ship that carried various goods on board.' Only one amphora published, a  Dr. 6A, stamped T.H.B.

Name: Fondana Amorosa
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 414.
Comments: Unidentified amphorae. 'A large quantity'.
Other cargo: Other artefacts?
Ship equipment: A sounding lead.

Name: Cape Andreas F
Reference: J. Green et al., The Research Laboratory for Archaeology, (1970), site 28; Parker (1992), 207.
Other cargo: Corinthian-style roof tiles and cover-tiles, still stacked in position, in two areas. The larger area has about 60 tiles in four rows with another layer underneath; the smaller has about 15 tiles.

Name: No name
Region: Between Rhodes and Alexandria 200 miles off Cyprus
Reference: www.nauticos.com/press/newyorktimes.htm (2001); www.archaeology.org/0103/etc/wreck.html
Comments: An intact cargo of 2000-3000 amphorae, at 2 miles deep and spread over an area 65feet long makes this the deepest ancient shipwreck yet discovered. At least six different types of wine amphoras have been identified and an unusual feature of this wreck is a large, intact metal cauldron that sits upright in the center of the amphora mound. The wreck lies at the midpoint along a line drawn between the ancient trading centers of Rhodes and Alexandria and there are four other possibly ancient shipwrecks in close proximity to the site.
Hull remains: A wooden deck beam and a segment of planking.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Pitchers, a serving bowl and a large metal cooking pot;
Ship equipment: Five large anchors - at least five lead collars and three stocks are still oriented as if they were lying on the foredeck of the ship; ballast stones.

Name: Apollonia B
Reference: A. Laronde, Bulletin de la Société Nationale des Antiquaires de France (1987), 322-330, Giornata lincea sulla archeologia Cirenaica (1990), 75-81.
Comments: Rhodian, stamped with Drakontida and Aristonos. Megarian bowls.
Other cargo: Main cargo of Megarian bowls made at the 'Atelier de Menemakhos' (eastern Aegean).

Name: Apollonia A
Reference: A. Laronde, Bulletin de la Société Nationale des Antiquaires de France (1987), 322-330, Giornata lincea sulla archeologia Cirenaica (1990), 75-81.
Comments: No cargo, maybe salvaged at the time?
Other cargo: Pottery including a black-gloss cup with Greek graffito 'Herakleides'.
Hull remains: Hull of local woods (fir and Aleppo pine with treenails of oak) well built though not large; a circular piece of lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Dated by 2 bronze coins.
Ship equipment: A small jar filled with pitch; a sounding lead, some bronze rings.

Name: Sidi Ahmad
Region: West end of Gulf of Sirte
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 403.
Comments: Date based on marble imports to Tripolitania
Marble type: Two long columns of white marble with green veins (cipollino?).

Name: Marsa -El-Brega Roman
Reference: C. Preece, Libyan Studies 31 (2000), 29-56.
Comments: One of two ancient wrecks probably caused by human error in an area particularly difficult to navigate. Over a hundred amphorae of various types suggest a ship's cargo rather than random discards. It is the first evidence of Neo-Punic forms in the Gulf of Sirte as well as indicating that Tripolitanian amphorae were shipped along the Gulf littoral.

Name: Qaitbay 2
Reference: http://www.cultnat.org/download/PdfConf/New%20Folder/underwater.pdf
Ship equipment: Stone and iron anchors and lead anchor stocks.

Name: Mahdia
Reference: A. Merlin, Mélanges Cagnat (Paris, 1912), 383-97; De Frondeville in J. Taylor (ed.), Marine Archaeology (London, 1965), 39-53; W. Fuchs, Der Schiffsfund von Mahdia (Tubingen, 1963); J.-P.  Morel, Céramique Campanienne: Les Formes (Rome, 1981), 61-4; F. Coarelli, Dialoghi di Archeologia 1 (1983), 45-53; G. Kapitän, IJNA 12 (1983), 145-53; D. Baatz, Archäolischer Anzeiger, (1985), 679-91; Parker (1992), 621; G. Salies et al. Das Wrack (Cologne, 1994).
Comments: One of the first shipwrecks to be investigated, it was discovered by spongedivers in 1907. Huge quantities of antiquities were brought to the surface and are still dispayed in the Bardo Museum in Tunis. Initially thought to be  the private collection of a Roman senator returning from Athens after the sack of Sulla in 86BC, possibly L. Licinius Crassus(?), there is still much debate about whether the goods were simply going to be sold on the open market in Italy.
Marble type:
Seventy Attic marble columns, weighing about 205 tonnes, varying in size from 1.85m to 4.4m. Also bases, capitals and basins. Total weight probably about 250 tonnes.
Seven life-sized marble heads and busts among them the bust of Aphrodite, that had already been used as tondi.
At least four large craters decorated with reliefs showing Dionysiac processions.
Bases, altars, fountain rims, small Doric capitals etc that had obviously furnished one or more sanctuaries. Two of the inscriptions refer to the sanctuary of the paraloi in the Piraeus.
Other cargo:
Full-size and miniature bronze sculptures, including a statue of a winged youth (Eros?) and a herm of Dionysus with the signature of Boethus of Chalchedon, both of which show traces of having been removed from their marble bases; vases and candelabra, other decorative pieces. 
Bronze couches inscribed with Greek numbers, showing that the ship was carrying at least 22 of them.
Hull remains: Remains include the keel  (elm) from which the ship can be judged to have been 26m. Also remains of the garboard strake which was double planked with fabric between the two layers and lead-sheathed.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Assorted amphorae from Italy, Spain and Tunisia; lead ingots stamped with Latin names originating from southern Spain; tiles, a mill-stone and pottery.
Ship equipment: Four lead anchor stocks.

Name: Cavalière
Reference: G. Charlin, J.-M. Gassend and R. Lequément, Archaeonautica 2 (1978), 9-93; J.-M. Gassend, Structure, proportions et tonnage de trois navires de commerce romaine d'après l'étude de leurs épaves (1980); P.  Pomey, Mariner's Mirror 67 (1981), 238; R. Lequément in M. Galley and L. Ladjimi Sebai (eds.), L'Homme Méditerranéen et La Mer (1985), 113; C. Aranegui, Ceramiques Grecques i Hellenistiques a la Peninsula Iberica, (1985), 108.
Comments:
Lamboglia  2, Dr. 1C, 1A and fragments of Coan. Most would have contained wine, a couple of the Dr. 1 still held olives.
The ship could have held at least 400 amphorae therefore she was less than a sixth full. About 25 amphorae equal to only 3 tons.
Other cargo:
A considerable quantity of bones of domestic pigs, without feet or many vertebrae, points to a cargo of quartered meat that may have been smoked or salted.
Black-gloss Campanian ware.
A group of Spanish pottery, jugs, a jar, two goblets in grey ware and 'six sombreros de copa'.
Hull remains: Very well-preserved hull of Bosnia pine with treenails of fir and oak. The hull was patched with lead sheathing. Only 13m long with a width of 3m and a tonnage of 19-21 tons. Three coins found in the mast-step are illegible. The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).
Shipboard paraphernalia:
Coarse ware and two lamps blackened with use.
Various fishing weights and a bronze key.
Coins from Massilia, Numidia and one from Spain.
Ship equipment:
Ballast of 10 tons of beach stone and basalt from Sardinia or southern France.
Lead stocked anchor with a shank of evergreen oak.
A sounding lead, two bronze terminals (from the steering oars?), a pulley wheel and wooden rings from the pump.

Name: Jakljan Island
Reference: M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.21.
Marble type: Three sarcophagi with lids.

Name: Panarea (Alberti)
Reference: Bernabo-Brea and M. Cavalier, Bolletino d'Arte Suppl. 29, (1985), 71-4; R. Wilson, AR 34 (1988-89), 125; Parker (1992), 784.

Name: Punta Mazza
Reference: A. Freschi, in G. Tigano (ed.) Rinvenimenti Subacquei a Milazzo e il Relitto di Punta Mazzo (Messina, 1997), 60-65; A. Olla, ibid., 65-98.
Comments: A large quantity of amphorae .Seven types, the main three are two sizes of Knossos 18, one-handled Agora F65-66 probably from the Ephesus area and Dr. 30. from Cilicia. There are also three Agora G199 from Paphos and some Zemer 57 from Palestine. Two other types are unidentifiable though resemble Syro-Palestinan. Many fragments of others from Asia Minor.
Other cargo: Corinthian relief cups showing the exploits of Heracles, battle scenes, ritual scenes and hunting scenes.
Hull remains: Lead sheathing, bronze and iron nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Tiles from the roof of the cabin, bronze lamps and cups.
Ship equipment: Pump, lead anchor stock.

Name: Beauséjour
Reference: H. Bernard, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (2000), 51-53 and (2001), p.45.
Comments: A relatively small navis lapidaria carrying Luna marble and some amphorae, Dr. 1A, Dr. 2-4 from Tarraconensis, and Gauloise. Dr 20 amphorae may be from a different site.
Marble type: Five blocks of Luna marble well buried in an area 8m x 3m. Different sizes 2.1m x 1.4m x 1.5m = 11.7tons; 1.48m x 1.04m x 0.28m = 1.14tons; 1.33m x 0.76m x 0.3m = 0.8tons; 3m x 1.26m x 0.68m = 6.83tons; 1.9m x 1.26m x 0.55m = 3.9tons. Small tonnage compared to St. Tropez or Porto Nuovo, but similar to Meloria. All blocks are inscribed with quarry marks.
Hull remains: Lead sheathing, six iron nails and bronze nails.

Name: Les Riches Dunes 5
Reference: M.- P. Jézégou, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (2002), p. 47;  M.- P. Jézégou and H. Bernard, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (2003), 41and 52-55.
Comments: Another wreck between Sete and Marseillan, found 30m from the 2 bronze statues (Les Riches Dunes 4), with a cargo of marble.
Marble type: A partially worked block of Luna marble 2m x 1m x 0.4m = 3.3 tons buried in sediment.Twenty-one plaques of grey marble; all are broken, but polished on both sides,  the largest one measures 28cm x 20cm apart from a triangular one of 44.2cm x 55.5cm. Small white column 50.4cm long.An Ionic white marble base of plinth and drum in perfect condition.
Other cargo: The head of an ibis made of lead 12.5cm long. These finds suggest the ship was carrying the property of a private collector.
Hull remains: Nails still in alignment give an idea of the hull shape. Lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A millstone.
Ship equipment: A pipe from the pump, tiles from the roof of the cabin.

Name: Ouest Embiez 1
Reference:
D. Foy and M.- P. Jézégou, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (1995), 61-62; ibid.((2000), 65-66; ibid. (2001), 71-72; ibid. (2002), 65-67; ibid. (2003), 86-90; ibid. (2004), 76-82; ibid. (2005), 76-81;  D. Foy and M.- P. Jézégou in E. Rieth (ed.), Méditerranée antique (1998), 121-134; D. Foy and S. Fontaine, Poseidons Reich XI 17.9.2006, p.18
http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/archeosm/fr/
http://www2.cnrs.fr/presse/journal/1318.htm?print=1
Comments: A secondary cargo of mixed amphorae, eleven Dr. 2-4 from Italy, eight from Gaul, two from Spain, six Agora F65-6 from Asia Minor and two Africano 1B. 30 in total, though some of these (Gaul and Spain) may have been for onboard use.
Other cargo: Principal cargo of colourless glass: irregular blocks of very good quality raw glass up to 25kg each with a total of at least 10 tons stacked in the centre of the boat. More than fifteen fragments of sheet glass, all rectangular except one circular piece with a diameter of 43cm (very rare). At least 2000 pieces of glassware, the majority of which are cylindrical goblets, with different types of bases, stacked together. The sheets of glass were definitely made on the Syrian-Palestinian coast between Acre and Haifa which was famous for its glass production (Pliny NH 36.45; Josephus BJ 11.188; Strabo 16,758). The other glass could have come from any Mediterranean area.
Hull remains: Eleven ribs of 2m long, other fragments including two strakes. The ship was no more than 15m long.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarseware (Eastern Sigillata A and African) and food remnants including animal bones, snail shells and olive stones.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones.

Name: Porticcio
Reference: H. Alfonsi, Bilan Scientifique 2001, 84; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 79; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 99; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 93.                http://www.wmaker.net/ARASM/index.php?action=article&id_article=43913                                                                                                                                       http://lci.tf1.fr/science/histoire/2004-11/decouverte-exceptionnelle-dans-eaux-corses-5518919.html
Comments: A hugely varied cargo  - eleven types of amphorae including Kapitän I and II, Africano I and II, Dr. 20, Gauloise, Almagro 50 and 51c, Béltran 72 and Egyptian - glass and 2 marble statues.
Marble type: Two 2m high marble statues representing the Roman Emperor Philip 1 of Arabia (ruled AD 244-249) and his wife Marcia Otacilia, in fragments but weighing about 600kg each.
Other cargo: African coarse ware and millstones. Sheets of glass and glass objects with a total weight of at least 230kg.
Hull remains: A 25cm wide section of the keel  as well as  pieces of frames and planking.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 18
Reference: L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1999, 41-43; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 54-55
Comments: A small cargo of Luna marble.
Marble type: Seven blocks of Luna marble in disorder over an area 8m long. The main block measures 2.8m x 1.1m, the others are smaller (1.4m x 1.7m, 1.8m x 1.5m etc).

Name: Saintes Maries-de-la-mer 21
Reference: L. Long, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (1999), 41-43.
Marble type: Seven blocks of Luna marble, two of which are completely buried in sediment. The heaviest load of the three marble wrecks at Saintes Marie.

Name: Saintes Maries-de-la-mer 22
Reference: L. Long, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (1999), 41-43.
Comments: A few fragments of Dr. 20 date the wreck.
Marble type: Six or seven blocks of Luna marble over an area 12m long, parallel to the beach. Two of the blocks are half cylindrical, i.e. part columns, 2.1m long. Three others are rectangular.

Name: Punta del Serrone
Reference: I Bronzi di Punta del Serrone: Ricerche Archeologiche Subacquee a Brindisi 1992, Bollettino di Archeologia, (Puglia, 1992); C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana (2002), 457; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 137-46.
Comments: A cargo of amphorae and bronze statues was excavated in the early 1990s. The bronzes may have belonged to a collector or they may have been a cargo of metal ready for recasting.
Other cargo: A bronze foot (45cm) was found in 1972, followed by another 150 pieces of bronze sculpture in 1992 in an area 15m x 10m. Another foot, two statues, one late Hellenistic male nude, another Augustan male in a toga (1.47m). Seven bronze heads are better conserved, two date to the C4th BC, one with a short beard to the Late Hellenistic period, another male head and two female heads to the early Imperial period, and a final male head to late Imperial times. This was either a ship carrying works of art belonging to a private collector or a cargo of metal ready for recasting.
Hull remains: Some pieces of lead sheathing are all that remain on the rocky bottom.
Ship equipment: A sounding lead and a lead ring.

Name: Meloria C
Reference: G. Poggesi and P. Rendini (eds.), Memorie Sommerse: Archeologia Subacqueia in Toscana  (Grosseto, 1997), 181;
Marble type: Eleven large white marble blocks and probably a half-worked column, 170cm in diameter and 350cm long. Total tonnage about 50 tons. Possibly Luna marble?

Name: Stentinello
Reference: G. Käpitan, Sicilia Archeologica 30 (1976), 87-103; IJNA 8 (1979), 101-03; C. Koehler, Beneath the Waters of Time (1978), 236-7; PhD thesis, Princeton, 1979 p.21 and 39; Parker (1992), 1113.
Comments: Corinthian A and B amphorae and a third unidentified type over an area 270m x 60m. Also several pithoi. 'A large quantity' of amphorae. Possibly two wrecks?
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two terracotta louteria, some coarse pottery and several bronze bowls and pots.

Name: Baia di Salinedda
Reference: P. Pala, Materiali imperiali dall Baia di Salinedda (Capo Coda Cavallo) in Da Olbia a Olbia vol. I, 477-94.             http://www.icimar.it/museo/relitto_baia_salinedda.htm
Comments: A wreck site measuring 14 x4m of a ship with a cargo of Africano amphorae.
Other cargo: African red slipware and coarse ware. Eastern Mediterranean glass.
Hull remains: A large number of timbers mainly of pine which suggest a large ship of 30m

Name: Serçe Limani D
Reference: G. Bass II. Kazi Sonuçlari Toplantisi (Ankara, 1981), p. 17; Parker (1992), 1073.

Name: Coscia di Donna
Region: Near Punta del Francese, north-west Sardinia
Reference: http://archeogate.it/subacquea/article.php?id=115&offset=3
Comments: A cargo of marble.
Marble type: A central file of three blocks of white marble 2.2msq.; on each side are four rectangular blocks 2.8m x 1.2m x 0.8m; at the end, four rectangular blocks of the same dimensions. A total of about 100m cubed, weighing 265-275 tons. Could be Luna marble but not certain. Small black and white marble chips, possibly from earlier voyages.
Hull remains: No hull remains but the ship was probably 17.65m long with a breadth of 7.8m, judging by the neat position of the marble blocks.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Some shipboard ceramics under the marble, including Gauloise 5, Agora M254 and Dr.12.
Ship equipment: Lead anchor stock 5m from the marble blocks.

Name: Pozzino
Reference: M. Calabri, Archeologia Viva 1 (1982); D. Gandolfi, Rivista di Studi Liguri 41-42 (1982), 403; E. Ciabatti et al., Subacqueo 17  (1989), 22-34; A. Spawforth, Minerva  June 1990, 9-10; Parker (1992), 898; M. Firmati, Memorie Sommerse: Archeologia Subacqueia in Toscana (1997), 184-192.
Comments: Rhodian amphorae with rectangular stamps of the eponym magistrate and month [Epi Pith]ogeneus Yakinthiou. Three Graeco-Italic amphorae.
Other cargo:
Fragments of Megarian bowls. 
Cuttings of 6 different species of cultivated vines. 
Folded lead sheathing.
A medical chest including a bronze cupping vessel; 136 small boxwood, lidded cylinders grouped in threes containing herbal medicines, such as vanilla and cumin from India. 
The right hand and lower forearm of a wooden and ivory statue. 
Vases made of bronze, lead and tin with foliage decoration;  three glass cups typical of Syrio-Palestine.
A bronze oil lamp decorated with leaves 14.7cm long and probably from the eastern Mediterranean.
Hull remains: Quite a small ship, 15-18m long, with lead sheathing along the central part of the hull.
Ship equipment: Lead sheathing folded up.

Name: Maratea A
Reference: P. Bottini et al, Archeologia Subacquea a Maratea. Catalogo della Mostra (1984), 25
Comments: Dr. 2-4 of at least two types, Coan and Italian  lay scattered off Capo La Secca.

Name: Ladispoli B
Reference: P. Gianfrotta, Mondo Archeologico 57 (1981), 27-31  and Bollettino d’Arte 66 (1981), 70-2; Parker (1992), 566.
Marble type: Nine marble columns, not yet identified, lying in three files of three.
Ship equipment: Two lead anchor stocks, one inscribed with TIBERI – EPAPR , possibly Tiberius Epaphroditus the Imperial freedman who waited on Nero.

Name: Capraia D
Reference: Summary reference only Parker (1992), 265. Could be part of Capraia C wreck of works of art at a depth of more than 100m
Marble type: Marble blocks.

Name: Agropoli
Reference: P. Gianfrotta, Mondo Archeologico 57 (1981), 27-31.
Comments: Only a brief reference has been made to this site.
Marble type: A brief reference to marble.

Name: Vulpiglia
Reference: C. Koehler, Corinthian A and B Transport Amphorae (1979), 46-7; A. Parker, Progress in Underwater Science 5 (1980), 56-7; Parker (1992), 1230.
Other cargo:
Over twenty pieces of  Attic or Corinthian black-gloss pottery.
Over forty bones and teeth of sheep and goats.
Hull remains: Two hull timbers of pine, one of which a strake with closely-space mortices; a medium-large sized ship. A few human bones.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Corinthian A amphorae. Personal items include an alabaster toilet-box, a bronze handle and an iron blade. A modelled head of Silenus in terracotta, possibly part of a shrine on board
Ship equipment: Lead sheets with nail-holes as repair equipment.

Name: Lampedusa B
Reference: Unpublished; Parker (1992), 568.
Comments: A single Rhodian amphora with an illegible stamp on a handle.

Name: Skerki Bank wreck D
Reference: A. McCann and J. Oleson, Deep-Water Shipwrecks off Skerki Bank; the 1997 Survey (JRA Suppl.58) 2004, 40-90.
Comments: Two large heaps, the first of twenty-one amphorae including Dr. 1B and C; the second of at least forty-two amphorae, including the above and six Coan amphorae with double-rolled handles. Twelve types in all; At least 65 amphorae in total
Other cargo:
Several black-glaze plates, and about fifteen cooking ware vessels in first heap. 
Fifteen cooking vessels, a bronze ladle, hundreds of lamps and other artefacts in the second. 
Heavy stone weights for weighing cargo (cf Valle Ponti wreck).
A very mixed cargo that may have been picked up in one place or along the coasts of the western Mediterranean.
Hull remains: Probably a 28m hull, with a width of 8m, based on the heaps. Lead sheathing and fragments of wood.
Ship equipment:
Two lead anchor stocks.
A section of a lead bilge pipe.

Name: Skerki Bank wreck F
Reference: A. McCann and J. Oleson, Deep-Water Shipwrecks off Skerki Bank; the 1997 Survey (JRA Supp.58) 2004, 90-118
Comments: Sixteen amphorae, including ones from Naxos, Baetica, Tunisia and Pompeii.
Marble type: Two layers of marble building stones, including  monolithic columns and large irregular blocks, loaded along the line of the keel (cf. Dramont I, Cape Izmetiste and Isole delle Correnti). The stone may be red granite from Aswan, or grey granite from the western Mediterranean.
Other cargo:
Stacks of coarse ware ceramics of N. African ware. 
Bronze artefacts.
Hull remains: Probably a 20m hull with a 5m beam.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarse ware containing fig and field chickweed seeds; also remnants of grapes and olives.
Ship equipment: Lead pipe, iron anchor.

Name: Skerki Bank wreck G
Reference: A. McCann and J. Oleson, Deep-Water Shipwrecks off Skerki Bank; the 1997 Survey (JRA Supp.58) 2004, 118-128.
Comments: Tunisian Mana 2C, Italian and Spanish Dr. 28, Dr. 9 amphorae. At least 12 in total.
Other cargo: At least seventeen coarse ware bowls, pitchers and jugs.
Hull remains: Hull probably about 15m long.
Ship equipment: Three lead anchor stocks, lead pipes.

Name: Skerki Bank wreck B
Reference: A. McCann and J. Oleson, Deep-Water Shipwrecks off Skerki Bank; the 1997 Survey (JRA Supp.58) 2004, 128-154.
Comments: At least 30 Campanian, Cretan (AC 3) and Egyptian wine amphorae, oil amphorae from Tripolitania.
Other cargo: Probably a lot of organic cargo, now disintegrated.
Hull remains: Hull probably of 40m; pine planking
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarse ware including a rare Pompeian amphora, Form X; a lamp.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock.

Name: Camarina A
Reference: A. Parker, Sicilia Archeologica (1976), 25-9; S. Tortorella MEFRA 93 (1981), 362; G. Di Stefano, Atti IV rassegna di Archeologia subacquea (1991), 127-34; AR 42 (1995-96), 71 (including photos).
Marble type: Two giallo antico columns (others salvaged?), 6m long,  wedged in by sandstone blocks.
Other cargo: Plates and casseroles of black-rim ware. Two small bronze buckets with swan's head terminal handles and other bronze objects, including strigils. A samovar 25cm high decorated with theatrical masks just below the rim and a lion's head protome snout. A rare (perfume?) container with blue enamel inlay, 24cm high, decorated with vine leaves and trellis patterns.
Hull remains: The hull is preserved and is of standard construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A lead box (34 x 23 x 43.5cm) with central circular hole and tendril designs on either side of the opening, and 34 lead sling shot.
Ship equipment: An iron anchor.

Name: Terrauzza
Reference: A. Parker and D. Squire, IJNA 3 (1974), 27-34; Parker (1992), 1143.
Comments: Badly smashed Kapitän 1 and 2 in concreted heaps a metre deep over an area 20 x 30m.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A colourless glass bottle and some unidentifiable table pottery.

Name: Marzamemi A
Reference: G. Kapitän, Klio 39 (1961), 290-300; Atti del III Congresso Internazionale di Archeologia Sottomarina, Barcellona 1961, (1971), 296-309; Parker, IJNA 10 (1981), 317-20; (1992), 670. http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article.php?id=114.
Comments: A navis lapidaria that was also carrying Kapitän amphorae.
Marble type: Main part of the cargo was fifteen grey-white marble blocks from Attica, in an area 30m x 8m. Some blocks are  partly shaped as columns or architraves, largest of which weighed 40 tons. The biggest column measures 6.2m long and 1.78m diameter. Total weight 172 tons.
Hull remains: None, but probably a length of 30m and breadth of 7-8m for a cargo of 200 tons.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Fragments of amphorae, some of which appear to be Africano.

Name: Capo Granitola A
Reference: P. Gianfrotta and P. Pomey, Archeologia Subacquea (1981), 219; G. Purpura, Archeologia Viva 2.5 (1983), 44-8; P. Pensabene in G. Fiorentini et al (eds.) Archeologia del Mediterraneo. Studii in Onore di Ernesto de Miro (2003), 533-543        http://www.archeogate.it/subacquea/article.php?id=77&offset=2
Comments: A 30 x 15m site of a marble cargo.
Marble type: Over sixty blocks approximately 3m x 1m x 1m in 8 files. Some salvage appears to have taken place in antiquity. Total weight c. 350 tons. Proconnesus marble in trapezoidal form; chips of Parian and unidentified Asiatic marble and verde antico were found between the blocks, presumably the remains of previous voyages.
Other cargo: Small pieces of pottery.
Ship equipment: Iron anchor and a large lead stock

Name: Giardini Naxos
Comments: Necks of two Mauretanian amphorae, found beneath two columns.
Marble type: Twenty-four  white-grey Aegean columns and thirteen green cipollino rectangular blocks, over an area of 17m x 5-6m, with an estimated weight of 95 tons. The columns are in a half-finished state, while the blocks show only a surface roughing-out. Loaded at the same time forming two levels inside the hull.
Hull remains: Bronze and copper nails of different sizes, all with a round head and square section shank, some of them severely twisted. The ship probably hit the bottom quite hard, as one of the columns is also broken in two pieces.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A large piece of a mortarium of lava found beneath one of the columns.
Ship equipment: Bronze fittings and fixtures: a boss with a ring, possibly fixed by nails to a curved wooden support, and part of a bronze hinge, probably from a door or wooden lid.

Name: Isola delle Correnti
Comments: A large wreck site, c45 x 12m, of white marble
Marble type: 350 tons of marble blocks, white with a bluish streak, probably Asiatic. One fragment of a worked architectural piece.
Other cargo: Some pottery
Hull remains: Piece of lead sheathing. Supposed length between 40 and 48m, with a minimum breadth for the hold of 10-11m and a cargo of 350 tons.

Name: Capo Taormina
Reference: G. Kapitän, Atti del III Congresso Internazione di Archeologia Sottomarina 1961, (1971), 296-309; F. van Doorninck, in  G. Bass (ed.) A History of Seafaring based on Underwater Archaeology (1972), 138; Parker, (1992), 256.
Marble type: Thirty-seven columns and two blocks of green marble, probable weight 90-100 tons.
Hull remains: Copper bolt with a square plate only part of the ship to survive.
Ship equipment: A sounding lead.

Name: Capo Granitola D
Reference: G. Purpura, Atti IV rassegna di Archeologia subacqueo (1991), 137 ; Parker (1992), 232.
Marble type: Corinthian and Ionic capitals and plinths in white marble with blue veins, probably Asiatic.

Name: Spargi
Reference: G. Roghi, in  J. du Plat Taylor (ed.), Marine Archaeology  (1965), 103-18; N. Lamboglia, Rivista di Studi Liguri 30 (1964), 258-66; S. Picozzi, Subacqueo 5 (1977), 78-80; P. Gianfrotta and P. Pomey, Archeologia Subacquea (1981), 141 and 339; F. Pallarés, Forma Maris Antiqui 11-12 (1983), 221-4; Parker (1992), 1108.
Comments: Main cargo of Dr. 1A and 1B but also quite a number of small Rhodian. Only 400-500 are accounted for, taking up c. a sixth of the hold so either a good deal was salvaged or there was perishable cargo too. 400-500 excavated out of a possible 2,500.
Other cargo:
A great quantity of black-gloss Campanian pottery stacked in the hold. 
Also Greek fineware from Megaria and Pergamum.
Hull remains: Hull at least 30m long although in poor condition; copper sheathing crumpled from impact; very fine construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two marble columns and two altars from a shrine; bronze lamps; a statuette; a bronze helmet and part of a skull still attached, a cuirass.
Ship equipment: Five sounding leads.

Name: Dramont D
Reference: A. Tchernia, Gallia 27 (1969), 469-70; J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d’Archéologie Subaquatique 1 (1972), (1973), (1974) ; A. Hesnard et al., Méthodes Classiques et Méthodes Formelles dans l’Etude des Amphores (1977), 186 and 293 ; C Panella, BCH Supp. 12 (1986), 618, note 13 ; J. Leuthner and E. Stender, Cahiers d’Archéologie Subaquatique 8 (1989), 85-9 ; Parker (1992), 374.
Comments: Over a site 18 x 16m, necks of amphoras; some Rhodian, with some Greek stamps on the handle, most of which contained the remains of figs. Others were Dr. 2-4, probably from the Aegean, two of which contained dates. Others Dr. 5 from Cos.
Other cargo:
Tilted piles of mortaria of two main types; the first with a flat rim was in four sizes (27, 33, 40 and 46cm diameter); one was stamped with HERM[  ]. The second variety, wall-rimmed was larger and heavier and mostly stamped with the Figlinae Marcianae. 
A set of four bronze pumps, one signed by the maker CLAV[DIVS] F[ECIT].
Shipboard paraphernalia: Several lamps and a lead jar. A Rhodian amphora full of resin, a Spanish fish-sauce amphora and a small jar full of flour. Various cooking utensils and crockery. Kingsholm 117 amphorae with dates.
Ship equipment: One lead-stocked and three iron anchors, two sounding leads. A basket of copper nails, with an axe, gimlet, graver, axe-hammer, key, knife and other tools.

Name: Bagaud A (a)
Reference: F. Benoit, Gallia 16 (1958), 37; Gallia 20 (1962), 169; J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d’Archéologie Subaquatique 1 (1972), 25 and 33; P. Pomey et al., Gallia Informations 1 (1989), 30; Parker (1992), 76.F.
Comments: Pear-shaped, of late C1st-2nd AD, according to investigation by DRASM.

Name: Bagaud A
Reference: F. Benoit, Gallia 16 (1958), 37; Gallia 20 (1962), 169; J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d’Archéologie Subaquatique 1 (1972), 25 and 33; P. Pomey et al., Gallia Informations 1 (1989), 30; Parker (1992), 76.
Comments: At least 2 mortaria , late Roman spatheia.
Other cargo: At least 2 mortaria , late Roman spatheia.

Name: Lastovska
Region: Mljet Island, north west of Dubrovnik
Reference: D. Vrsalovi?, Istraživanja i Zaštita Podmorških Arheoloskih Spomenika u S.R. Hrvatskoj (1974), 53 and 240; M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 35.
Comments: Amphorae of mostly transitional La.2/Dr.6A but also some Rhodian imperial.

Name: Kvarner Gulf
Reference: Plongées 76, xvi; Parker (1992), 561.

Name: Silba B/ Arat Cape
Region: Silba Island, north west of Zadar
Reference: Z. Brusiç, Otocki Ljetopis Cres-Losinj 3 (1980), 162 and 166; Parker (1992), 1085; M. Jurisi? Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.1.
Comments: Rhodian amphorae with a ribbed belly. 'Largish cargo'.

Name: Margarina Point
Region: near Susak Island, NW of Zadar
Reference: D. Vrsalovi?, Istraživanja i Zaštita Podmorških Arheoloskih Spomenika u S.R. Hrvatskoj (1974), 53 and 240; M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.43.
Comments: A cargo of unfinished blocks of stone and marble columns, the largest such cargo in the eastern Adriatic.
Marble type: Several unfinished blocks and  20 worked white marble columns.
Other cargo: Flat roof tiles and curved roof tiles.

Name: Pakleni/ Izmetište
Reference: B. Ilakovac, Diadora 4 (1968), 183-202; M. Orli? and M. Juriši?, Obavijesti Hrvatska Arheološka Drustva 18 no. 1 (1986), 43; J. Isteni?, Diadora 10 (1988), 99-110; Parker (1992), 773; V. Gaffney et al., Projekt Jadranski otoci, Arheološka baština otoka Hvara, Hrvatska (Oxford: BAR International Series 660, 1997), 109-110; M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.20.
Comments: A combined cargo of stone blocks and pottery.
Marble type: About 10 half-finished stone blocks, one of them dark greenish granite, while others are of limestone.
Other cargo: About 2,500 pieces of various  pottery, half are Eastern Sigillata B (plates and platters) many with stamps, potter Sporos's amongst them. The rest was eastern coarse ware with about 10 forms of mugs, jugs, dishes, pots, plates, pans etc.
Hull remains: Timber and nails.

Name: Viganj (Sv. Ivan promontory)
Reference: Z. Rapani?, Arheoloski Pregled 14 (1972), 79-80; D. Vrsalovi?, Istraživanja i Zaštita Podmorških Arheoloskih Spomenika u S.R. Hrvatskoj (1974), 39 and 239-40, figs. 2, 30 and 67; J. Isteni?, Diadora 10 (1988), 99-110; M. Juriši?, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no.73; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A large but now looted cargo of ECW pottery.
Other cargo: Estimated 50,000 pieces of Eastern coarse ware pottery, much looted, including bowls, dishes, trefoil mouth jugs, pots, lids, platters with profiled rim, braziers etc. More than 200 pieces were raised.
Hull remains: Hull is well preserved.

Name: ?avlena
Reference: D. Vrsalovi?, Istraživanja i Zaštita Podmorških Arheoloskih Spomenika u S.R. Hrvatskoj (1974), 53 and 240; Parker (1992), 288.
Marble type: Marble ‘elaborated’ columns and other stones.

Name: Savelletri
Reference: G. Kapitän,  Ricerche e Studi 6 (1972), 41-54, IJNA 2 (1973), 185-6; C. Koehler, Beneath the Waters of Time, (1978), 237, Corinthian A and B Transport Amphorae, (1979), 21, 40 etc; Parker (1992), 1043
Comments: Fragments of Corinthian A and B, a Greek amphora of undefined type. At least 120 fragments of necks, handles and bottoms.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Household ware.

Name: Valle Ponti
Reference: S. Ruscito, Archeologia Viva 1 (1982), 19-26; M. Bonino, Sewn Plank Boats (1985), 91-3; F. Berti, Rivista di Studi Liguri 51 (1985), 553-70, Archeologia Subacquea 3 (1986), 25-36; Parker (1992), 1206; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 165-68.
Comments: Four types of amphorae, including Dr. 6, Greek variant of Dr. 2-4 with tituli picti and Chian.
Other cargo:
A large load of shingle in the centre of the hold; 102 lead ingots of five varieties of shape but all marked with the counter stamps  L.CAE.BAT and AGRIP probably of Spanish origin. 
Coarse pottery, bronze vessels including pots, pans, ladles, strainers and plates. 
Six tiny votive models of temples each with Hermes or Venus inside of lead.
A number of five-foot long boxwood logs.
Seventeen lamps.
Heavy stone weights for weighing cargo.
Hull remains: Originally stranded on a sandy beach, a well preserved hull 25m long x 5.4m. Planking seams were caulked with pitched vegetable fibre and stitched.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Single Greek amphora. A dozen shoes and sandals. A bronze balance, animal bones (mutton). Strigils, dice, gaming pieces and a sword.
Ship equipment: Baskets, leather bags, sacks, and a collection of carpenter’s tools. One basket contained shellfish, another fish-hooks. A  large stone weight of 32.7kg inscribed M and T.RVFI . Iron anchor.

Name: Secche Di Ugento A
Region: South of Gallipoli, Gulf of Taranto
Reference: G. Roghi, Forma Maris Antiqui 2 (1959), 315-6; P. Desy, L’Antiquité Classique 52 (1983), 188; Parker (1992), 1066.
Comments: A concentration of broken  ‘Greek or Rhodian’ amphorae, possibly Dr. 2-4.

Name: Tremiti Islands (?)
Reference: L Casson, Archaeology 21.3 (1968), 219; D. Ruegg, IJNA 1 (1972), 199.
Marble type: ‘A load of marble slabs and blocks’, relatively intact, in at least four layers.

Name: Taranto C
Reference: P. Throckmorton, Shipwrecks and Archaeology (1970), 10 and 28-9, History from the Sea (1987), 78-80; Parker (1992), 1133.
Comments: Coan and Rhodian amphorae at the end of the line of anchors. 'Hundreds of broken amphorae'.
Other cargo: Hundreds of broken roof tiles.
Ship equipment: A line of 5 lead anchor stocks each weighing 590kg beginning a mile off shore, leading to a reef near the coast.

Name: Riace
Reference: L. Vlad Borrelli and P. Pelagatti (eds), Due Bronzi di Riace (Bollettino d'Arte, Serie Speciale 3) 1984; C. Moccehgiani, Archeologia Subacquea. Note di viaggio nell'Italia Sommersa (Rome, 1986), 170; Parker (1992), 985.
Other cargo: Works of art:  two male bronze statues of C5th BC type, but probably Hellenistic or Roman copies. Tenons of lead show that they have been taken from their bases and are therefore probably spolia. Also other statue fragments including a shield-grip.
Hull remains: A fragment of the keel.
Shipboard paraphernalia: The lead lid of a jar.
Ship equipment: 28 lead rings.

Name: Capo Cimiti
Reference: P. Pensabene, IJNA 7 (1978), 105-118 and 223-4.
Comments: A 12 x 6m site of 100 tons of cipollino marble
Marble type: Five columns of cipollino, 8m long or less, lie parallel on a rocky bottom .

Name: Cap Camarat 2
Reference: M.-B. Carre, Bilan scientifique 1992, 50-1; Bilan Scientifique1993, 49, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 50-51.
Comments: A cargo of oil amphorae.
Other cargo: Red slip Arretine ware. Eastern sigillata A.
Hull remains: Very well preserved section of the hull. Parts of the cabin.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Tableware and metal tools ( 2 bronze 'simpula', a spatula , tweezers and a curette that may be medical impements; a lamp; a fibula decorated with a bird's head. A box filled with a concretion of coins and fish hooks. A touchstone.
Ship equipment: Pipe from the bilge pump.

Name: Dramont I
Reference: A. Lopez, Bilan Scientifique 1991, 52-53; Bilan Scientifique 1993, 51; A. Joncheray and J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d' archéologie subaquatique13 (1997), 165-195; A. Joncheray, in E. Rieth (ed.), Méditerranée antique (1998), 139-156.
Comments: A navis lapidaria whose 3 remaining blocks of marble were curiously not covering the hull which was found a few metres away,
Marble type: In an area of 500m sq, three blocks of africano marble were found (2.2m x 1m x 1m; 3.8m x 0.95m x 0.8m; 2.68m x 1.1m x 1m). A total weight of 23 tons.
Other cargo: A complementary cargo of polished (pumice) stones, equivalent to 500 litres. Several hundred kilos of corundum, a very hard and heavy mineral probably from the island of Naxos.
Hull remains: On the eastern side is a large fragment of the hull, more than 8m long of more than thirty frames and seven strakes, two of which are larch. On the other side are two fragments of the keel and some strakes.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Statuette (or mirror handle?) in bronze of a cobra. A scrolled oil lamp. Already broken fragments of Dr. 2-4, Dr.7-11 and Dr. 20 amphorae. A very crumpled bronze urn.
Ship equipment: A piece of lead piping.

Name: La Maddalena
Reference: Bollettino di Archeologia 13-15 (1992), 213-4.
Marble type: Fragments of slabs of marble in different sizes.
Other cargo: Some African tableware.

Name: Sanguinaires
Reference: H. Alfonsi and P. Gandolfo, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 13 (1997), 35-74;                                 http://www.wmaker.net/ARASM/index.php?action=article&id_article=43913
Comments: A mixed cargo of amphorae, ceramics, glass and ingots.
Other cargo: Coarse ware, fineware, red and black-glazed pottery. Attic lamps. Small copper ingots and millstones as ballast. At least 550kg of glass, both manufactured and unmanufactured.
Hull remains: None of the hull itself, only some copper nails and fragments of lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A bronze coin of Ptolemy Euergetes (246-221BC) or Ptolemy IV (211-204BC).

Name: Lixouri
Reference: Press reports in G. Touchais, BCH 105 (1981), 805; Parker (1992), 604.
Marble type: Six headless statues of three male nudes, a draped female and a seated male;  two Ionic capitals, four half-column bases.

Name: Ag Pavlos Bay (?)
Comments: Many amphora fragments.

Name: Lindos A
Reference: N. Nikolitsis, Antike Welt 12 (1981), 47-9; Parker (1992), 598.

Name: Akandia A
Reference: N. Nikolitsis, Antike Welt 12 (1981), 45-7.
Comments:
A well-preserved wreck of Roman Rhodian amphorae, both full-size and half-size, with capacities of 22 and 11 litres respectively, was found covering an area 15 x 11m. 
The site had already been looted.

Name: Paloi (?)
Other cargo: Large cargo of glazed plates.

Name: Syrna Island (?)
Reference: www.hcmr.gr/english_site/services/it_app/archeology.html (2004)

Name: Idhra
Reference: P. Throckmorton, Shipwrecks and Archaeology (1970), 225; Parker (1992), 510.

Name: Ithaki 1
Reference: www.norwinst.gr/Feltarbeid/Ithaki.htm (2000); K. Delaporta et al. IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87.
Comments: Unidentified amphorae in one of the wrecks with a ‘complete amphora cargo’.

Name: Corfu
Reference: P. Throckmorton, Shipwrecks and Archaeology (1970), 225; Parker (1992), 337.
Comments: Present but not identified, destroyed by divers.

Name: Dhia A
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 359.
Comments: Main cargo of Rhodian amphorae, also some Nubian, Coan, Dr. 18 and 25.

Name: Cape Sidero A
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 214.
Comments: Unidentified amphorae?

Name: Matala
Region: North of Bay of Matala, South Crete
Reference: Grile and C. Davaras (1963), 43-9; Parker (1992), 681.
Comments: Present but not described apart from what looks like a Schoene 8 of local origin from an illustration.
Ship equipment: Three heaps of ballast stones.

Name: Ayia Galini
Region: West end of Mesara, south Crete
Reference: V. Theophanidis, Arkhaiologike Ephemeris  1949; M. Hood and P. Warren, BSA 61 (1966), 169; I. Sanders, Roman Crete (1982), 165; Parker (1992), 68.
Other cargo: A variety of bronze statue fragments and statuettes. Bronze and brass weights, filled with lead, lamps, a portable altar, rings, locks, tools and various handles and feet from bronze vessels. A hoard of 259 coins, closing with Probus (AD 276-82).
Hull remains: A piece of lead, apparently hull sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Shipboard pottery, and an amphora with a mid-3rd century parallel.

Name: Camarina E
Reference: AR 42 (1995-96), 72 (including figure).
Comments: A cargo of Graeco-Italic amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A helmet, 34cm high, of the Montefortino A type, probably of the third century BC, with exaggerated cuspings on the cheek pieces.

Name: Mercury
Reference: G. di Stefano, Archeologia Viva xix. 84  (2000), 86-8; AR 47 (2000-01), 166 (including photos).
Other cargo: Bronze objects including two containers, three lamps and a statuette of Mercury. One of the lamps is of Campanian manufacture and another Egyptian.

Name: Barbarossa
Reference: M. Zecchini, L’Archeologia nell’Archipelago Toscano (1971), 183; F. Pallarés, Forma Maris Antiqui 11-12 (1983), 184-5; Parker (1992), 90.
Comments: Graeco-Italic amphorae, indicating a probable wreck.

Name: Secca Del Bagno
Region: Off west coast of Lipari Island
Reference: E. Will, Hesperia 51 (1982), 352; L. Bernabò-Brea and M. Cavalier, Archeologia Subacquea 2 (1985), 65-6;
Comments: Much looted wreck of 7 Graeco-Italic amphorae, similar to Le Grand Congloué A; and 1 unidentified Greek amphora.
Ship equipment: Lead anchor stock 1.49m across decorated with two bosses (shells?) on each arm.

Name: Porto Ercole A
Reference: P. Rendini in M. Martelli et al, Archeologia Subacquea (1982), 43-4; Parker, 1992, 887.
Comments: Dr. 1A, Apulian, Punic and Greek amphorae.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock decorated with knucklebone signs.

Name: Torre Sgarrata
Reference: P. Throckmorton, National Geographic  135 (1969), 282-300; B. Booth, IJNA 13 (1984), 189-204.
Marble type: Eighteen roughed out sarcophagi and twenty-three large blocks and marble veneer weighing at least 160 tons, from Thasos. Alabaster from Asia Minor. Total tonnage possibly 250 tons.
Hull remains: The ship’s length was at least 30m and the hull of Aleppo pine had been repaired with a patch. The spaces between the frames and planking were packed with twigs of tamarisk.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Tripolitanian and other amphorae, pottery, tile fragments, two glass vessels, a cuirass buckle and several coins including one of Commodus AD 180-192.

Name: Grado (Julia Felix)
Reference: S. Picozzi Subacqueo 16 (1988) 46-50; R. Auriemma, MEFRA 112 (2000), 27-51; C. Beltrame and D. Gaddi, IJNA 34 (2005), 79-87; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 184-91; C. Beltrame, IJNA 36 (2007)138-147; JP Oleson and R. Stein, IJNA 36 (2007), 415-416; P. Dell'Amico, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 7 (2010).                                               http://www.archeosub.it/news1999/news9911.htm#felix2                                                                                                                                       http://www.archeosub.it/news2000/news0007.htm
Comments: At least one layer of several types including Africano I, Tripolitanian, Coan, Dr.5 and Kapitän 1. They held garum and small pieces of fish that were perfectly preserved. Small amphorae of North-east Italy. It seems that all of the amphorae were being re-used to carry fish products. At least 600 in total, estimated 23-25 tons.
Other cargo: Bronze stands with lions’ paws and acanthus decoration. Glass, much of it waste glass, packed in a barrel which had disintegrated; some square bottles with the base mark C SALVI GRATI.
Hull remains: The ship is estimated 18m x 5m, lead sheathed and some of the frames are squared off. The right side of the ship is completely preserved and shows a mortise and tenon construction, with all the frames built from pine, while planking is either of pine or elm. Some strakes, of Alpine larch, are a repair made by patch-tenons. Presumably a short-haul trade ship? A bronze coin was found in the mast-step.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A dolium, common and African pottery. A box of fishing hooks. Some games including a die. Bronze figurine of Neptune.
Ship equipment: A bronze steelyard-weight in the form of Minerva and a conical sounding lead. Many wooden elements of the rigging have been preserved including a large block with six pulleys and a bilge pump that are unique, as well as3 wooden toggles. An iron anchor.

Name: Punta Scifo A
Reference: P. Orsi, Notizie degli Scavi (1911), 18-24; N. Lamboglia, Rivisti di Studi Liguria 40 (1974), 155-91; P. Pensabene, IJNA 7 (1978), 105-18 and 233-4; Parker (1992), 965.
Comments: Unidentified broken amphorae.
Marble type: Pavonazzetto and white marble from Docimium and grey-white marble from Proconnesus: columns, basins, blocks, capitals, bases, tables and a statuary group of Cupid and Psyche, some roughed out, some half-finished and some finished. Consular dates of AD 197 and 200 cut into some of the columns. 150 tons were raised from an area 50m x 50m, 3m thick and in 2 sections (cf Marzamemi A).
Hull remains: Oak planking from a hull 30-35m long, with large iron nails and lighter planking of a lighter wood, maybe fir.
Shipboard paraphernalia: High quality shipboard items include bronze lamp with a base decorated with three dolphins. Plaques of slate and marble may have been samples to help with ordering.

Name: Torre Chianca
Reference: Unpublished, Parker (1992), 1153.                                                                                                                             http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html               site 155, area 9
Comments: A shipwreck of Dr. 43 (AC 4) wine amphorae from Crete and marble columns.
Marble type: Five marble columns, 8-9m long of cipollino, lying approximately 50cm apart, still in the original position in which they were transported. Another 2 are still buried in sand.
Other cargo: A lead seal marked with a Greek monogram and a star.

Name: San Pietro
Reference: J.B. Ward-Perkins and P. Throckmorton, Archaeology 18 (1965), 201-9;  A. Alessio and A. Zaccaria, Atti del Congresso Nazionale di Archeologia Subacquea: Antium May-June 1996 (Bari, 1997), 211-234; R. Petriaggi et al, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 7 (2010).
Comments: Amphora fragments.
Marble type: Twenty-three half-finished sarcophagi,  some left double and some with lids in fine white, crystalline stone, maybe from Aphrodisias. Most of the shapes are rectangular, while nine are rounded at the ends. Total weight about 75 tons.
Other cargo: Tile fragments.
Hull remains: Two elm frames with square holes where iron nails had been, The ship may have been about 20-22m long, judging by the position of the marble.
Ship equipment: A lead ring and a sheet of lead.

Name: Zwammerdam E
Hull remains: s

Name: Zwammerdam F
Hull remains: i

Name: Palagruza B (Pupak Reef)
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 62; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A badly looted site of a cargo of amphorae and pottery.
Other cargo: Pottery, numerous sherds of clay mortaria and, uniquely for the Adriatic,  chamber pots (lasanua). South Italic services of 'orlo bifido' dishes with plates/lids and Pompeian red ware plates were also found.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A massive profiled bronze rod of indefinite function

Name: Bumbiste
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 4
Comments: Various scattered amphora sherds may signal a shipwreck.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock was found nearby may be part of the same site.

Name: Drazica
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 6

Ship equipment: Some corrided iron, possibly an anchor.

Name: Kopa

Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock was found nearby.

Name: Kopiste
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 29, and in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A cargo of amphorae that was well preserved on first inspection in 1993 but devestated by 1995.

Name: Krbar
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 32
Comments: A cargo of Dr 29(?) amphorae

Name: Lirica
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 36
Comments: A cargo of Dr 6A amphorae

Name: Mala Palagruza
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 39

Ship equipment: Remains of an iron anchor and a lead anchor stock.

Name: Mali Frasker
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 40
Comments: Dr 6A
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock.

Name: Mrcara
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 47

Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 53; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
