Other cargo: Mortaria
Ship equipment: A large amount of ballast stones indicate that the ship was partially empty when it sank.

Name: Pelegrin (cape)
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 54
Comments: A totally looted site of amphorae and pottery.
Other cargo: ECW -like pottery

Name: Skolj od Volam
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 74

Name: Supetar
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 66  and in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A dolia shipwreck although there are no hull remains.

Name: Supetric
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 69
Comments: A probable shipwreck of tegulae and imbrices.
Other cargo: A large quantity of tegulae and imbrices suggests a shipwreck.

Name: Tijascica
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 78
Comments: Only piles of fragments remain from this amphorae wreck.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock and an iron anchor stock were found nearby.

Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 83
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock was found nearby.

Name: Vratnicka
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 90
Comments: A cargo of different-sized Dr 2-4 was found.

Name: Bay of Naousa
Reference: Five wreck sites?

Name: Ithaki 2
Reference: www.norwinst.gr/Feltarbeid/Ithaki.htm (2000); K. Delaporta et al. IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87.
Comments: A cargo of several thousand amphorae froma ship estimated to have been 25m long.

Name: Ithaki 4
Reference: www.norwinst.gr/Feltarbeid/Ithaki.htm (2000); K. Delaporta et al. IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87.
Comments: A cargo of lead ingots.
Other cargo: Lead ingots.

Name: Ithaki 3
Reference: www.norwinst.gr/Feltarbeid/Ithaki.htm (2000); K. Delaporta et al. IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87.
Comments: A cargo of roof tiles.
Other cargo: Roof tiles.

Name: Skerki Bank
Reference: McCann and Freed 1994

Name: Torre Flavia C ?
Reference: http://www.gatc.it/ritagli/torreflavianave.htm
Comments: Dated by Arretine ware to first years of 1st c AD - Augustan; assumed to be different from Torre Flavia B (Parker 1158). Some interesting shipboard items, well preserved in the mud.
Hull remains: Fairly well preserved, with an estimated size of 20m length and 5 m width.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Cooking pots and tableware including pans and pots of various types and sizes, jars, cups and plates all of decent quality. Some of them are certainly Arezzo production as indicated by the pottery with Arezzo stamps imprinted on them. Particularly valuable are some trappings of a back of a bed, decorated with carvings and moldings, culminating with the head of a duck, whose empty slots in the head and beak indicateng that originally it was embellished with colored stones . Even more unusual was the discovery of a wooden box covered with a tiny lock of bronze. Surprisingly it was found that it contained capsules of coriander and cumin. Both substances were widely used in medical treatment. In particular, the coriander and cumin were used to treat stomach ailments, ever present on board an ancient ship
Ship equipment: A dozen wooden disks with holes in their centre  were found in the middle of the ship. They belonged to the internal workings of a manually operated hydraulic pump that sucked water from the bilge.

Name: Culip VIII
Reference: C. Carreras et al, Culip VIII i les Amfores Haltern 70 (Monografies del Centre d'Arqueologia Subaquatica de Catalunya, 5), 2005
Comments: A Roman wreck discovered by divers and subsequently excavated by the CASC in 2002-03, one of the largest known to have carried Haltern 7 amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Seven broken pots and fragments of amphorae, a fish hook and 6 fishing weights of different forms.

Name: Bou Ferrer (Alicante)
Reference: http://www.elpais.com/articulo/cultura/joya/mundo/antiguo/mar/valenciano/elpporcul/20061114elpepucul_4/Tes               http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2006/11/061120-rome-ship.html         F. Cibecchini et al, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 2 (2006), 43-56
Comments: The ship is estimated to have been 30m long with capacity for around 400 tons of cargo, making it twice the size of most other Roman shipwrecks found in the Mediterranean (?) Newspaper reports say 1200-1500 amphorae, of Spanish fish products were on board, around 70 of which had been looted before excavation took place in the early 2000s. Forty intact amphorae were brought to the surface with many of their lids found inside. Because the ship sank onto its side, it is hoped that not only a significant part of the hull, but also much organic material may be well preserved. The site has been covered by 250 sq m of netting and steel bars.
Hull remains: Probably still fairly intact buried in the sand.

Name: Sinope deep wreck C
Reference:
http://archives.cnn.com/2000/NATURE/11/02/ancient.shipwreck/index.html
R. Ballard et al., AJA 105 (2001), 607-23; C. Ward and B. Ballard, IJNA 33 (2004), 2-13; C. Ward and R. Horlings, The remote exploration and archaeological survey of four Byzantine ships in the Black Sea, in R. Ballard, ed., Archaeological Oceanography (2008, Princeton University Press), pp. 148-173
Comments: A deep-water archaological survey conducted during 2000 about 15-30km west of Sinope revealed 4 of the best-preserved ships from antiquity. This wreck consists of three piles c. 5 m across, of  carrot-shaped Sinope amphorae. The site was examined in 2000 and 2003 with noticable differences in the visibility of the amphorae.
Hull remains: Several timbers were seen. The ship's length is estimated at 8.5m.

Name: Sinope deep wreck B
Reference:
http://archives.cnn.com/2000/NATURE/11/02/ancient.shipwreck/index.html
R. Ballard et al., AJA 105 (2001), 607-23, at 616-7; C. Ward and B. Ballard, IJNA 33 (2004), 2-13; C. Ward and R. Horlings, The remote exploration and archaeological survey of four Byzantine ships in the Black Sea, in R. Ballard, ed., Archaeological Oceanography (2008, Princeton University Press), pp. 148-173
Comments: A deep-water archaological survey conducted during 2000 about 15-30km west of Sinope revealed 4 of the best-preserved ships from antiquity. This wreck consists of a single cluster of amphorae, larger than wreck A. Length at least 25 m x 15 m wide. Mostly carrot-shaped Sinope amphorae, many more broken visible ones than at sites A and C,  but also one large oval amphora suggesting a 5th-7th c. AD date.
Hull remains: A substantial number of timber planks. The ship's estimated length is 14-16m.
Ship equipment: Possible bilge pipe.

Name: Sinope deep wreck D
Reference:
http://archives.cnn.com/2000/NATURE/11/02/ancient.shipwreck/index.html
R. Ballard et al., AJA 105 (2001), 607-23; C. Ward and B. Ballard, IJNA 33 (2004), 2-13; C. Ward and R. Horlings, The remote exploration and archaeological survey of four Byzantine ships in the Black Sea, in R. Ballard, ed., Archaeological Oceanography (2008, Princeton University Press), pp. 148-173
Comments: A deep-water archaological survey conducted during 2000 about 15-30km west of Sinope revealed 4 of the best-preserved ships from antiquity. This is a very deep wreck c 25km off shore with its 11m mast still standing. AMS date from timber rudder support. No cargo visible, except for 3 Sinope amphorae, but since the deck was intact any cargo is probably below deck. Comparisons have been made with the mosaic of a ship from Kelenderis, Turkey.
Hull remains: The ship without visible cargo was almost perfectly preserved, (although significant parts of the hull are missing), 14m long with an 11m mast. This is a unique example of an ancient ship’s deck. Eighteen top timbers, stern post, rudder support and stanchions also present and show mortise and tenon construction. Radiocarbon dating of a sample of fir wood gives a date of 410-520 AD.

Name: Atlit A
Reference: Radan 1981; Raban, 1985: 33-7
Other cargo: Parker notes Assyrian bronze helmets, Babylonian weights (in the form of swans), furniture and candelabras.
Hull remains: Partly preserved.

Name: Acquaviva
Comments: A buried Roman wreck with scattered amphorae, only briefly reported.

Name: Acque Chiare
Reference: Sciarra, 1973; Freschi 1989, 455.
Comments: A poorly preserved, looted wreck extending over 50 m.
Other cargo: At least 4 terracotta 'vaulting tubes', but these may not have been part of the cargo.

Name: Addaya
Reference: Mascaro, 1961 and 1971, 74, fig.7

Name: Agay A (Camp Long)
Reference: J.-P. Joncheray and M. Jezegou, Bilan Scientifique 1996, 104-105; J.-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1998, 50-51; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 103-04.
Comments: Originally excavatged in the 1970s, the wreck was re-examined in the 1990s. The flat-bottomed ship is estimated to have been 20-25m long and at least 7m wide and was carrying only 200-300 trade items. A ship's boat was also found, 8-10m long, with the skeleton of a man of Mediterranean type with slight negroid features, 1.7m tall and aged 25-35 years with a sword and cutlass-sheath.
Other cargo: At least 7 basalt grinding stones atnd 250 bronze ingots of slender form, 38-40cm long. A brass ingot and some copper vessels were possibly also part of the cargo.
Hull remains: Short timbers attached by means of a large number of iron nails. There are no joints in the planking which is nailed to the frames. The construction was transitional between shell-first and frame-first

Name: Agde A
Other cargo: Campanian B pottery
Hull remains: Traces of ship's timbers
Ship equipment: Iron anchor possibly from this site

Name: Agde B
Reference: Bouscaras, 1953, 1954, 1962: 11 and fig.5, 1974; Jannoray, 1954: 413; Gallet de Santerre, 1961; Carrazé, 1970d; cf. Clavel, 1970:409 ff.
Comments: A 'quantity' of amphorae  but reports disagree as to their form which suggests that several wrecks lie on top of each other cf. Marzamemi B, D, G and H although there is no direct evidence to confirm this.
Other cargo: Campanian B pottery
Hull remains: Traces of timbers

Name: Agde D
Reference: Galllet de Santerre, 1961, 209-211; Liou 1973, 575-78 and 1975 576; Oleson 1983, 161-63.
Comments: This wreck is situated between Agde wrecks B and C but further offshore.
Hull remains: Oak frames and fir planking survive along with oak tenons and treenails. Lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A jug in white fabric and sherds of Campanian A  and black gloss ware. A piece of basalt mill stone.
Ship equipment: A pulley block with a scrap of rope and a piece of a yard.

Name: Agde E
Reference: Bouscaras 1961, 19; Laubenheimer-Leenhardt 1973, 57.
Comments: The amphorae were apparently asociated with a small, water-worn copper ingot.

Name: Agde F
Reference: Bouscaras, 1962, 6-11 and 1964a, fig 3.

Name: Agde G
Reference: Gallet de Santerre, 1961, 205; Clavel, 1970, 445-6; Marechal, 1987.
Comments: A cargo of red lead clay.
Other cargo: Tablets of litharge (red lead) clay were stacked together in an area 20 x 14m, representing about 100 tons.

Name: Agde H
Reference: Gallet de Santerre, 1964, 486; Clavel, 1970, 445-6.
Comments: A wreck of lead ore (galena) along with other unspecified material has only been briefly reported.
Other cargo: Lead ore.

Name: Agde J
Reference: Gallet de Santerre, 1966, 464-5;  Laubenheimer-Leenhardt 1973, 134-45 and 178ff; Fonquerle, 1982, 128-30.
Comments: A group of lead ingots signify a wreck.
Other cargo: A group of lead ingots of Republican Spanish type. They bear the mould-marks L. PLANI.L.F.RUSSINI, SOC GARGILI T F ET M LAETILI ML and SOC.M.C. PONTILIENORUM.M.F..The ingot of L. Planius Russinius is exactly similar to 2 ingots found in the Mahdia wreck.

Name: Agde K
Reference: Bouscaras, 1960, 29-31 and 1961, 17-19; Gallet de Santerre, 1962, 622;  Laubenheimer-Leenhardt 1973, 146-61 and 169-172
Other cargo: A group of lead ingots, cast in oval mounds resembling the "Pinna nobilis" shell and inscribed with TT. Compare the ingots from the Cabrera B wreck.

Name: Ai-Yannis Tholou A
Reference: Catling 1984-5, 57.
Comments: According to Touchais, 1985, 831, there is only 1 wreck of Chian and Cnidian amphorae at this site not 2, Ai-Yannis Tholou A and Ai-Yannis Tholou B.

Name: Aigus Blava
Dating: End C 1st BC- early C1st AD
Reference: Unpublished
Comments: A possible wreck site of a concentrated deposit of broken amphorae, although there is clearly contamination in accordance with the dating of the 2 types of amphorae.

Name: Ain El Gazala
Reference: Panella, 1974, 597
Comments: A group of Kapitan 2 amphorae in CyrenenMuseum come from a wreck in this location.

Name: Ajaccio
Reference: Demians d'Archimbaud, 1972, 13-4.
Comments: The remains of a ship laden with various goods were found in 1960.
Other cargo: Yellow or green glazed ware pottery 'a stecca' (ribbed), imitating products of Pisa, commonly found in Liguria and less frequently in Corsica.

Name: Akandia B
Reference: N. Nikolitsis, Antike Welt 12 (1981), 49.
Comments: A second cargo of amphorae was found near Akandia A, described by the Swedish expedition as a 'new type of transport-amphora',

Name: Akko A
Reference: Unpublished, information from M. Prausnitz
Comments: A Hellenistic wreck is known to lie north of Akko.

Name: Akko B
Reference: Unpublished, information from M. Prausnitz
Other cargo: Millstones.

Name: Albenga
Reference: Taylor, 1965, 53-66; Lamboglia 1961a and 1964a and 1972b, 447 and 1973; Tchernia and Pomey 1978; D'Angelo, 1980, 53-4; Ferrandi, 1980; Gianfrotta, 1981b, 236; Morel, 1981, 64; Pallares, 1977a and 1985d.
Comments: This large wreck consisted of a tumulus up to 2m high, 30 x 10m, almost completely unconcreted, buried in silt. Over 1200 amphorae have been raised from a debated 9 or 6 layers, which may originally have totalled between 5,000 and 13,500 amphorae, i.e. 500-600 tonnes
Other cargo: A variety of pottery: black-gloss ware, including Campanian A plates and 'imitation Campanian' bowls. Some is said to have been stacked between the amphorae.
Hull remains: Well preserved. The frames are of oak, the planking (lead-sheathed) of soft wood. The main mast survives, unusually, in position, square as far as the main beam and circular above.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A number of Lamboglia 2 amphorae. Black-gloss plates and jugs, grey ware, cooking ware and jugs with external slip, coated with a black lining internally. Seven bronze helmets of different types, possibly for use by the crew or as part of a passenger's belongings.
Ship equipment: Roof tile fragments and a lead horn. Lead pipes.

Name: Alcudia
Reference: Mascaro, 1962 and 1968 and 1971, 81-4.
Other cargo: 'A considerable number' of tin ingots is said to have been found. About 30cm tall, with a hole near the top, and weighing 10.5-11.5 kg. They were slightly alloyed with silver.

Name: Alexandria B
Reference: B. Vailiti and P. Curto, Mondo Sommerso 22 (1980), 53.
Comments: A cargo of millstones, presumably ancient is shown in a photo without further description.
Other cargo: A cargo of mill-stones.

Name: Algajola
Comments: A widely spread site, over an area of 200m.
Other cargo: 44 uninscribed lead ingots.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A few Dressel 1A amphorae.
Ship equipment: 6 anchor stocks.

Name: Alghero
Comments: Only a press report has been published about a Roman ship with a cargo of bricks.
Other cargo: Bricks/ tiles.

Name: Ametilla de Mar A
Reference: Vilaseca, 1954 and 1958, 237; Oliva and Domenech, 1971. Information from M. Wlfida Perez.
Comments: A cargo of Dressel 12 amphorae damaged by fishing trawlers.

Name: Ametilla de Mar B
Reference: Vilaseca 1958.

Name: Ametilla de Mar C
Reference: Unpublished.
Comments: A wreck of very broken up Dressel 20 amphorae is known here but no details have been reported.

Name: Ancona
Reference: Profumo 1986.
Comments: Groups of amphora fragments could be the remains of a wreck.

Name: Antalya
Reference: Bass, 1966, 87; Throckmorton, 1970a, 217-219.
Comments: Unconfirmed reports from sponge divers indicate there may be as many as 4 copper ingot wrecks in the area. One of these seems to be earlier than the Cape Gelidonya A wreck.
Other cargo: Copper ingots.

Name: Antheor
Reference: Demians d'Archimbaud, 1972, 13.
Comments: A wreck with glazed ware discovered before 1960 in inknown circumstances.
Other cargo: Glazed ware similar to that of the wreck Ajaccio.

Name: Anzio
Reference: Gianfrotta and Pomey 1981, 222.
Comments: A cargo of tufa blocks has been summarily reported.
Other cargo: Tufa blocks, presumably ancient.

Name: Aragnon
Reference: Carraze, 1970e and 1976a, 71-2, fig.5; Pomey et al, 1989, 25-6.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A flat-bottomed amphora and a large jug were also found, presumably not part of the cargo.

Name: Ardenza
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2000, 238 no 6

Name: Ayios Stephanos
Comments: Mound of amphorae measuring 24 x 12m.

Name: Bagaud B
Comments: A cargo of small tin and iron ingots weighing 2-3kg each
Other cargo: Tin and iron ingots, some marked. According to one round inscription, the merchants were Celts, specifically Hypocelts who were assembled by a Greek named Heracleides for the coomercial exploration of tin.

Name: Bagaud C
Reference: L. Long and G. Volpe, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 73-74;  Bilan Scientifique 1998, 45-46; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 63-64
Comments: A cargo of Gauloise 4 amphorae first discovered in the 1960s and recently re-examined. Although only several amphorae have been found, they probably numbered several hundred originally.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A few fragments of ceramics including a cup, Hayes 196, and a pot Hayes 197. A terracotta pipe may be left over from a previous load, possibly belonging to a heating system.

Name: Les Basses du Can
Comments: An area 80 x 90m was assessed by a single-seat submarine in 1987.

Name: Preveto
Comments: The first Arab wreck found in Sicilian waters.
Other cargo: Cups, pitchers and bowls. Many tiles.
Hull remains: The ship measured at least 25m long

Name: Bera
Reference: Berges, 1970; Corsi-Sciallano and Liou, 1985:153; Liou, 1987b: 284
Comments: A substantial cargo that covered an area of at least 12 x 7m.

Name: Bozburun Byzantine
Reference: http://www.diveturkey.com/inaturkey/selimiye.htm        L. Dillon Gorham and V. Bryant, IJNA 30 (2001), 282-298;  S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 61-63; M. Harpster, IJNA 34 (2005), 88-94; M. Harpster, IJNA 38 (2009), 297-313           http://www.inadiscover.com/projects/all/southern_europe_mediterranean_aegean/bozburun_turkey/introduction/
Comments: Dating changed since Parker 1992 as the site was re-examined by the INA from 1995-98. The hull remains provide some of the earliest evidence for the arithmetical design and construction methods that later dominated ship building in the Mediterranean.
Hull remains: Quite well preserved with the keel and most of the starboard side of the bottom surviving. Probable size 15 x 5m. White oak keel and planking from NW Anatolia, felled in AD 874, unusual use but suggests emphasis on strength and durability. Construction sequence is notable as a mix of Classical period edge fastenings and frame-based design. Brushwood dunnage was still inplace between some of the amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: At least 10 cooking pots, all black with a nearly spherical body, a flared rim and 1 or 2 broad strap handles; 6 pitchers; 2 copper jugs; a set of 3 very fine glass goblets with a small, mould-blown glass bottle; a lamp amd a bronze steelyard beam with lead counterweight. A very small elephant tusk, the left antler of a deer and a lump of arsenic sulfide (for pigments)  were presumably personal items.Absence of coins and valuables suggest that the crew had time to collect their things and abandon ship.
Ship equipment: An anchor, of typical early Byzantine cruciform pattern.

Name: Cadiz C
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2004, 213 no. 1
Comments: Flavian

Name: Cala Gadir
Reference: P. Selvaggio and S. Tusa, IJNA 38 (2009), 417-420
Comments: An area scattered with amphorae down to a depth of 100m, difficult to establish individual wrecks. However, there does seem to be a coherent wreck datable to the end of the C3rd/first half of the C2nd BC.

Name: Cala Rossa
Reference: H. Bernard and F. Cibecchini, Bilan Scientifique 2004, 92-93; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 99; F. Cibecchini et al, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 2006, 13-41
Comments: Discovered in 1962 and re-examined in the early 2000s, the site covers an area of 65m sq. NB Date change since Parker
Shipboard paraphernalia: A large amount of common ware and cooking pottery (jars, ollae, pots etc.)

Name: Cala Rossano
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 459; F. Arata,  Archeologia Subacquea. Studi, ricerche e documenti 1 (1993), 131-151.
Comments: A partially looted site excavated in 1990.
Ship equipment: Elements of the bilge pump are all that remain.

Name: Calanque de l'Ane
Reference: S. Ximenes and M. Moerman, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 12 (1994), 95-112; Bilan Scientifique 1997, 49-50; Bilan Scientifique 1998, 39; Archaeonautica 14, (1998), 299-302
Comments: A very robust ship, about 25m x 6m, carrying a cargo of tiles.
Other cargo: A cargo of tiles, tegulae and imbrices, still in rows.
Hull remains: Well preserved section of 13.4m of robust construction. A massive mast step sits on 2 lateral keelsons; it is supported on both sides of the mast-step cavity by 2 pieces of buttressing with a triangular profile, elements never seen before on an ancient wreck. These pieces rest on the lateral keelsons and are nailed at their ends to the frames. A bronze sestertius of Domitian was found in the mast-step.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Ceramics: plates, jugs, bowls, several terra sigillata bowls, oil lamps, some amphorae (Dr 20 and Gauloise 4) and glass containers. A piece of leather possibly from a sling. A sestertius of Titus.

Name: Camarina B
Reference: G. di Stefano, Archaeologia maritima Mediterranea 2007, 143-156
Comments: A cargo of 73 oil lamps.
Other cargo: A block of 73 North African oil lamps that had been carried in fabric sacks, and all were marked with the maker's mark STACTE as well as being decorated
Hull remains: Some preserved, four bronze nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A bronze stylus, a bronze dolphin, a silver cockerel (5cm high) a marble plate, a 2-handled silver cup, a bronze stone-cutter with pointed ends and a hole for hanging it up; a bronze spoon with a long handle (15.7cm).

Name: Cap Bear C
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369
Hull remains: The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1,  Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).

Name: Sud Lavezzi 5
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2005, 94-96.
Comments: The site covers an area 30 x 15m with a variety of scattered remains but no obvious principal cargo suggesting wheat or some other organic material.
Other cargo: Tegulae; ceramics, terra sigillata plates from N Italy etc
Hull remains: About 20m of the hull seems farily well preserved from what seems to have been a substantial ship. Fragments of lead plates (sheathing?), a bronze nail.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Gauloise 5 amphora.
Ship equipment: Six to eight iron anchors; a piece of the pump.

Name: Cap del Vol
Hull remains: The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).

Name: Cap Gros C
Reference: B. Gauthier, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 55; Bilan Scientifique 1995, 63
Comments: A small cargo of amphorae from the Adriatic, unusual to find this far west.
Ship equipment: Three stockless lead anchors, an iron anchor and a lead ring

Name: Cape Gelidonya A
Reference: Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 26-33, incl. illustrations and site plan;         http://www.inadiscover.com/projects/all/southern_europe_mediterranean_aegean/cape_gelidonya_turkey/introduction/
Comments: Originally discovered in 1958 and re-examined in 1994, this is the oldest shipwreck ever found! A Cypriot cargo of copper ingots and scrap bronze, although the personal possessions of the crew suggest a Canaanite origin.
Other cargo: 34 flat four-handled copper ingots (25kg each) cast in the shape of an ox hide, several tin ingots, several raw bronze ingots and broken bronze tools (scrap axes, adzes, knives and a spade carried in wicker baskets)) destined to be melted down for re-use.
Hull remains: Little remains of the hull, although there is enough to show mortise and tenon construction. Brushwood dunnage still lay in the bottom of the ship's hold.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A set of smith's tools including a small anvil, hammers, a whetstone, stones to polish metals and a bronze block pierced with holes to make metal thread, suggesting that a smith was sailing on the ship. Other possessions include a lamp and a pair of stone mortars made in Syria, as were 4 scarabs and a cylinder seal. There were also nearly 60 graduated stone weights of Near Eastern origin, including Egyptian qedets and Syrian and Canaanite nesefs and shekels. A bronze bracelet was found in a jar of  glass beads. Knuclebones
Ship equipment: A stone anchor of Near Eastern type, was found about 100m away from the main site in 1994.

Name: Capo di Torre Cavallo
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 11, area 6

Name: Capo Rasocolmo A
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 459; Bacci 1994

Name: Carry-le-Rouet
Comments: A 10m site
Marble type: 24 tons of local French limestone.

Name: Cavallo A
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Cefalu
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/77/3/archeologi-in-fondo-al-mare-di-gianfranco-purpura.html
Shipboard paraphernalia: Fragments of a lecturn?
Ship equipment: Iron and stone anchors and a nearly complete wooden anchor.

Name: Chiessi
Reference: http://www.legambientearcipelagotoscano.it/localmente/storia/archeologia.htm
Other cargo: Bronze ingots.

Name: Chretienne A
Reference: P. Pomey and F. Guibal, Bilan Scientifique,1996, 102; Bilan Scientifique, 1998, 52
Comments: Originally excavated in the 1960s, the wreck has been re-examined more recently.
Hull remains: Fairly well preserved, some of the keel, strakes and frames have been examined and were built of pine and oak and a small section of beech. A mast-step coin, a bronze of Punic Pantelleria dating from 217-50 BC, was found.

Name: Chretienne C
Reference: P. Pomey and F. Guibal, Bilan Scientifique, 1996, 102
Hull remains: Fairly well preserved. An unusual apsect is the use of yoke-elm for parts of the keel.

Name: Chretienne D
Reference: J-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 54; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 13 (1997), 121-135
Comments: Over 2,400 amphora sherds have been identified, 58% of which are Amalgro C and 17% are Dr 23, thus giving an estimated total of 500 amphorae.
Ship equipment: At least 2 iron anchors

Name: La Ciotat C
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2001, 64-68
Comments: A site measuring 16.5 x 3.5m of a cargo of Dr 1A amphorae
Shipboard paraphernalia: Thirty fragments of coarseware including 'ollae'.

Name: Colonia de Sant Jordi A
Reference: http://www.abc.se/~pa/publ/comm-rom.htm#SJ1

Name: Agios Petros Byzantine
Reference: K. Delaporta et al, IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87
Comments: Partly excavated in the 1970s, this wreck was re-examined in 2001 during a Greek-Norwegian deep water archaeology survey.

Name: Cova del Infern
Comments: Dolia

Name: Cueva del Jarro B
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 190 no. 2
Comments: "fin du Ier siecle"

Name: Dhokos
Reference: Master Seafarers: The Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 98-105.                 http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?6
Comments: Originally discovered in 1975, the site was re-examined between 1989 and 1992. Although nothing remained of the ship itself, more than 15,000 pottery shards and other artfacts were found over a surface area of 690sq m. The sunken Dokos cargo is impressive for its quantity and the variety of pottery types it contains. It is certainly one of the largest assemblages so far known of Early Helladic II pottery and testifies to the high level of ceramic technology of this period, just before the introduction of the pottery wheel.
Other cargo: Most of the 1,381 objects recorded were vase fragments dating from the Early Helladic II  period, inlcuding saucers, deep and medium-depth bowls, pots, jugs and plates. Fragments of a pyxis, a cylindrical or spherical box with a lid were also found. Larger vases included several wide-lipped earthenware jars and a pithos. Grinding wheels, fragments of lead ingots and obsidian blade shafts were also found.
Shipboard paraphernalia: 'An abundance' of coins.
Ship equipment: 2 anchors made of greenish schist pierced with a hole and lying at a depth of 34m and 38m, weighing 18.5kg and 21.5 kg were found about 14m away from the main cargo. These suggest a ship of only 15-20m long.

Name: Diano Marina
Reference: T. Mannoni and S. Sfrecola, Archeologia Subacquea 1995-96, 111-112; F. Pallares,Archeologia Subacquea 1995-96, 127139; C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369; S. Marlier, Archaeonautica 15 (2008), 156
Comments: This shipwreck illustrates the final period of Tarraconensian amphorae exports
Hull remains: 4.5m preserved, corresponding to the keel, a part of the side and 9 sections of frames. The ship probably measured 20-22m with a width of 6m. A bronze as was found in the mast-step.

Name: Dramont A
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998, 52
Marble type: Stone blocks measuring 4 x 1 x 1m
Hull remains: Well preserved 17m x 4-8m  portside section.

Name: Dramont B
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Dramont C
Reference: J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 12 (1994), 5-51; Bilan Scienifique 1998, 52
Comments: A small coastal boat, 12-14m long, that was carrying amphorae, ceramics and iron bars
Other cargo: Iron bars and blocks of resin; 3 millstones. Numerous ceramics, ollae, olpes, jars, plates, cups and some copper tableware.
Hull remains: A 6m x 1.6m section was preserved and some ligature attachments were seen, cf Cap Bear 3 wreck
Shipboard paraphernalia: Stone slabs interpreted by J. P. Joncheray as a work bench for cutting out amphora stoppers.
Ship equipment: Ballast of limestone blocks. Four different anchors, 3 of which had lead stocks.

Name: Dramont E
Reference: C. Santamaria, Archaeonautica 13 (1995); M. Bonifay et al, in L. Rivet and M. Sciallano (eds). Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 197-198; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 72
Comments: Initially discovered in the 1960s, the site was re-examined in the 1980s and early 90s. A small ship, 13m long, that could have carried between 700 and 750 amphorae in 2 layers and at least 800 pieces of terra sigillata.
Other cargo: 30 tubuli of which 22 were intact may have been  part of the cargo? 800-900 plates of terra sigillata D  (Hayes 61B, Hayes 64, Hayes 65 and Hayes 50 B), some with geometric motifs, others botanical.
Hull remains: About 10m of the keel was preserved and the rest of the remains are fairly well preserved. Mortise and tenon joints were paced 10-14cm apart along weak areas of planking and 26-31cm elsewhere. Bronze nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarseware - a variety of jugs, pots, plates; 2 oil lamps, one of which originated in North Africa; a millstone; measuring weights and fishing weights. 143 coins dating from the reigns of Constantine, Valens and Theodosien.
Ship equipment: Iron anchors, sounding leads

Name: Dramont F
Reference: J-P Joncheray, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 4 (1975), 91-132
Comments: A  small ship, only 10-12m long.
Hull remains: Shell first construction with mortise and tenon joints, set 19-36cm apart.

Name: Dramont G
Comments: A cargo of tiles, amphorae and ceramics.
Other cargo: Tegulae and imbrices from Frejus, cf Bartelemy B and Roches d'Aurelle wrecks.

Name: Est-Perduto 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique  2005, 93; C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369
Comments: A mcu pillaged iste of Dr 2-4 amphorae

Name: Favaritx
Comments: Syrian wreck
Other cargo: Hundreds of bronze plates, keys, chains, candelabra, statuettes, balances and coins - Christian liturgical objects,

Name: Femmina Morta
Hull remains: One of the latest dated ships to be externally sheathed in lead

Name: Les Fourmigues
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Gandolfo
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 190, no 4

Name: Gela A
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 458; G. Fiorentini, in Quaderni dell'Istitituo di Archeologia della Facolta di Lettere e Filosofia della Universita di Messina 5 (1990), 25-39; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 109- 13                                                                                                                                                                                                                http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/7531639.stm for video of 2008 raising of hull
Comments: The ship was constructed with the sewn technique.
Other cargo: Pottery
Shipboard paraphernalia: A bronze tripod, 4 small clay altars, a bone flute and stylus and 8 vegetal fibre baskets.

Name: Giens A/Redonne B1
Reference: L. Long and A. Hoyau, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 66
Comments: Originally excavated in 1972, the site was re-examined in 1997, and is in a fairly bad state. NB date change since Parker
Other cargo: Campanian A ceramics - Lamboglia 27Ba cups with palms et 27c with rosettes as well as small cups L34a.

Name: Giglio Campese A
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 46; M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Other cargo: Attic and Corinthian ceramics, circular ingots (80cm diameter).
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Corinthian bronze helmet
Ship equipment: A wooden toggle.

Name: Giglio Porto
Reference: P. Dell'Amico and P. Rendini, Archeologia Subacquea 1995-96, 157-165; P. Dell'Amica, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea I (2004), 13-39G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 46
Comments: A fairly small but robust ship originally measuring 15 x 5m, wrecked at least 50m from the port.
Hull remains: Fairly well preserved.

Name: Goica/Gojca Islet
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 11
Comments: Although other amphorae (Dr 2-4 and Dr 1) and remains of a lead bilge pump are mentioned by other sources, this may be unreliable information. NB Date change since Parker
Shipboard paraphernalia: Three mugs of Izmetiste type are mentioned in the initial report of 1974.

Name: Grand Bassin D
Hull remains: One of the lastest dated ships to be sheathed in lead.

Name: Le Grand Ribaud D
Reference: S. Marlier, Archaeonautica 15 (2008), 154-5
Hull remains: Fragments

Name: Le Grand Rouveau
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Le Grand Souffre
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 49
Comments: A looted site of a shipwreck of Dr 1B amphorae
Hull remains: A few fragments of wood and a small piece of lead sheathing
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarseware fragments

Name: Grebeni
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000) no. 14
Comments: A cargo of tegulae sherds were found scattered around the reef
Other cargo: A cargo of tegulae.

Name: Guardias Viejas
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 190 no. 3
Comments: "fin du Ier siecle"

Name: Gusteranski
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000) no. 17
Comments: A heavily looted cargo of amphorae and Pompeian red ware.
Other cargo: South Italian Pompeian ware consisting of 'orlo bifido' bowls, with plates/lids and standard Pompeian red plates, which were only 15% of the total of 50 brought to the surface.

Name: Heliopolis A
Reference: J.-P. Joncheray,  Bilan Scientifique 1992, 51; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 13 (1997), 137-164; M. Bonifay et al, in L. Rivet and M. Sciallano (eds). Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 195-196.
Comments: A small ship holding an estimated capacity of only 720 amphorae, most of which had already disappeared by the time this site was properly excavated.
Hull remains: One of the latest dated ships to be sheathed in lead although not much remains. Some nails. Probable length of 14m.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarseware, a copper dish, fragments of lead.

Name: Heliopolis B
Reference: J.-P. Joncheray and L. Long, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 14 (2002), 131-160

Name: Herculaneum I
Comments:
Sailed.
Lat 40 N 45, Long 14 E 30

Name: Ile Rousse
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Ilovik
Region: between Sv. Petar isl and Kozjak island
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 19; M. Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A cargo of North Italian amphorae which probably numbered over 1700 originally, before the site was looted.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Three North Italian lamps, a red Pompeian plate, an ESB Hayes 80 plate, 3 ESW specimens, a few North Italian(?) glass vessels, south italian (?) bronze service patera-jug and a sestertius of Trajan.

Name: Isis
Reference: A. McCann and J. Freed, Deep Water Archaeology; a Late-Roman Ship from Carthage and an Ancient Trade Route Near Skerki Bank off Northwest Sicily (1994)
Comments: The site covered an area 11.5 x 9.5m and was  mapped, photographed and excavated by new robotic technology, JASON, in the late 1980s-1990s. 48 objects were documented. The ship's main cargo may have been organic such as North African wheat as grains of wheat and barley were found in one of the iron anchor concretions.
Other cargo: Common ware pottery, mostly Tunisian, datable to c AD 400, some are unique in style. A basalt millstone from Libya with a concave hopper and protruding handles is an previoulsy unknown form.
Hull remains: A small (12-15m x 5m ) typical Late Roman mortise and tenon conctruction ship with pine planking, oak, pear and possibly Mediterranean cedar decking and oak tenons. The ship was not elad sheathed but lead patching can be seen suggesting this was an old vessel.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A bronze coin dating to least years of Constantius II (AD 355-361), found in a pot of pine tar used for daily repairs, gives a terminus post quem for the earliest possible date of the wreck. A North African red-slip ware lamp from Carthage, datable to c AD 375-425, supports this date.
Ship equipment: 4 iron anchors

Name: Pakleni Cape
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 52
Comments: A probable shipwreck from a much looted site of amphorae.

Name: Kepec (Kepce Burnu)
Reference: E. Greene et al, INA Annual 2008, 65-70
Comments: A scattered wreck of Cypro-Levantine basket-handle amphorae discovered in the 1970s and re-examined recently by INA.

Name: Krava
Reference: N. Cambi in Amphores Romains et Histoire Economique, Dix Ans de Rechereches (Siena, 1986) 1989, 323-5; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: The earliest known wreck in the Adriatic
Other cargo: Grindstones and handmills

Name: Ladispoli A
Reference: M-B Carre, 'L'epave a dolia de Ladispoli' in Archaeonautica 11 (1993), 9-31; D. Gibbins, 'More underwater finds of Roman medical eqipment', Antiquity 71, no. 272 (1997), 457-9.
Comments: The wreck site covers an area of 400 sq m. The ship may have been adapted specially to hold dolia.
Other cargo: A wooden head of a duck as decoration for a kline.
Hull remains: 6.6 x 3.3 m of the hull were preserved, including parts of the keel, frames and shell. The mid-section of the ship seems to have been reinforced. 12 wooden discs thought to be part of the pump. An 'anneau de cargue' which is very rare, cf Chretienne C. Estimated total length of the ship is 18m.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A doctor's bag containing a small wooden box 12.4 x 8 8cm with a sliding lid and bronze lock containing phials of coriander and cumin. Also 2 Italian red-slip plates suitable for mixing potions, 1 inscribed L. APPV (LEIVS) preceded by the verb MEDEOR (to cure or administer)

Name: Lastovo A (Mali Brod)
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192

Name: Lastovo B (Saplun)
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A complete cargo of 150 amphorae
Shipboard paraphernalia: A loutherion

Name: Les Laurons B
Reference: S. Ximenes and M. Moerman, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 10 (1991), 210-222; P. Pomey, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 35; M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Comments: NB Date change, much nearer to Les Laurons III and IV.
Other cargo: Wheat - grains were preserved in pitch
Hull remains: Well preserved sections
Shipboard paraphernalia: Basket lid; cermamics - 2 oil lamps, pitchers, ollae etc. Three coins, one of Marcus Aurelius, one that was stuck in pitch was a follis from the C3rd AD and the other unidentifiable.
Ship equipment: A buckthorn toggle.

Name: Lavezzi A (1)
Reference: B. Liou, Archaeonutica 10 (1990), 125- 155
Other cargo: At least 7 lead ingots and 18 copper ingots.

Name: Lazzaretto A
Reference: http://members.xoom.it/crasa/lazzaa.htm

Name: Lido di Sant'Anna
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 183, area 6
Comments: A remarkable quantity of amphorae fragments atached to an esplanade of stone and sandstone blocks.
Ship equipment: A T-shaped object, probably an anchor

Name: La Luque A
Hull remains: Two coins dated to the reign of Hadrian were found in the mast-step

Name: La Luque B
Other cargo: 250 oil lamps

Name: Ma'agan Mikha'el
Reference: Archaeonautica 14, 1998          Y. Kahanov and E. Linder, The Ma'agan Mikhael Ship. The Recovery of a 2400-year-old Merchantman. Final Report Volume I (2003) and Volume II (2004)        http://mushecht.haifa.ac.il/hecht/archeology/maagan_ship_eng.aspx              Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 50-55          R.R. Steiglitz, AJA 110 (2006), 195-203          M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Comments: Unusually good preservation of rope and other organic materials. The ship was approximately 13.5m long and 4 m wide and seems to have been new when it sank. The hull of the ship was dismantled underwater and the timbers conserved at the University of Haifa where it has now been re-assembled.
Other cargo: Seventy Cypriot and East Greek clay vessels, including a pithos, basket-handled jars, oil lamps, small jugs,mortaria and a cooking pot. 12 tons of rocks, mainly blueschist from Euboea, as well as some magmatic from southern Cyprus.
Hull remains: Much has been preserved in excellent condition, including the complete keel and the mast-step. Shell-first construction with moritse and tenon joints and some sewn sections. The keel was made of a single pine timber, 8.26m long. Adze, saw and chisel marks are clearly visible, and along with wood shavings found inside the ship, point to new construction.The ship resembles the Kyrenia ship in some respects and the Bon-Porte and Gela ships in others; it was probably built in NW Turkey.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Remains of food
Ship equipment: Rigging (including  3 wooden bobbin toggles), shipwright's tools and a one-armed wooden anchor with ropes still attached. The two instruments found on the shipwreck are the earliest preserved classical Greek measuring tools. The two units represented on the rule are identified as a Pheidonian and a Solonian foot, whose ratio may be correlated precisely to a statement by Aristotle about the metrological reform of Solon. The square used a shorter unit, identical to a measure known from Hellenistic and Roman times as the Italic foot, whose length was five-sixths of a Pheidonian foot. The notched subdivisions on the square suggest its originating standard was perhaps an archaic Greek foot, or 3 ft. multiple—a yard—first mentioned by Hesiod. The three standards represented on the shipwrecked tools indicate that Greek architects of the fifth century B.C.E. used multiple linear measures, traceable to diverse sources.

Name: La Madonnina
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 196, area 10
Other cargo: Courseware pottery.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Various objects.
Ship equipment: Two stone anchors

Name: La Madrague de Giens
Hull remains: A bronze as, dated to c 187-155 BC,  was found in the mast-step.

Name: Mal di Ventre
Reference: D. Salvi, Bollettino di Archeologia 1992, 237-248C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, (2002),  460; Salvi, 1992; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 89-95.
Comments: A large merchant ship, estimated at 30m x 9m, carrying a cargo mainly of lead ingots, the biggest haul found so far.
Other cargo: 1100 Spanish lead ingots mined from Cartagena, each weighing about 100 Roman pounds and inscribed on theupper side with the manufacturer's mark. One was SOCMPONTILIENORUMMAE, ie Societas Marci et Caio Pontilienorum figli di Marco. The other LCARULILFHISPALIMN, ie. Luci Caruli Luci fili Hispali MeNenia tribu.
Hull remains: The keel seems to have been strengthened with bronze nails to support the enormous weight of its cargo (cf Capo Testa wreck).
Shipboard paraphernalia: Dressel 1 amphorae and coarseware pottery. A millstone
Ship equipment: Three lead and wood anchors, 2 lead sounding weights.

Name: Malamocco
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 175-77

Name: Marsala (Punic Ship)
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 113-116

Name: Marsala A
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 116; M. Bonino, Archaeologia Mediterranea maritima 2007, 179-190
Hull remains: The remains show the early development of the skeleton building technique on a ship that measured 15.5m x 4.5m

Name: Marsala B
Reference: A.M. Ferroni and C. Meucci, Bollettino di archeologia subacquea 1996, 283-333; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 116
Comments: A 9m long wreck

Name: Marzamemi B
Other cargo: A cargo of pre-fabricated marble architectural pieces from a Byzantine church, including 28 bases and 27 capitals of Proconnesian marble, and an 'ambo' with 2 staircases from which a priest would deliver sermons.

Name: Mateille A
Other cargo: A bronze consignment of female statue fragments, animal terminals for furniture, boar's tusk decoration, pendants, dishes and pots.

Name: Le Miladou
Reference: M. Dumontier and J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 10 (1991), 109-174.
Comments: A small ship, 15m long, carrying a single layer of about 250 Italian amphorae that have spread over an area 35m sq..
Hull remains: Nine metres of poorly preserved remains show a classic construction. The keel was made of pine while many species of wood were used for the frames and planks including fig!
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock weighing 82kg. Two lead pipes, 1.6m and 1.49m long.

Name: Mljet A
Reference: V.Han and Z. Brusic in Annales du 7ieme congres internationale pour l'histoire du verre, Berlin-Leipzig 15-21 Aout 1977 (1978), 271-82
Comments: A primary cargo of Byzantine amphorae and a secondary one of Islamic glass, possibly from Syria cf composition of cargo from Serce Limani wreck

Name: Minorca
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0303.htm#minorca
Comments: Discovered in 2000, only a summary report has been given about this Roman wreck of bronze ingots.
Other cargo: Bronze ingots weighing 80kg each, still arranged in rows.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Some amphorae, presumably too few to be cargo.
Ship equipment: An anchor.

Name: Montecristo F
Comments: NB Date change since Parker. The site had been heavily looted before excavation.
Hull remains: Still buried in the sand
Shipboard paraphernalia: An intact jug, part of another and a piece of roofing tile.

Name: Nerezine
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 48
Comments: Probably a shipwreck with a cargo of unidentified pottery and Eastern coarseware.
Other cargo: Eastern coarseware.

Name: Palombina Vecchia
Reference: Mercando 1983, Toniolo 1991, Beltrame 'Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana' 2002, 457
Hull remains: Possibly in a good condition under a thick layer of sand.

Name: La Palud 1
Reference: L. Long and G. Volpe, Bilan Scientifique 1993, 46-47; Bilan Scientifique 1994, 48; Bilan Scientifique 1995, 53;  in M. Bonifay (ed.) Fouilles a Marseille. Les mobiliers (Ier- VII siecles ap. J.-C.), (1998), 317-42S; M. Bonifay et al, in L. Rivet and M. Sciallano (eds). Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 198-199; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Perpilus, 2004), 41.
Comments: An 18,000 litre cargo of North African and Eastern wine amphorae covering 60-80 sq m.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A unique find was a rectangular wooden box that once held secure round round copper or bronze weights from a merchant's balance. The designs of the weights are still preserved in the soft grain of the wood, so that a Byzantine emperor (of the period AD 527-28) staring out of the box is all that remains of the weights today. Fragments of African sigillata Hayes type 99 and 103B, as well as Late Roman C ware, type Hayes 3E.

Name: Pampelonne
Reference: M. Bonifay et al, in L. Rivet and M. Sciallano (eds). Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 196-97
Comments: A principal cargo of African amphorae of which 46 were brought to the surface. NB Date change since Parker

Name: Pantano Longarini
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 75; S. Kampbell, INA Quarterly 34 , 20-22
Comments: A large merchant ship of more that 200-300 tonne capacity, between 30 and 40m long. It must have been heavily laden as it snapped in two.
Hull remains: The upper section of the stern with oak frames and cypress wood planking was preserved. The surviving 9.1m starboad side shows unusally heavy framing and a rough finish with iron fastenings throughout. The cypress planks and pistachio wood tenons used below the water line suggest the ship was constructed in , Sicily, Greece or southern Italy.

Name: Perduto
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Le Petit Congloue
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Plane A
Hull remains: The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Jeaume Garde B, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).

Name: Plane C
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2001, 60; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 105.
Comments: This Islamic ship was carrying only 200-300 trade items
Hull remains: Some remains.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A small number of pottery items.
Ship equipment: Anchors.

Name: Planier A
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Planier C
Comments: Dating refined according to Tchernia 1990.

Name: Plavac A
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 56; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: An eastern cargo of amphorae in a fairly well preserved wreck.
Hull remains: Quite well preserved
Shipboard paraphernalia: ECW mugs, profiled plates, dishes with lids and trefoil mouth jugs; cups and 2-handled saucers from Pergamom, Arretine Conspectus R2 form, a TS plate with the stamp TETTI and parts of 2 oil lamps.
Ship equipment: Two iron anchors, the lead parts of a bilge pump, the remains of a pulley and a lead sounding weight.

Name: Plemmirio A
Other cargo: Bronze lamps, censers, pitchers, bowls and a steelyard.

Name: Plemmirio B
Reference: D. Gibbins, Antiquity 71 no.272 (1997) and World Archaeology 32 (2001), 311-334
Comments: A cargo of North African amphorae which had been looted before excavation
Hull remains: Fragments of timber. The ship probably only measured 12-18m in length.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Surgeon's instruments including a wooden bandaging stick, 3 copper alloy scalpel handles, 2 with long slender dissectors suitable for opthalmic surgery, the 3rd was attached to a corroded iron instrument which may have been a solid cataract needle or cautery. Tiles and bricks from the galley's roof and hearth; at least 22 different items of table and kitchen pottery; 4 oil lamps; 2 glass vessels. fishing weights. Several individual amphorae
Ship equipment: A sounding lead, one of the few to date later than the early Imperial period; ferrous concretions of anchors

Name: Plocice
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 58
Comments: A cargo of roof tiles.
Other cargo: A cargo of roof tiles.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock.

Name: Pointe Debie A
Reference: B. Dangreaux, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 44
Comments: This is no longer considered to be a wreck site, rather a deposit of various amphorae, since Dr 7-11 and Beltran 2B cannot chronologically have been cargo in the same ship.

Name: Ponza Porto
Reference: http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/galliuk.htm
Hull remains: The wreck was orientated north-west, at 315°; despite the damage it had suffered in places, it was of striking mass and dimensions, with planking assembled by mortise-and-tenon joints. The frames, of which 27 were found, are on average 210 mm. thick (moulded) and 190 mm. broad (sided). The strakes are, on average, 60 mm. thick and 210 mm. broad (see the report of A.S.S.O. for the Archaeological Superintendency of Latium)

Name: Port-Miou (Port Miou B)
Reference: C. Dovis, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 46
Comments: A late C4th to early C5th AD wreck with a cargo of African amphorae and ceramics.
Other cargo: Sigillata D or African redslip, Hayes 81 B and 67 B 33

Name: Port Vendres A
Reference: M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252v

Hull remains: A bronze coin of Constantine was found in the mast-step.
Ship equipment: Different kinds of wooden toggles

Name: Port Vendres C/ 3
Reference: M. Jezegou, Bilan Scientifique 2005, 41

Name: Port Vendres D
Dating: end C1st BC- beg C1st AD
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369; M. Jezegou, Bilan Scientifique 2005, 42

Marble type: Five unfinished sheets of Luna marble.
Hull remains: Incomplete fragments of strakes and planking.
Ship equipment: Various fittings including part of the bilge pump

Name: Porticello
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 39, area 17                 C. Eiseman and B. Ridgway, The Porticello Wreck (1987); M. Lawall, IJNA 27 (1998) 16-23; M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Comments: A much looted ship measuring about 16.6m long with a cargo of mixed amphorae from the northern Aegean and the western Mediterranean, and an array of bronze sculpture.
Other cargo: At least two dozen lead ingots, looted, only 2 have been excavated that are stamped, probably from Laurion. Eight small clay inkpots. Bronze sculpture: a superb male bearded  head, approximately life size, cast in 2 sections; a fragment of right leg and buttock with drapery; a large fragment of drapery; a left hand; the rear protion of a left foot; right foot and leg; genitals; left buttock and thigh; right buttock and upper thigh; other miscellaneous fragments - in total, probably at least one draped male and two undraped males.
Hull remains: Few fragments of the hull survive. Several dozen copper nails, round-headed and square shafted. Lead patches.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Lamps, oinochoe, Attic black glaze pottery, coarse ware, mortar, whetstones, a wooden bowl, an awl and a sheep or goat bone. Four fragmentary black-glaze bolsals. Metal objects include lead fishing weights and cake ingots and lead and silver nuggets (currency??)
Ship equipment: Several anchors : a wooden shank, wooden arms with bronze teeth and a wooden stock with lead cores. Other lead anchors may have been looted prior to excavation. A wooden bobbin toggle, with rigging, attaching lines to clews and luffs.

Name: Povile
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192

Name: Procchio
Comments: This wreck discovered in the late 1960s has been recently subjected to a project of protection to ensure its future preservation against the strong local currents.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A larchwood box containing 10kg of huntile, probably originally magnesium.

Name: Punta Ala A

Name: Punta Braccetto

Name: Punta Licosa 1
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html       site 51, area 22                 C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 459
Comments: Excavation and recovery 1990-1995 of the cargo of amphorae.

Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock and a piece of lead tubing, probably part of the bilge pump.

Name: Punta Scaletta
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 50-51
Comments: A  fragmented wreck with a heterogenous cargo
Ship equipment: Seven anchors, 3 iron and 4 wooden and lead

Name: Las Puntas
Reference: Etienne & Mayer 2004, 214 no. 4
Comments: Flavian

Name: La Roche Fouras
Hull remains: The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3,  Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).

Name: Roches d'Aurelle
Comments: A cargo of tiles, amphorae and ceramics.
Other cargo: Tegulae and imbrices from Frejus, cf Bartelemy B and Dramont G wrecks.

Name: Saint Gervais B (2)
Reference: M.-P. Jezegou, Archaeonuatica 4, 1984; M.-P. Jezegou in M. Bonifay (ed.) Fouilles a Marseille. Les mobiliers (1er-VIIe siecles ap. J.-C.) (1998), 343-52; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004),  111, 128-9.
Comments: The only wreck so far discovered in which wheat and a wooden barrel have been preserved.
Other cargo: Wheat - a layer of pitch spilt from the amphorae glued  this rich archaeological layer of organic material  in position in the back one third of the ship.
Hull remains: 9.5m x 4.5m of the hull was well preserved underneath a layer of sand, showing even less reliance on mortise and tenon construction than the contemporary Yassi Ada wreck. Poor design can be seen where frames didn't fit and small pieces of wedged wood were used to fill the gaps.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A half-follis coin dating to the reign of Heraclius (AD 611-612). A wooden barrel, the only one ever found on a Late Antique wreck, measuring 32cm in diameter and 70cm long with a 120l capacity. North African bowls (Hayes 108 and 109) and lamps, a Palestinian amphora. Coins dated to the time of Heraclius of Carthage AD 611-612 although the wreck is of a later date.
Ship equipment: A wooden chain pump housing (55cm x 18cm, pierced vertically with 2 cylindrical cavities) was preserved in the layer of pitch.

Name: Saint Gervais C
Reference: B. Liou and J-M Gassend, Archaeonautica 10 (1990), 157-264
Comments: Liou's dating puts this wreck in the middle of the C1st AD
Other cargo: 11 glass ungentaria, 10 of which were found in a basket; an ESA plate;
Hull remains: 14.7m x 6.8m of the hull was preserved.
Shipboard paraphernalia: 3 copper cauldrons

Name: Saint Honorat
Comments: Cargo composed entirely of Dr  20. Cargo looted
Hull remains: None.

Name: Salakta

Name: San Nicola
Reference: Etienne & Mayer 198 no. 48

Name: Santa Caterina di Nardo

Name: Scole A, Le

Name: Scopello

Name: Secca dei Mattoni
Reference: G. Galli, Archeologia Subacquea. Studi, ricerche e documenti 1 (1993), 117-129                                                                              http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/ukartsec.htm
Other cargo: Ceramics mainly consist of cups of the Morel 2323 and 1222 type, Lamboglia 3 vases and ciboria (Morel 7450 and 7550 types), other forms such as the Lamboglia 5 (low bowls without handles) small Lamboglia 10 urns and two spindle-shaped ointment jars.

Name: Secca di Capistello
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 123; M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252
Ship equipment: Wooden toggle.

Name: Serçe Limani A
Reference: G. Bass et al, Serce Limani, Vol I: the ship and its anchorage, crew and the passengers (2004); G. Bass et al, Serce Limani, Vol II: the glass of an eleventh-century shipwreck (2009)
Comments: The well-dated and undisturbed nature of this cargo makes this an extremely important find for Islamic glass studies.
Other cargo: Two tons of raw glass and one ton (between half a million and a million sherds) of broken glass (broken prior to loading on board and possibly stored in baskets as they were found in clumps) as well as 80 intact glass vessels were found. The number of vessels present may have been as high as 10-20,000., They include cups, plates, dishes, bowls, bottles, ewers, jugs, jars, lamps, cupping glasses, alembics and stemmed vessels, all of an Islamic origin.
Hull remains: Skeleton-first construction, now reconstructed in the Bodrum Museum
Shipboard paraphernalia: Carpenter's tools including a caulking set; 4 padlocks; faunal remains indicating the crew's diet and season of sailing (early autumn).
Ship equipment: Nine anchors

Name: Skoljic
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 75 and  in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Shipboard paraphernalia: One Forlimpopuli C. 1 Dr 2-4 and 1 mini Dr 2-4 amphorae; an atypically large Drag. 24/25 terra sigillata with the stamp EDIAT, probably N Italian and an Italian lamp Loeschke Vib.

Name: Sobra
Comments: The ship had an estimated length of 25m and was one of the latest yet found to be lead sheathed.
Hull remains: One of the latest dated ships to be sheathed in lead.
Shipboard paraphernalia: North African pottery points to Tunisian merchants managing the shipment.

Name: Les Sorres C
Comments: Dolia

Name: Stori Stoni (Stari Stani)
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A fairly intact cargo of more than 100 (possibly empty?) amphorae plus remains of the ship.

Name: Sud-Lavezzi B (2)
Reference: Etienne & Mayer 196 no. 37; B. Liou and C. Domergue, Archaeonautica 10 (1990), 11-124.
Comments: A diverse wreck of Baetican amphorae and ingots (cf Port Vendres 2), unfortunately too pillaged to know the total amount of the cargo.
Other cargo: 95  lead ingots arranged in 11 rows all bearing the the mould-mark MINVCIORVM and the counter stamp AP.IVN and ZETH and graffiti indicating their weight (51-54kg). 237 circular copper ingots were stacked in piles fore and aft of the lead (20kg), bearing 20 different inscriptions, but most commonly Q. C. ANTO.19 pieces of  Arretine pottery from 8 different objects - 1 small cup stamped with CERES[IM] / P CORNE , Chresimus was one of 30 slaves known to have belonged to P. Cornelius of Arezzo. Other small fragments of fineware and some coarseware.
Hull remains: Broken up except where protected by the ingots but at least 23.8m preserved.
Ship equipment: One sounding lead weighing 8 kilos. 9 anchors, 6 of iron and 3 lead stocks, weighing between 200 and 250kgs inscribed AP.SE found forward of the ship.

Name: Sud-Lavezzi C (3)
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Sud-Perduto A
Reference: Bilan Scientifique  2005, 94
Comments: Originally seen as a mound of amphorae 2m high in 1980, the site is now spread out  measuring 25 x 15m.

Name: Sveti Andrija (Svetac island)
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 70; M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A much looted wreck of western Mediterranean amphorae

Name: Tiboulen de Maire 1
Reference: S. Ximenes and M. Moerman, Bilan Scientifique 1999, 48; Bilan Scientifique 2000, 62; 2001, 59; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 6; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 81; Bilan Scientifique 2004, 72; Bilan Scientifique 2005. 75.
Comments: A cargo of Spanish and Gauloise amphorae from a ship measuring about 30m. NB Date change since Parker.
Hull remains: At least 2.1m x 1.35m is preserved with part of the keel and 6 frames. The ship is estimated to have been 30 m long and 12m wide.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Pottery including jugs, amphorettes and an oil lamp.

Name: Le Titan
Hull remains: A semi-uncial bronze as was found in the mast-step.

Name: Torre Guaceto
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html        site 184, area 6
Comments: Numerous fragments of  amphorae, mainly unidentified due to erosion.
Ship equipment: Large worn stones, probably ballast.

Name: Torre Santa Sabina 1
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana (2002), 457

Name: Tour d'Agnello 1

Hull remains: Bronze nails.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock and a small iron anchor

Name: La Tour Fondue
Reference: B. Dangreaux, Bilan Scientifique 1993, 44-45; Bilan Scientifique 1994, 47; Bilan Scientifique 1995, 51-52; Bilan Scientifique 1996, 89-90; Bilan Scientifique 1997, 57-59

Other cargo: Massiliot ceramics - cups and millstones.
Hull remains: Built with oak and pine, sections survive that show that the ship was partially constructed with ligatures as well as by moritse and tenon cf Cavaliere wreck.
Ship equipment: An anchor, 4kg of ballast stones

Name: Tre Senghe
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html           area 1 site 8
Comments: Shipwreck A of the Tre Senghe (shipwreck B = Punta del Diavolo).

Name: Los Ullastres
Dating: end C1st BC - beg C1st AD
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369

Name: Ulu Burun
Reference: R. Payton, Anatolian Studies 41 (1991), 99-106; P. Warnock and M. Pendleton, Anatolian Studies 41 (1991), 107-110; C. Haldane, World Archaeology 24 (1993) 348-360;  INA Quarterly 21.4 (1994); M.-H. Gates, AJA 100 ( 1996), 304-306; C. Pulak, IJNA 27 (1998), 188-224; C. Bachhuber, AJA 110 (2006), 345-363
Comments: An 11 year excavation was undertaken by the INA of this Late Bronze Age merchant ship. Its cargo was amazingly varied, luxurious and was worth a considerable fortune. It has thus been suggested that the ship may have been on a diplomatic voyage carrying palatial gifts.
Other cargo: Ten tons of Cypriot copper ingots (354 oxhide ingots and 121 smaller bun- and pillow-shaped ingots). Nearly a ton of tin ingots. Raw ivory (elephant tusk and hippo teeth!) and ivory carvings, a gold goblet, ebony, glass ingots and an assortment of gold jewellery. Huge amount of organic material including fruits, nuts, spices and other plants  . Bronze tools and weapons Cypriot pottery
Shipboard paraphernalia: Cooking ware, tools, weapons and over 130 pan-balance weights (2 pans were found in a wooden case); saucer lamps, cylinder seals; amber beads and at least 200 flattened blue faience beads. A pair of  intricate wooden (boxwood) writing-boards set with ivory hinges from the Near East.
Ship equipment: 24 anchors

Name: Yassi Ada A
Reference: P. Van Alfen, JRA 9 (1996), 189-213; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 45-52; http://ina.tamu.edu/yasymposium/PDFs/Van%20Doorninck2.pdf
Comments: A well preserved 21m ship carrying 3 rows of about 900 amphorae. The ship can be dated from 16 gold coins and 50 copper coins to AD 626, as all but one gold coin were issues of the Emperor Heraclius. The ship may have belonged to the Church and was transporting low-grade wine intended for Byzantine troops. The ship, with a  slim 4:1 length to width ratio, sharp bow and full stern was designed for speed and carried a lateen sail. At the stern was a large galley complex, well equipped to serve food and drink to quite a number of passnegers.
Hull remains: Well preserved. A fairly weak construction of widely spaced, small and unpeggedd mortise and tenon joints only up to the waterline; above that hull planking was fixed to already erected framing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: At least 40 iron carpentry tools, numerous cooking wares and copper containers, coins, fishing equipment and 16 oil lamps. 8 bronze weights (and 1 of glass) and at least 3 steelyards, the largest of which is 1.46m long and decorated at one end with a boar's head terminal. Its sculptural counterweight was a bust of the goddess Athena. A bronze censer and cross.
Ship equipment: 11 iron anchors with straight arms set perpendicular to the shank, a cruciform anchor design used from the C4th-10th AD. Three of the anchors weighed 78.75kg, another one 110.25kg and another three were sheet anchors weighing 141.75kg.

Name: Yassi Ada B
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 51.
Comments: A 19m long by 8m wide ship carrying 1,100 probably Aegean amphorae some of which are now displayed in the Bodrum Museum.
Hull remains: The port side of the hull was well preserved up to the waterline. Mostly cypress wood but with a keel of white oak, with a shell-first construction. Mortise and tenon joints were used but are small and widely spaced and more easily assembled than they normally were in Roman hulls.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A spacious galley set down in the stern had a rough-stone firebox. At least 6 pantry jars, a funnel, 4 cooking pots, 11 pitchers, a cup, a bowl, 2 large plates, a smaller dish, 5 glass vessels, a copper jug, possibly 3 steelyards, some copper coins, a casting net and 4 lamps, 1 signed KY from an Athenian workshop.

Name: Zaton A
Ship equipment: A number of roughly shaped wooden toggles

Name: Zaton B
Ship equipment: A number of roughly shaped wooden toggles

Name: Arles IV
Reference: http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/archeosm/fr/fr-medit-antiq.htm             Pomey et al 1992; L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1993, 30-31; Long 1997, p. 79-82
Comments: The site measures 30 m by 10m and was investigated in the early 1990s by submarine, 74km from the mouth of the Rhone. The cargo comprised several layers of amphorae, possibly 1000-2000 in total, of 3 different types - a large group holding fish sauce in the middle, surrounded by oil amphorae with small, flat-bottomed amphorae at each end.
Other cargo: Pottery and copper ingots.
Hull remains: Probably in good condition under the cargo of amphorae
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock and  an iron anchor.

Name: Cavaliere (medieval)
Reference: http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/archeosm/fr/fr-medit-moyen.htm

Name: Culip II
Comments: Nieto says Roman in Culip VIII

Name: Culip VII
Comments: Nieto says Roman in Culip VIII
