Name: Cala Piomba
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 198-9.no. 50        http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: A cargo of amphorae spread over an area 50 x30m.
Other cargo: Two lead ingots of trapezoidal shape

Name: Cabo de Gata
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2004, 214 no. 7

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer 2
Reference: L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1995, 40-41; Bilan Scientifique 1996, 73; Bilan Scientifique 1997, 65-68; Liou 2000, 1070 no. 39; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 65; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 49.
Comments: A cargo of iron ingots and bars seen as a number of concretions over a 15m long site.
Other cargo: Iron ingots and 146 bars some of which are very well preserved with stamps EROTIS and LEPIDI, plus symbols of anchors and other unidentifiable oval shapes. Some measure as long as 123cm and weigh 6.5kg. The total number may have been as high as 3000 to 4000.
Hull remains: Partially preserved under the concretions along with some branches of grapevines used as protection for the cargo, the ship is estimated to have been 15-20m long.

Name: Esteu dou Mieu 2
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2004, 220 no. 36

Name: Anse de Montfort
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2000, 241 no. 22

Name: Mounine 2
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2000, 241 no. 23

Name: Els Reis
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2000, 239 no. 9

Name: Callela I
Reference: Etienne & Mayet 2000, 242 no. 28

Name: La Giraglia
Reference: M. Sciallano, Bilan Scientifique 1995, 60; Bilan Scientifique 1997, 81; Bilan Scientifique 1998, 56; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 70-72; Etienne & Mayet 2000, 245 no. 44; S. Marlier and P. Sibella, IJNA 31 (2002), 161-171; M Sciallano and S. Marlier, Archaeonautica 15 (2008), 113-152.
Comments: Discovered in 1992, spread over 200m sq, a  cargo of dolia and amphorae, very badly wrecked probably due to the dolia rolling out of place as the ship sank. A very similar cargo to that of Chretienne H.
Other cargo: Six fragments of Aretine ware, one with a stampTHALI. Four fragments of blue-green glass from 2 plates and 2 cups.
Hull remains: 7m long by 2m wide, 26 frames but no trace of the keel. The ship was probably about 20m long and was of classic hull first construction, built from oak, elm and beech, ash and fir.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two miniscule fragments of oil lamps, some fineware fragments, 5 nuts and 8 noisettes; several Gauloise 4 or 5 fragments.
Ship equipment: Pump remains, lead anchor stock

Name: Calaminnola
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0407.htm#egadi
Comments: A cargo of amphorae which will be left on the sea bed and viewed by video from a museum in Favignana.

Name: Albenga II
Reference: Abysso blu - http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksLI045.htm
Comments: Discovered in 2003 by carabinieri divers, the wreck site measures approximately 20m x 10m. The ship could carry about 3000 amphorae (about 150 tons). Just a few amphorae of the cargo have been stolen by souvenir hunters.

Name: Les Sorres VIII
Reference: http://www.abc.se/~pa/publ/sorr-helm.htm (REMESAL, J. & MUSO, O.: "La presencia de material etrusco en la Península Ibérica", Barcelona, (1990) 1991, p. 601-614. Published March 2000 on Nordic Underwater Archaeology)
Comments: Republican/Etruscan helmets; ?Greco-Italic amphorae.

Name: Pisa A
Reference:
S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674 ; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                                http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_naveA.htm   
http://www.archaeology.org/9907/etc/shipa.html
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa.
Hull remains: Unfortunately split into 2 during the construction works, this ship is estimated to have been 30m in length
Shipboard paraphernalia: Ceramics including African terra sigillata.

Name: Pisa B
Reference:
S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                           http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_naveB_carico.htm
http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/rosso2.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. A transport ship of medium dimensions, recovered tilted on its side. Adriatic and Baetican amphorae had been reused to carry fruit, nuts and salted fish as well as augitic sand of Latium or Campania origin. It is still uncertain what the real purpose was of such sand. The skeletons of a 40-45 year-old man and a dog were also found.
Hull remains: Enough remains were preserved to show that the ship was 4m wide.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones, formed from rounded off blocks of various sizes, from Campania; stowage material found between the amphorae from the Neapolitan area.

Name: Pisa C
Reference:
S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                            http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_naveC_nave.htm
http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/rosso2.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This large fluvial boat, 14m long, has been recovered moored to a pole with a large cable: the boat is still in an optimal state of conservation
Hull remains: The majority of the structural elements are intact (keel, keelson, frame, mast partners and step, top of bulwarks, prow bollards and six rowing benches set at regular intervals). All around, in correspondence to the benches, are conserved the holes for the oars, into which are series of small nails in order to fix the leather. White and red paint can still be seen on the external planks above the waterline. A Greek inscription, ALKDO, can be read on the 1st rowing bench.

Name: Pisa D
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                   http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_naveD.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This is the draft of a large river boat, 14m long and 6m wide.  It has been recovered turned upside down and quite completely lacking its hull; some parts, like the keel, were perhaps cut off in ancient time.
Hull remains: Some structures of this upside down river boat survive.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones.

Name: Pisa E
Reference:
S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000); G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); H. Neilson, IJNA 31 (2002), 248-253;  M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                                   http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_naveE.htm
http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/rosso2.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This ship is lying on its side and had been transporting dolia and Dr 2-4 amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A terracotta phallus which suggests that the Priapus deity was seen as an icon of maritime activity as well as a garden fertility god.
Ship equipment: A large wooden anchor.

Name: Pisa F
Reference:
S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                            http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_barcaF.htm
http://www.mclink.it/assoc/assonet/arcart/rosso2.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This is a 9m long river boat.
Hull remains: A slim fluvial 9m long and only 1m wide, a 'lintres' type of Roman ship. Made of oak and small alder sections.

Name: Pisa P
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                  http://www.navipisa.it/scavo_barcaP.htm
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This is a flat-bottomed boat comparable to Pisa G.
Hull remains: Flat bottomed boat only partially excavated.

Name: Pisa G
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This is a flat-bottomed barge probably originally 9m long.
Hull remains: A flat-bottomed barge of which only the prow has been excavated so far.

Name: Pisa H
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This is a fluvial punt.
Hull remains: A small fluvial punt.

Name: Pisa I
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. This river boat was carrying African amphorae, presumably unloading them from a much larger ship.
Hull remains: A river boat 12m x 2.5m, Roman 'lintres' type. Mortise and tenon construction with iron nails.

Name: Marsa -El-Brega Byzantine
Reference: C. Preece, Libyan Studies 31 (2000), 29-56.
Comments: One of two ancient wrecks probably caused by human error in an area particularly difficult to navigate.
Other cargo: Fineware - Hayes Late Roman C, Form 3, Type H - cooking pots and a sherd of African redslip ware

Name: Point Iria
Reference: http://www2.rgzm.de/navis/cargo/Iria/Iria.htm            Master Seafarers: The Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 105-111.
Comments: Cypriotic origin, dated to ca 1200 BC, lying on 12-27 m depth. Transporting Cypriotic pottery. The ship was probably less than 10 m long. Investigated by the Hellenic Institute of Marine Archaeology in 1991-1995.
Other cargo: 25 pieces of Mycenaean and Cypriot pottery, and Cretan transport jars. "Cypriot pithoi and LH/LM IIIB 2 pithoid jars) and medium size ones (Cretan stirrup-jars, Cypriot jugs and an amphora with incised linear signs)."  "a few decorated Mycenaean vases in fine ware (a deep bowl krater and one or two deep bowls)"
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Cypriot heavy broad-based water jug (jug A20 or the 'Tsouchlos jug').

Name: Antidragonera
Reference: http://www.culture.gr/2/21/215/21502/e21503.html       Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 128-129.
Comments: The shipwreck has been excavated since 1993 under the direction of Dr. Dimitris Kourkoumelis. Finds to date include 9 large stone anchors, a few amphorae and at least two storage pithoi, probably belonging to the crew. The bulk of the cargo was probably perishable.
Hull remains: A few bronze nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: 2 storage pithoi, plates, lamps, lekanides, pitchers, mortars, bowls etc.
Ship equipment: 9 large pyramid shaped stone anchors, similar to those found in Zea port in Piraeus and the 4th-c. BC wrecks of La Madonnina in the Bay of Taranto, and Ognina 4 in Sicily. The first group lay at the head of the bay on the north side of the islet, at a fairly shallow depth of 9 meters, and included four anchors, the smaller of the two groups. These anchors were probably used by crews to secure the ships?? anchorage at the head of the bay. The second group included another five anchors, larger in size than the first group, 150 meters from the first group, towards the northeast headland of the islet. Four of these five anchors were recovered by the excavation team.

Name: Tanit
Reference: National Geographic, Jan 2001; American Journal of Archaeology, April 2002; Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004),34-40.
Comments: Phoenician amphora wreck found in deep water by a US Navy nuclear research submarine in 1997 and researched by R. Ballard in 1999, 20 miles off Ashkelon harbour and about 2km away from the similarly dated Elissa wreck. The area of the cargo measuerd 4.5 x 11.5m, suggesting an overall ship size of 14 x5.5m.
Other cargo: Timber, most probably cedars from Lebanon, bundles of wool and potter's clay.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Cooking pots with close parallels to those found in coastal Lebanon; an Egyptian handmade bowl, a Syrian mortarium, a small one quarterwine amphora; a wine decanter with mushroom-shaped rim for libations, a typical Phoenician design, and a small portable incense stand.

Name: Elissa
Reference: National Geographic, Jan 2001 & American Journal of Archaeology, April 2002;Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004),34-40.
Comments: Phoenician amphora wreck found in deep water by a US Navy nuclear research submarine in 1997 and researched by R. Ballard in 1999, 20 miles off Ashkelon harbour and about 2km away from the similarly dated Tanit wreck. The area of the cargo measuerd 5 x 12m, suggesting an overall ship size of 14.5 x 6m.
Other cargo: Timber, most probably cedars from Lebanon, bundles of wool and potter's clay.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Cooking pots with close parallels to those found in coastal Lebanon; an Egyptian handmade bowl, a Syrian mortarium, a small one quarterwine amphora; a wine decanter with mushroom-shaped rim for libations, a typical Phoenician design, and a small portable incense stand.

Name: Soldaya
Reference: http://www.abc.se/~pa/uwa/wreckblk.htm
Comments: "13th century shipwreck at Soldaya, on 12 m depth, investigated since 1999 by University of Kiev". No further information?

Name: Tekta? Burnu
Reference:
T. Nowak, IJNA 30 (2001), 86-94; K. Trethewet, IJNA 30 (2001), 109-114; Master Seafarers: The Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 118-121

 
 Bibliography

Bass, G.F.  “Golden Age Treasures,” National Geographic (March 2002): 102-117. 

_____. 2002b. “The Excavation of A Fifth-Century B.C. Shipwreck: 1999 Campaign.” In Tropis VII: 7 th International Symposium on Ship Construction in Antiquity, edited by H. Tzalas, 93-102. Athens: Hellenic Institute for the Preservation of Nautical Tradition.

Carlson, D.N. 2003. The Classical Greek Shipwreck at Tekta? Burnu, Turkey.” American Journal of Archaeology 107:581-600. 
 http://ina.tamu.edu/tektasburnu/
Comments: A small Greek ship, possibly 10-12m long, dated to 450-425 BC, carrying a cargo of wine and pine tar. Located on a shelf at a depth of 38-43 m in 1996, it was investigated in 1999-2001 by INA. The wreck also yielded the first and earliest discovered opthalmoi (decorated marble eyes).
Other cargo: Pottery appears to have been made in Ionia or on Chios, including a modest assortment of 2 handled drinking cups, one-handled bowls, table amphorae, oil lamps, a jug, a water pitcher and an askos. Fineware is limited to a stamped blak-glazed Attic kantharos and 2 small perfume vessels (a black-glazed askos and a creamy white stone alabastron.
Hull remains: Very little remained of the hull except for copper and lead nails; 2 opthalmoi (marble eyes)  were found, measuring 14cm, pierced by a lead spike and still showing the painted decoration, the first ever found on a shipwreck.
Ship equipment: 14 lead bars scattered around the wreck represent the remains of 5  anchors - the lead bars once formed the core of the wooden anchor stocks, in this case made of elm.

Name: Tantura A/Dor J
Reference: http://ina.tamu.edu/tanturaa.htm              INA Quarterly 22.2, 24.1 and 24.4         E. Galili and B. Rosen, IJNA (2008), 67-76
Comments: Probably 12m in length, and 4m wide, the Tantura A seems to have been snapped like a matchstick, indicating that the hull had broken on the rocks while entering the cove during a storm. The ship was excavated in Trench IV and VI of Tantura Lagoon on a NW to SE axis, with plenty of other material from a variety of  wrecks, dating from the C6th BC to the C6th AD,  in and around it, including stone anchor stocks. Repairs were made to the hull around the mid-ship area.
Marble type: A fragment of pavement from Trench IV and 2 slabs and 4 small fragments from Trench VI.
Other cargo: Plenty of organic material.
Hull remains: About 25% of the bottom of this small coaster remains showing its construction without the aid of un-pegged mortise and tenon joinery, although there were nail and bolt attachments - this makes it the oldest recorded hull built with this technique. The keel is preserved for a length of 5.2m. There is evidence of charring on some planks above and beneath the frame stations near the post, indicating that the burn marks are not the result of a haphazard blaze, but rather that the planks were charred prior to their attachment to the frames.  The charring was localized to the extremities of the strakes.  These considerations led  J.R. Steffy to conclude that the burn marks are the result of "char-bending," a process in which water-soaked planks are bent to shape as they are heated over a fire.   Tantura A is the earliest recorded evidence for this process in planked-hull ship construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: An amphora lid.
Ship equipment: Ropes were preserved in several locations beneath the hull.

Name: Tantura B/Dor N
Reference: http://ina.tamu.edu/tanturab.htm             INA Quarterly 24.4;   H. Khalilieh, IJNA 34 (2005), 314-322       M. Polzer, IJNA 37, (2008), 225-252
Comments: INA excavation. 19-30m in length, the only shipwreck discovered so far that dates to the C 9th. Due to its shape and angles, Steffy has suggested that it may be an oared galley.
Other cargo: Numerous remains of basketry, some of it amazingly delicate. Ceramics. Egyptian??
Hull remains: A considerable portion survives which suggests a long and narrow vessel strangely lacking in longitudinal strengthening. There is much evidence of caulking.
Shipboard paraphernalia: An exceptionallly large Abbasid-period lamp, another smaller lamp and 5 complete and one broken bivalve shells which may have been used as spoons (?, cf Yassi Ada wreck). Several spoon-like wooden items with pierced holes. A bone or ivory inlay, a wo
Ship equipment: At least 90 ballast stones of 4 main types: basalt, gabbro, chalk and limestone which point to a provenance of either north west Syria or Cyprus. Ropes of various sizes and 4 wooden toggles, 2 of which were beautifully lathe-crafted, polished smooth and decorated. Three  wooden roundels, one inscribed in Kufic, an early Arabic

Name: Tantura C
Reference: INA Quarterly 24.4 http://ina.tamu.edu/TL-Roman.htm
Comments: This 'Roman' wreck lies directly underneath Tantura B. This  hull appears to be a small portion of an enormous sea-going vessel. Said to be "Roman", but oil lamp clearly has a chi-rho.
Other cargo: Coarsewares, including perfectly preserved jugs.
Hull remains: Keel with mortise and tenon joints
Shipboard paraphernalia: Oil lamps, one with a Tau-Rho cross monogram
Ship equipment: Chain and hook (of a steeleyard?).

Name: Les Sorres X
Reference:
X. Raurich, M. Pujol et al, "Les Sorres X. Un vaixell medieval al canal olímpic de rem (Castelldefels, Baix Llobregat), Barcelona, (1992)
http://www.abc.se/~pa/mar/sorres10.htm
Comments: This is a small merchant ship (about 9.5-10 m long), dated to 1350-1400 AD that was carrying a cargo of amphorae filled with fish. The ship may have been emptied before being abandoned as there are not many artefacts on board.
Other cargo: A few fragments of bowls.
Hull remains: Well preserved. The boat carried a single mast-step for a lateen sail.Unusually there are two types of rudder: axial rudder (side rudder a.k.a. quarter rudder) and lateral rudder (stern rudder).

Name: Capraia Etruscan 2004
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0411.htm#capraia
Comments: One of two ancient wrecks discovered in 2004 300m off the island of Capraia.  No details given about the cargo except that there were 'various relics'.

Name: Capraia Roman 2004
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0411.htm#capraia
Comments: One of two ancient wrecks discovered in 2004 300m off the island of Capraia. No details given about the cargo except that there were 'various relics'.

Name: Le Grand Ribaud F (A??)
Reference: Les Etrusques : un voyage interrompu, by Bernard George; L. Long, P. Pomey and J-C Sourisseau, Les Etrusques en Mer (2000); L. Long et al, Bilan Scientifique 2000, 68-71; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 74-44; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 68-70; L. Long, Cahiers d'Archeologie 14 (2002), 5-40; L. Long and M. Rival, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 16 (2007), 98-114.         http://www.abc.se/~pa/uwa/wreckmed.htm
Comments: Etruscan wreck found by DRASSM and Comex in 2000 near Giens, France. Investigated by Luc Long in 2000 and 2001, using divers, mini sub and ROV. Several amphoras and bronze drinking bowls, and black-figure ceramics, were recovered. The ship is ca 30 m long, 7 m wide, loaded with 700-800 amphoras. The amphoras are made of clay from the Pyrgi area in Etruria.  The largest Etruscan wreck found so far.
Other cargo: Etruscan and Greek black-figure ceramics and bronze drinking bowls.
Hull remains: The lower hull is perfectly preserved under sand and sediment, including the rudder (cf Pointe Lequin 1A). False-tenon construction, with framing timbers (fastened by iron nails) which retained the forms of the frames found in stitched ships such as the Bon-Porte and Jules-Verne wrecks - points to local Greek construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: The bottom of a cup inscribed with a graffito which may be Greek. Etruscan amphorae type Py 5, Greek amphorae; mortars; an iron knife; .

Name: Melkarth
Reference: http://shipwreck.net/melkarth.html                  Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 56-57.
Comments: Punic or Phoenician ship, discovered by Odyssey Marine Exploration in 1998. The site covers an area of at least 50 x 30 feet.

Name: Marseille 3 (Jules Verne 9)
Reference: P. Pomey, Les épaves greques et romaines de la place Jules-Verne à Marseille. CRAI, 1995, 459-484; P. Pomey,Les epaves grecques du VI ieme siecle av. JC de la Place Jules-Verne a Marseille, Archaeonautica 14, (1998), 147-154.
Comments:
Fishing vessel of 6th c. BC, found in 1993, a typical example of an ancient sewn boat and of the lashing technique used in archaic times.
Lat 43 N 18, Long 5 E 24.
Hull remains: Over 5m x 1.4m of remains are intact, showing  an assembly entirely done with lashing.

Name: Marseille 4 (Jules Verne 7)
Reference: P. Pomey, Les épaves greques et romaines de la place Jules-Verne à Marseille. CRAI, 1995, 459-484; P. Pomey,Les epaves grecques du VI ieme siecle av. JC de la Place Jules-Verne a Marseille, Archaeonautica 14, (1998), 147-154.
Comments:
Greek sailing  vessel of 6th c. BC, found in 1993, an exceptional example of the transitional period betwwen lashing and portise and tenon joints
Lat 43 N 18, Long 5 E 24.
Hull remains: 14m x 4.7m has been preserved, the hull is broken in many places but still has complete forms (whole keel, wall up to the 3rd wale). Its most remarkeable characteristic is its double assembly system consisting of mortise and tenon joints for most of the hull and lashing for certain other parts. The frames are directly nailed to the hull.

Name: Marseille 5 (Jules Verne 3)
Reference: P. Pomey, Les épaves greques et romaines de la place Jules-Verne à Marseille. CRAI, 1995, 459-484.
Comments:
Roman coastal working boat.
Lat 43 N 18, Long 5 E 24.

Name: Marseille 6 (Jules Verne 4)
Reference: P. Pomey, Les épaves greques et romaines de la place Jules-Verne à Marseille. CRAI, 1995, 459-484.
Comments:
Roman coastal working boat.
Lat 43 N 18, Long 5 E 24.

Name: Marseille 7 (Jules Verne 8)
Reference: P. Pomey, Les épaves greques et romaines de la place Jules-Verne à Marseille. CRAI, 1995, 459-484.
Comments:
Roman coastal working boat or fishing vessel.
Lat 43 N 18, Long 5 E 24.

Name: Herculaneum II
Reference: F. Ruffi, Il nuovi scavi. Il nucleo edilizio all'angolo nord-occidentale della città. In: Cronache Ercolanesi 28, 1998, 39-42.
Comments:
Sailed.
Lat 40 N 45, Long 14 E 30

Name: Pointe Lequin 1A
Reference: P. Pomey et al 1987-88, 32-35; L. Long et al., Bilan Scientifique 1990, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 50 Bilan Scientifique 1993, 45-46; L. Long and M. Rival, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 16 (2007), 98-114.
Comments: The wreck of a ship carrying a cargo of wine and fine tableware from the Aegean.
Other cargo: Small bronze statue of a helmeted soldier; a large amount of Attic coarse ware and B2 cups (about 2,500 pieces) - decorated with scenes of  battle, mythology and daily life; oil lamps
Hull remains: Part of the hull and keel? with mortise and tenons, 7.5 cm pieces of strakes. Two pieces of wood which are thought to be part of the rudder, cf Grand Ribaud F wreck .

Name: L'Isolella
Reference: H. Alfonsi and P. Gandolfo, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 10 (1991), 199-207
Comments: A cargo of tiles
Other cargo: Tegulae (57 complete and 388 fragments) and imbricae (56 complete and 80 fragments).
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Dr 20 amphora, a carpenter's pick-axe and a small axe

Name: Cap Benat B/ Cap Benat 2
Reference: J-P Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1992, 51; Bilan Scientifique 1993, 48-49;  Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 13 (1997), 97-119 .
Comments: There are a few anomolies regarding this small ship that held 3 or 4 dolia eg. why did one of the dolia contain bones?
Hull remains: A classic construction, only 4m survives, including sections of the keel and frames. Probably only 8m long
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarseware, Campanian A and C ware.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones made up of different rocks, and Massiliot, Dr 1A and Dr 1C amphora fragments.

Name: La Jaume-Garde B
Reference: P. Pomey, Bilan scientifique du Département des recherches archéologiques sous-marines (1993), 44
Hull remains: The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Barthelemy B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol, Cavaliere and Port la Nautique).

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 27
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2005, 51
Comments: The eleventh shipwreck or iron ingots discovered in the Camargues area.
Other cargo: Iron ingots and bars.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A basket/ container of small iron nails.

Name: Elba
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/112/1/relitto-profondo-dallelba-di-mario-galasso.html
Comments: A large cargo ship of Spanish amphorae seen as a 45m long mound, accidentally discovered during a dive with a mini-sub.

Name: Perelli
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0307.htm#perelli
Comments: An early Imperial wreck of amphorae and other ceramics.
Other cargo: Ceramics?

Name: Isole di Ponza
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2001/news0107.htm
Comments: An intact deposit of amphorae although no signs of hull remains.

Name: Bocca Grande
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html                 archeomar site 80, area 25
Comments: The deposit measures approximately 15-16m in length and 8m in width and rises from the seabed about 3-4m.

Name: Bocca Piccola 1
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 178, area 25
Comments: Fragments of amphorae possibly belonging to a wreck.

Name: Punta dell'Arcera
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html                site 180, area 25              http://www.archeomar.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=21&Itemid=35#relitti
Comments: A large accumulation of amphorae seemingly still in their original vertical position, with an inclination of between 30-40 degreeswith respect to the seabed. A few amphorae lie randomly on top.

Name: Pigne (Salerno)
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=21&Itemid=35#relitti
Comments: The site covers an area of 30m x 9m.
Marble type: Over a hundred marble closed pine cones.
Other cargo: Glazed ceramic vessels
Hull remains: Pieces of wood.
Ship equipment: Fragment of an anchor and other various objects such as metal bars and cylindrical metal objects.

Name: Ischia
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2002/news0203.htm#ischia
Comments: Artefacts were found suggesting a Roman ship that also seems to be a bireme.

Name: Gallipoli 1
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html              site 143, area 9
Ship equipment: Two groups of at least 5 large iron anchors; 2  are still upright, of which one has its stock still attached. Further away but on the same longitudinal line, are 2  other large completely conserved anchors, one with its shank.

Name: Gallipoli 2
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0307.htm#gallipoli
Comments: One of two wrecks found by chance by police a mile from the coast between Gallipoli and Santa Maria di Leuca. Twenty-five amphorae were seized from looters and other artefacts but thee are no other details.

Name: Gallipoli 3
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0307.htm#gallipoli
Comments: One of two wrecks found by chance by police a mile from the coast between Gallipoli and Santa Maria di Leuca. Twenty-five amphorae were seized from looters and other artefacts but thee are no other details.

Name: Torre Santa Sabina 2
Reference: F. Zongolo, Atti del Convegno Nazionale de Archeologia Subacquea: Antium May-June 1996 (1997), 245-249; C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana (2002), 457
Hull remains: The outline of the ship is visible and construction points to mortise and tenon joints.

Name: Margherita di Savoia
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0407.htm#margherita                                                       http://www.archeomar.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=32&Itemid=47
Comments: The remains of a hull and unspecified ceramics mark the site discovered in 2004.
Hull remains: At least 9 beams and numerous other parts of planking can be seen. Mortise and tenon construction, many iron nails also found on the site.

Name: Ancona 1
Reference: http://www.archeomarche.it/scap.htm
Comments: One of three Roman wrecks discovered during a military operation and subsequently examined by a ROV 40 miles off the coast of Ancona. The site covers an area of 35 x 25m.

Name: Ancona 2
Reference: http://www.archeomarche.it/scap.htm
Comments: One of three Roman wrecks discovered during a military operation and subsequently examined by a ROV 40 miles off the coast of Ancona.

Name: Ancona 3
Reference: http://www.archeomarche.it/scap.htm
Comments: One of three Roman wrecks discovered during a military operation and subsequently examined by a ROV 40 miles off the coast of Ancona.

Name: Caorle
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana 2002, 456; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 181.         http://www.comune.caorle.ve.it/storia_e_cultura/archeologia.php
Comments: Discovered in 1992 in international waters and seen through videos, the site appears to be a classic ellipsoidal tumulus of amphorae covered by a layer of concretion 30cm thick. The wreck had already been damaged by fishing boats, but is now protected and "sealed". The ship may have been 23m long and 9m wide.
Hull remains: Good condition.

Name: Lazzaretto B
Reference: http://members.xoom.it/crasa/cracur.htm

Name: Ottiolu
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0306.htm#ottiolu
Marble type: Finished grey, fine-grained marble slabs, possibly from Luna.
Hull remains: Some fragments of wood and some nails.

Name: La Speranza
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/3/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: A totally shattered wreck of Dr 8-9 amphorae spread over a 100m sq area.
Other cargo: Concretions of iron items?
Shipboard paraphernalia: A bowl, broken Dr 7-11 amphorae

Name: Cala Reale
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 460; P. Spanu, Atti del Convegno Nazionale di Archaologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996, (1997), 109-119.          http://members.xoom.it/crasa/calareal.htm
Comments: A cargo of 5 types of mainly Spanish fish sauce amphorae found in 1995.
Other cargo: A shipment of glass paste tesserae accompanied the main cargo of amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A coin manufactured by the mint of Rome between 364 and 367 during the reign of Valens

Name: L'Asinara 2
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 460; P. Spanu, Atti del Convegno Nazionale di Archaologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996, (1997), 109-119.          http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/678/1/trovati-due-relitti-nei-fondali-del-golfo-dellasinara.html
Comments: A very deep wreck of Lusitanian amphorae examined by ROV in 2007.
Other cargo: A large concretion of minerals or metals.

Name: Olbia Late Roman 1
Reference: R. D'Oriano, Archeologia in Sardegna, 2007,  98-103                                                                                                                                   http://www.archeosub.it/news2000/news0009.htm#olbia
Comments: At least eleven C5th shipwrecks found during construction work of the tunnel in Olbia and excavated between 1999 and 2001. They are lying side by side and have been burned and sunk. This was correlated with the assault and destruction of the city by the Vandals in the C5th AD. The area in fact corresponds to the port of ancient Olbia.
Hull remains: Remains of nine Late Roman wrecks, some of which were as long as 30m. Four rudders over 8m long, only seen previously in the now burnt Lake Nemi ships. Characteristics of transition between the technical construction of  Greek-Roman to Medieval shipbuilding can be seen.

Name: Cala del Falco 1
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/3/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Other cargo: In the late '70s a 4m long lead bar was still visible .

Name: Teulada
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0311.htm#cagliari
Comments: A massive mound, 4m high and 20 or 30m long, of 5 types of amphora was found in 1998.

Name: Trapani
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 458
Comments: Excavated by the G.I.A.S.S. Group
Hull remains: A section is preserved.

Name: Caucana
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2002/news0207.htm
Comments: A vague report of a Byzantine wreck that seems to have been a merchant ship.

Name: Capo Feto
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 127     http://www.regione.sicilia.it/beniculturali/archeologiasottomarina/sez_eventi/capo%20feto.htm
Hull remains: A portion of the keel and part of the stern.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones

Name: Porto Palo di Menfi
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, (2002), p. 458; B. Basile, in Atti del Convegno Nazionale di Archaologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996,  (1997), 147-152                        http://www.regione.sicilia.it/beniculturali/archeologiasottomarina/prod_editoriali/op_scras/Opuscolo%20SCRAS-Pag%2023_31.pdf            http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/77/6/archeologi-in-fondo-al-mare-di-gianfranco-purpura.html
Comments: Excavated by the G.I.A.S.S. Group, the site covers an area 16 x 6m, unusually for Sicily is in shallow waters.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Ceramics including a pyx with black paint, maybe an inkwell, and fragments of dishes and cups

Name: Secche della Circe
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0408.htm
Comments: Presumably a cargo of amphorae.
Hull remains: In good condition, the ship measured 20m x 6m.
Ship equipment: An iron anchor has been brought up.

Name: Cala Minnola
Reference: http://www.regione.sicilia.it/beniculturali/archeologiasottomarina/
Comments: A cargo of Dr 1B amphorae much looted before its excavation in 2005. It is now on CCTV to allow people to see the wreck from dry land.
Hull remains: Some fragments of wood.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Fragments of coarseware and black-gloss pottery.
Ship equipment: Lead pipes from  the bilge pump, an anchor.

Name: Sciacca
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 458
Hull remains: Yes.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Some lamps and amphorae, although these may be cargo??
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock.

Name: Olbia Roman Imperial
Reference: E. Riccardi, IJNA 31 (2002) 268-269; R. D'Oriano, Archeologia in Sardegna, 2007,  98-103
Comments: Two C1st AD merchant ships that had sunk in a flood were found during the construction work in Olbia and excavated between 1999 and 2001. In this area was also found the remains of a naval shipyard and amongst these remains, a 7.6m length of a mast was found (probably half its original length).
Other cargo: Oil lamps and glassware.

Name: Capo Galera
Reference: P. Spanu, in Atti del Convegno Mazionale di Archeologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996 (1997), 109-119; C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana (2002), 462
Comments: An Islamic cargo investigated in the 1990s.
Other cargo: Glazed pottery - bowls, plates and casseroles
Shipboard paraphernalia: Sandals, a silver pitcher and a musical wind instrument.

Name: Les Aresquiers 3
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998, 27
Comments: It’s not certain whether this is a mooring place where amphorae were jettisoned or an actual shipwreck site.

Name: Les Mouettes
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998,  27; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 33
Comments: A wreck that has not been excavated although many objects have come to light from the site at the entrance to the port of Frontignan.
Other cargo: Tiles, copper ingots and lead ingots some of which are stamped M AURELI; a bronze tripod
Hull remains: Copper nails
Shipboard paraphernalia: Bronze and silver coins (one of Marcus Aurelius); a bronze ax head and  bronze scales; an oil lamp and part of a pot representing the head of a ram.
Ship equipment: A sounding weight, rings associated with the rigging and 2 iron anchors

Name: Les Lingots
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998, 27

Name: Les Aresquiers 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 33
Comments: A possible wreck a mile and a half off the coast of Frontignan.

Name: Les Pierres
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 33; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 47
Comments: A presumed cargo of stone.
Other cargo: 75 blocks of stone from Bois des Lens, north-west of Nimes, including 7 columns and capitals. The blocks were still lying in alignment and were rectangular; the dimensions varied between 0.7 0.75 x 0.6m and 2.85 x 0.6 x0.7m. This type of stone was popular for its similar look to marble.

Name: Plage Beauregard
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 34; Bilan Scientifique 2000, 48
Comments: An area 150m long of concreted amphora fragments found 250m from the coast. It is uncertain whether this is a homogenous wreck site or simply spillage from the nearby Riches Dunes 2 and Beausejour wrecks.
Hull remains: A piece of lead sheathing showed traces of nails.

Name: Conque des Salins
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 35-38
Comments: A 15m hull in very good condition, the shipw as probably only used within the Etang for trading or unloading from larger ships.
Hull remains: A section 7.7m long and 2.2 m wide was preserved of this flat-bottomed boat showing  the keel, frames etc.

Name: Redoute Bear 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2000, 40; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 41; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 38-39
Comments: The ship was about 15m-17m long and 6m wide.
Hull remains: 192 copper nails
Shipboard paraphernalia: Campanian ware, Catalan ware

Name: Les Tambours
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2000, 53-54
Comments: Dispersed over an area 20m x 6m were 16 stone column drums
Marble type: Sixteen drums measuring between 0.5 and 0.8m high with traces of inscriptions, possibly from Les Lens

Name: Bonnieu 5
Reference: S. Gadal, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 36
Comments: A small cargo of limestone blocks
Marble type: Three rows of 57 finished limestone blocks

Name: Baie de l'Amitie/Les Battuts 2
Reference: M.-P. Jezegou, Bilan Scientifique 1998, 28; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 43-44
Hull remains: Hull measuring an area of 7.75m x 3.2m comprising 22 frames, 14 strakes, the keel and the stempost. The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Cavaliere, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Barthelemy B, Cap del Vol and Port la Nautique).

Name: Les Riches Dunes 4
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2002, 47; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 42-46; Bilan Scientifique 2004, 42-43.
Comments: A storm shifted sand that exposed 2 Roman statues lying 25om off the coast.
Other cargo: Two bronze statues: the first is of a young naked child, 65cm high, possibly Eros, datable to C1st BC- AD. The second is also of a child, in a short tunic, 80cm high and very well preserved, datable to the same era. They are both probablly from Campania and may have belonged to an Italian moving to Gaul (?). A mosaic  emblema measuring 48 x 49cm representing the judgement of Marsyas on a base of travertine.
Hull remains: Copper nails, lead sheathing.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Various ceramics including fragments of terra sigillatta produced between 30 and 10 BC
Ship equipment: An iron anchor, a lead pipe and bronze rings probably from a bilge pump.

Name: La Fangade
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2002, 44-

Name: Est Brescou
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 55-56

Name: Marine de Tollare
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1992, 59

Name: Calanque de Conca
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1992, 58
Comments: Discovered in the 1960s and re-examined in the 1990s, this was a cargo of dolia (but interestingly without the usual accompaniament of Dr 2-4 amphorae).

Name: Marina di Fiori
Reference: H. Bernard, Bilan Scientifique 1993, 60-61; Bilan Scientifique 1994, 63; Bilan Scientifique 1995, 69; Bilan Scientifique 1996, 113' Etienne and Mayet, 2000, 245, no 45
Comments: Spread over an area 17m sq, an interesting wreck of blocks of minerals as well as amphorae with hitherto unknown stamps. Evidently there had been a serious fire on board (blackened sherds and melted resin) which probably led to its demise.
Other cargo: A secondary cargo of blocks of minerals, never found on a wreck before. Some are of clay and are stamped M.ACILI and VENU
Hull remains: Iron nails and part of the cabin including tegulae stamped with L.HEREN (IUS) and MARI.
Ship equipment: Part of a pipe

Name: Ratino 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1993, 62
Comments: A cargo of Dr 2-4 amphorae.

Name: Bugho I
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1994, 59; Bilan Scientifique 2004, 88

Ship equipment: Lead sounding weights

Name: Martinska
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 44
Comments: A probable shipwreck of flat-bottomed amphorae.

Name: Erbalunga
Reference: H. Bernard, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 87

Other cargo: 32kg of medium and small-sized coins dated to the end of the reign of Constantine I and the end of the C4th AD. The amphora was a Byzantine Keay XXV.

Name: Pointe Cacalu

Other cargo: Oil lamps including Dressel-Lamboglia type 3 classic.
Hull remains: Some remains show that the ship was built of oak, ash and pie. Iron and copper nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Part of some bronze scales
Ship equipment: A complete pulley made of beech, oak and ash

Name: Porto Pollo 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 75

Name: Les Moines 1

Name: Les Moines 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1993, 61; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 75-76

Name: Olmeto

Name: Cavallo 4
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 77

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer 3

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer 8
Reference: L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1996, 75

Name: Plage d'Arles 5

Name: Plage d'Arles 8
Reference: L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1996, 78.

Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 52; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 62        http://piccard.esil.univmed.fr/venus/external/webMarseille/pres2.php?language=en

Name: Sud Gracieuse

Comments: A cargo of bronze objects.

Bronze scales, measuring 26cm and engraved with numbers I-VII on one side, with hooks decorated as ducks' heads; a few other bronze decoration fragments including part of a 'simplum' and a hinged bronze lid decorated with a dolphin.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer 24
Reference: L. Long et al, Bilan Scientifique 2002, 53-54; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 66-71.
Comments: Another wreck of iron bars and ingots from a ship 20-25m long.

Name: Cavalaire 1
Reference: M. Dalhaye, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 50;  Bilan Scientifique 1995, 54-56; Bilan Scientifique 1996, 100-101
Comments: An interesting ship in that its construction seems to have originated from the Bay of Biscay/Atlantic style of ship building. It was carrying weapons.
Other cargo: A huge amount of weapons - at least 8 cannons, projectile weapons, crossbow parts, lance tips
Hull remains: Extremely well preserved - Bay of Biscay style of ship building (clinker style) - position of the cabin, the type of nailing etc.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Whale bones - the remains of a whale hunt or simply bones that were used as tools?
Ship equipment: All sorts of pulleys.

Name: Balise de Rabiou
Reference: B. Dangreaux,  Bilan Scientifique 1993, 50; A. and P. Joncheray,Bilan Scientifique 2001, 78-79; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 91-92; Bilan Scientifique 2004, 83; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 80-81.
Comments: A cargo of amphorae from a small local ship.
Hull remains: Some well preserved sections including the keel, the mast-step  and about 40 frames and interestingly, some pieces of leather.
Ship equipment: Anchor parts

Name: Chretienne M
Reference: A. and J.-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 53, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 76-77; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 14 (2002) 57-130

Name: Barthelemy B
Reference: A. and J.-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 54; Bilan Scientifique 1995, 59-60; Bilan Scientifique 1996, 105-106; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 71-73; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 15 (2004), 7-72; S. Wicha, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 15 (2004), 135-144.
Comments: A small coastal ship, 12m long, transporting local tiles.
Other cargo: Tegulae and imbrices from Frejus cf Dramont G and Roches d'Aurelle wrecks.
Hull remains: Well preserved. The construction was mixed with a combination of ligatures and more traditional mortise and tenon (cf Tour Fondue 1, Cavaliere, Jeaume Garde B, Plane 1, Cap Bear 3, Roche Fouras, Baie de l'Amitie, Cap del Vol and Port la Nautique).
Shipboard paraphernalia: A lead 'foculus', cf the wrecks of Lardier 4 and Cap Benat.

Name: Lardier 4
Reference: A. and J.-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1995, 58; Bilan Scientifique 1997, 75-76; Bilan Scientifique 1998, 50; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 65; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 15 (2004), 73-118.
Comments: A small cargo of local tiles
Other cargo: Nine rows of tegulae in 2 layers and imbrices in the residual spaces. A large amount of pottery typical of the lower Argens valley (Rivet form 17)
Hull remains: Twelve strakes and 9 frames, as well as part of the keel show a typical mortise and tenon construction of a small (12m) ship.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Massiliot amphora, an iron stove (a 'foculus', cf Barthelemy B and Cap Benat wrecks) and kitchen utensils; 2 ceramic pipettes, small scales and a touchstone
Ship equipment: Twenty-five rigging rings

Name: Baie de Sanary
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1996, 89.

Name: Grand Rouveau 2
Reference: A. and J.-P. Joncheray, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 56; Bilan Scientifique 1999, 57-58; Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 15 (2004), 119-134.
Comments: A cargo of tiles dispersed between two great rock masses over 15m, possibly one of the earliest in Antiquity.
Other cargo: Tiles, between 100 and 300 imbrices and probably as many tegulae.
Hull remains: None.

Name: La Palud 2
Reference: L. Long and G. Volpe, Bilan Scientifique 1994, 48-49
Comments: An archaic shipwreck carrying dozens of Massiliot amphorae, cf Dattier and Bon Porte wrecks.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Some Massiliot coarseware

Name: La Plage d'Argent 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 60
Comments: Although this is a site comprising objects from various eras that has been damaged and pillaged, there does seem to be a wreck datable to the Roman Republic .

Name: Baie du Brusc
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2001, 72; Bilan Scientifique 2002, 67

Name: Marinieres I
Reference: M. Daeffler, Bilan Scientifique 1997, 78.
Comments: Dated by dendrachronology. No cargo.
Hull remains: A large section of the hull, 18 x 8.7m, is well preserved resting on its side.

Name: Pabuç Burnu
Reference: http://ina.tamu.edu/yasymposium/PDFs/Greene.pdf                  http://ina.tamu.edu/pabucburnu/   Polzer, M.E. 2004. An Archaic Laced Hull in the Aegean: The 2003 Excavation and Study of the Pabuç Burnu Ship Remains. INA Quarterly 31.3: 3-11          E. Greene et al, AJA 112 (2008), 685-711
Comments: Twenty-eight of the amphorae have been studied and there is a distinct lack of standardization in capacity despite relatively consistent linear dimensions. a modest-sized merchant vessel unlikely to have sailed beyond the immediate area between Rhodes and Miletus. The wreck, which carried an assortment of coarseware cups, bowls, and pitchers, along with about 250 amphoras that probably carried wine or olive oil. The site covers an area of 26m x 14m and was excavated in the early 2000s.
Other cargo: A heavy concentration of grape seeds in the lower region of the site suggests that the ship also carried a bulk cargo of grapes or raisins, perhaps packed in sacks or baskets, which did not survive underwater.
Hull remains: Construction features visible on six fragmentary planks recovered from the ship's hull reveal that it was laced together. Such lacing of planks appears in Homer's Odyssey where the hero builds a boat for his journey away from the island of Calypso (5.244-8). There is also evidence for an early adaptation of mortise and tenon joinery.
Shipboard paraphernalia: An assemblage of plain wares (bowls, mortars, and pitchers) and Ionian cup sherds decorated with black slip. These are likely all of southern Ionian production.
Ship equipment: A large, stone anchor stock from near the center of the site (M10). It has a wide notch carved at its mid-point, measures 1.65 m (5.4 ft) long, and weighs 115 kg. A similar shaped smaller stone anchor was found farther down the slope.

Name: Marina Grande di Bacoli
Dating: 2nd half C1st BC- end C1st AD
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html               archeomar site 53, area 25
Comments: A probable shipwreck as there are several intact amphorae in what looks like their original position.
Other cargo: Numerous fragments of unidentified pottery.

Name: Golfo di Pozzuoli (Le Crastole)
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html             archeomar site 57, area 25

Name: Bocca Piccola 2
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html   site 189, area 25               http://www.archeomar.it/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=21&Itemid=35#relitti
Comments: A long, oval mound of amphorae measuring approximately 12m by 2.5m with a height of about 80-100cm.

Name: Golfo di Pozzuoli
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 211, area 25
Comments: The site of a probable shipwreck with a cargo of various African amphorae.

Name: Li Galli - Vetara
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 260, area 25
Comments: Heavily looted complete cargo of amphorae of which only two remain since its discovery 40 years ago.

Name: Punta Licosa 2
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html   site 59, area 22
Comments: A probable wreck although no hull fragments were discovered, and various random amphorae were found nearby - an archaic Greek C6th, Lamboglia 2/Dressel 6 and the base of a medieval jar.
Marble type: About 15-20  blocks with dimensions varying from 50 to 100cm which have clearly been squared

Name: Capo Palinuro - Punta della Quaglia
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 217, area 21
Comments: The wide spread of the material and the size of the anchor stock suggest that this was a large vessel. However the anchor shank only provides a general chronology, as it can be dated over a wide period.
Hull remains: Part of the planking still in position.
Ship equipment: A complete anchor stock, 3m long. A tube about 15cm long, probably made of lead, bent at one end, possibly part of the bilge pump. Several metal objects lying in an upright position,  may belong to part of an anchor shank.

Name: Punta di Zambrone
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html   site 133, area 18
Comments: A probable shipwreck with sparse fragments of amphorae.

Name: Capo d'Armi
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html  site 134, area 17
Comments: The probable remains of a a cargo of amphorae.

Name: Capo Bianco
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html   site 26, area 14                 http://www.reitia.it/nave_lapidaria_di_capo_bianco.html         http://www.reitia.it/archeologia_subacquea_nel_crotonese.php
Comments: Excavated 1991, this is another navis lapidaria discovered in shallow water off Calabria.
Marble type: Blocks of heterogeneous dimensions and drums of columns, distributed in a chaotic manner among the rocks. One of the larger blocks had been worked to create a semi-column on one of the long sides. The marble is of 3 different types.

Name: Capo Donato
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html    site 75, area 14
Comments: Fragments of material jumbled up and overlaying one another to form blocks of concretions and forming a sort of artificial reef.
Other cargo: Cooking ware, generally of an open-form type.

Name: Seleno
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html    site 88, area 14
Comments: A probable shipwreck with a  cargo of scattered pieces of pottery in poor condition.
Hull remains: Apiece of wood of modest dimensions but heavily eaten by termites.

Name: Capo Colonna, Cicala
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html site 19, area 14
Comments: A cargo of architectural material.
Marble type: Blocks of considerable dimensions, 6-7m in length, including 2 coumn drums with a diameter of c70cm and a length of 4-5m. The blocks laid as headers and sitting on their long sides are stacked without any particular order and are mostly parallelepiped or cubed in form and all are semi-worked and carved.

Name: Cantafora B
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 20, area 14
Comments: A probable shipwreck of semi-worked blocks of marble.
Marble type: An accumulation of semi-worked blocks distributed in a disorderly manner and slightly overlying one another. Several of the column drums, with a diameter of 70cm, are already prepared with the hole for fixing the the column cut in the centre of the circumference.

Name: La Tonnara
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html    site 22, area 14
Comments: A group of amphora fragments now attached to the rocks, probably the remains of a ship's cargo.

Name: Torre Melissa - Villaggio Sirio
Dating: end of the C2nd- end C1st BC
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html        site 33, area 13
Comments: The site is almost completely covered in sand. Several sporadic pottery fragmments are visible.
Hull remains: A fragment of wood, heavily compromised by parasites and by xlophagous organisms.s

Name: Nardo
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html       site 164, area 9

Name: Santa Caterina di Nardo 2
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html      site 161, area 9

Name: Torre Sinfono
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html        site 139, area 9

Name: Cala Palombara
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html       site 149, area 8
Comments: The site is covered with scattered pieces of amphorae attached to the seabad or amassed inside the cavaties if the rocks.

Name: Mucurune
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html        site 6, area 8
Comments: The site area can be identified by a wide spread of amphorae sherds
Ship equipment: A large 2m anchor, heavily concreted, lying with the shaft and arms resting against a large block.

Name: Torre Chianca (Lecce)
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html             sites 81, 167 and 168  area 7
Comments: Three connected sites that may well be one shipwreck.
Hull remains: A 3m x 20cm piece of wood, probably part of a keelson. Close by are at least 5 pieces of planking and other external planking boards, all mortise and tenon. Lead sheathing found on site 168 may be part of the same hull. Part of a keel found at site 167 may be part of the same hull too.

Name: Torre Testa - Porto di Brindisi
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html            site 271, area 6
Comments: A range of pottery spread over a vast area of silt and debris. Maybe a shipwreck that has been disturbed by the continuous passage of lare ships.

Name: Isole Pedagne Grandi
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html          site 5, area 6
Comments: A probable shipwreck with a variety of very fragmented pottery, including amphorae, coarse ware and glazed pieces, with assorted pieces of wood.
Marble type: Various broken pieces of an unidentified column.
Hull remains: Assorted pieces of wood.

Name: Atlit E
Other cargo: Scrap metal

Name: Dor A
Comments: 22m (?) in length, ballast stones

Name: Dor D
Reference: Y. Kahanov and J. Royal, IJNA 30 (2001), 257-65; S. Kingsley, A Sixth Century AD Shipwreck off the Carmel Coast, Israel: Dor D and the Holy Land Wine Trade (2002); S. Kingsley, IJNA 32 (2003), 85-90; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Later Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 68-71; J. Royal and Y. Kahanov, IJNA 34 (2005), 308-313
Comments: One of 13 wreck sites in the area, this ship was only 15m in length, and seems to have been returning empty amphorae for recycling, collected from northern Mediterranean cities. About 750 amphora fragments have been examined and most belong to LR5 amphorae some with grape pips still embedded in the pitch lining. The wreck site was protected by the ship's ballast stones.
Hull remains: Fourteen Cyprus timbers were protected by the ballast stones with evidence of char-bending. Loose moritse and tenon joints are  26.4cm apart, 68% are fixed with treenails, 32% with iron nails, showing a leaning towards frame-first construction. The timbers have been dated by C14 to mid C5th-mid C6th AD.
Shipboard paraphernalia: An Egyptian Aswan-ware bowl.
Ship equipment: 350 Cypriot ballast stones covering an area 10.6 x 8.3m. Roof tiles. At least 3 single-hole tone anchors (66kg, 85kg and 109kg), found nearby, very much inferior type anchors for the time, may be part of this wreck.

Name: Dor E
Comments: Ballast stones

Name: Dor F
Comments: Ballast stones, masonry

Name: Dor G
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Perpilus, 2004), 40-41.
Comments: At least 9m in length, masonry
Shipboard paraphernalia: A pair of bronze steelyards, the largest of which measured 97cm with Greek inscribed along the beam showing that it could weigh up to 160lbs. It had had 3 successive owners according to the inscriptions: the earlies reads "Saviour Jesus Christ, come to the aid of Khala and Artemon"; the second, "Jesus Christ, come to the aid of George son of Ision"; the third, "Jesus Christ, generated God, take pity on Psates of Rhion".

Name: Dor O
Comments: masonry
Hull remains: Yes.

Name: Dor M
Comments: A ship 13.5m in length.
Hull remains: Yes.

Name: Ginosar B
Hull remains: Yes.

Name: Givat Olgar
Comments: Ballast stones

Name: Hahotrim C
Marble type: 'Masonry', capitals and columns

Name: Sdot Yam D
Hull remains: Lead sheathing

Name: Sdot Yam E
Marble type: Bowls and columns

Name: Ashkelon
Marble type: 'Masonry' columns and drums.

Name: Tantura F
Reference: INA and RIMS and NAS             http://maritime2.haifa.ac.il/eng/UWarchold.asp;                http://maritime2.haifa.ac.il/eng/nl/Rims31/rims31.pdf#page=17                                          O. Barkai and Y. Kahanov, IJNA 36 (2008), 21-31
Comments: The archaeological remains spread over an area of 12 by 13.5m, although the ship was probably 15 metres in overall length, with a beam of about 5 metres. Another ship to add information about the period of transitional ship construction, this is the first early C8th vessel discovered and excavated so far in the Eastern Mediterranean.
Other cargo: About 30 ceramic vessels, some containing fish remains, and a juglet. A large amount of fish bones, carobs and olive stones were also found on the site.
Hull remains: The keel, frames, planks, central longitudional timbers, stringers and mast step assemblage survive, up the turn of the bilge and nearly from bow to stern. The keel is of pinus brutia and pinis niagra, the frames of Tamarix smyrnensis and pinus brutia, as are the planks. Evidence of caulking. Skeleton-first construction.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A reed mat, a wooden spoon, and a large needle. A large amount of fish bones and food remnants (carobs and pits of Nabali olives)
Ship equipment: A rope, and a wooden roundel. Two anchors.

Name: Tantura Trench VIII
Reference: INA
Comments: Only 8m west of Tantura A, this hull is also situated on a NW to SE axis.
Hull remains: At the far end, the ship has been broken and its keel tortuously ripped apart. It has a massive centre-line timber overlying the keel and frames, inot which is cut a long rectangular mast-step heel (40 x 8.6 x 6.5cm). Its unusual shape may indicate that the ship carried a lateen rig.

Name: Tantura E ? Trench IX
Reference: INA;
Comments: 12m NE of Tantura A this hull is roughly contemporaneous with Yassi Ada and in a better state of preservation.
Other cargo: Two ashlar blocks are retained in their original alignment, directly inboard of the transverse timber. Maybe cargo, alternatively they may have served as ballast.
Hull remains: A large hull, the upper parts of which were damaged by teredo, fairly well preserved. Two carved graffiti - one depicting a cross covered by ana rc, the other a 'delta' -  were noted on the ceiling planking.
Ship equipment: See other cargo above.

Name: Dor 2001/1
Reference: http://maritime2.haifa.ac.il/eng/UWarchold.asp               http://maritime2.haifa.ac.il/eng/nl/rims30/rims30.pdf#page=22
Comments: The flat-bottomed medium-sized merchant ship originally measured 16m in length and 6m in width. and is very well preserved.
Other cargo: Almost all of the hull remains were covered by about 100 building stones made of local kurkar (coarse calcerous sandstone) stacked in 2 layers of 3 to 7 rows.The stones are approximately the same size, 57 x 28 x 18cm.
Hull remains: Most of the lower part of the hull survived. Eight different species of wood were used for the hull construction, 6 of which originate from western Turkey. The other 2 types which are local may have simply been repairs as they are found only in the frames in the NW part of the hull. No mortise and tenon joints were found, thus suggesting a frame-first construction, although traces of caulking were found.
Ship equipment: The stones were laid on a woven mat which protected the ceiling planking.

Name: Dor south-east
Reference: E. Galili et al, Hadeshot Journal 119 (2007);  E. Galili and B. Rosen, IJNA (2008) 67-76                                                                                                                                        http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.asp?id=562&mag_id=112
Comments: A medium-sized boat constructed with iron nails, its artefacts scatterd over an area 40 by 50m. Coin finds dated it to c. AD 665 (bronze coins from 600-650 and a corroded clump of coins that contained 53 coins from the time of Anastatius I until Constans II). The fishing tackle shows that the ship was engaged in various fishing activities and the basket for kindling is the first viable archaeological evidence for night fishing in antiquity.
Other cargo: Two piles of kurklar (ashlar) stones measuring 24 x 25 x 60cm, some of which have a rectangular slot. Metal artefacts.
Hull remains: The hull was represented by scores of square-sectioned iron nails, 13-21cm long. Traces of fibre, probably used for sealing, were preserved on some of them
Shipboard paraphernalia: A basket-shaped pottery vessel containing grape remains, a bronze cooking pot with 2 ear-shaped handles, a ploughshare. Iron tools including 2 distinct assemblages: a shipwright's kit comprising an axe, a builder's hammer with a nail extractor, a drill with a wooden handle and a 92cm-long sharpened iron bar with a hole near the sharp tip. Fishing gear included lead net sinkers, an iron fishing spear-head with 5 prongs and an iron fire-basket for a lantern, as well as a sounding lead and a bronze steelyard weight in the shape of a woman's bust (7.41kg).
Ship equipment: Several heaps of unworked ballast stones. Dozens of wooden pulleys (diam. 4cm) probably used for rigging or as floats for a fishing net.

Name: Ashkelon North Roman
Reference: Hadeshot/ESI 120 (2008)          http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.asp?id=743&mag_id=114
Comments: The remains were scattered over an area of 30 by 30m and the ship is estimated to have been 15-25m in length.
Other cargo: Bronzes: 3 figurines, a nude female (20cm, Aphrodite?), a naked bearded man (10cm, a Satyr?)  and a small zoomorphic  figure (1.9cm, monkey?). Other bronzes: a bell (12cm), a weight in the shape of a cardium shell, 2 decorative pieces, a lid of a vessel that bears 2 busts in relief and a lead mace head.
Hull remains: Bronze nails with a square cross-section that were used for the hull, lead sheathing fragments.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Fishing objects, including hooks, bronze needles and lead weights.
Ship equipment: A lead assembly piece of a wooden anchor with 2 arms (0.82m, c. 20kg), several sections of lead pipes (diam. c 4cm length 1-1.5m) and a lead collecting box (0.5 x0.5 x0.8m) used to pump water from the bilge. Six bronze pulley wheels.

Name: Herzliya Beach
Reference: http://www.hadashot-esi.org.il/report_detail_eng.asp?id=507&mag_id=112                     E. Galili et al, Hadeshot Journal 119 (2007)
Comments: The ship was probably about 20-25m long, carrying a cargo of millstones, possibly from Syria or Turkey.
Other cargo: A cargo of unfinished donkey millstones made of basalt - 6 conical lower stones (0.8 x 0.85 m, 395kg) and 5 biconical upper stones (0.6 x 0.57m, 250kg) - were scattered along the flat rocky seabed.
Hull remains: Copper-alloy nails with square shanks, all bent and distorted, seemingly from the force of the wreck. Different sizes are 8-9cm, 10-12cm, and 13-16cm with a max thickness of 5-6mm.
Ship equipment: An iron anchor, 2m long, with a rope ring, 20cm long, was found about 20m away.

Name: Çamalti Burnu 1
Reference: http://www.nautarch.org/camalti.htm        "Marmara Adasi, Camalti Burnu I Batigi-1999/2000", XXIII. Kazi Sonuclari Sempozyumu, Ankara, 2002, p. 381-390     "Camalti Burnu I Batigi", Bogazici Universitesi, 2002 Sualti Bilim ve Teknolojisi Toplantisi, Istanbul, (2002), p. 51-54         "Camalti Burnu I Wreck - 98/99 Field Seasons", VIIth International Symposium on Ship Construction in Antiquity, Tropis VII (Atina), 2002, p. 391-399; N. Gunsenin, Anatalia Antiqua IX (2001), 117-133;  Anatolia Antiqua XI, Paris (2003), 361-376
Comments: Over an area 42m x 18m, at least 800 stamped amphorae have been found on a 25m long merchant ship that had 2 masts and a half deck. The amphorae on this wreck have been dated to the thirteenth century , placing them among the last amphorae in large-scale commercial use. Some of them had stamps and graffitti and wooden stoppers.
Other cargo: Other types of storage jars and two or three dozen broken anchors destined to be repaired or used as scrap iron
Hull remains: Poorly preserved due to marine organisms. Only 1m of the keel, a few frame segments, a short length of bilge wale and the traceable remains of perhaps 6 strakes.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Various high quality ceramics including one handled jars, cooking pots, decorated glazed plates, a sgraffito plate and a cup.
Ship equipment: Three anchors, 2 Y type and 1 T type.

Name: Cape Qefalit
Reference: INA Annual 2008,  22.
Comments: A 15 x 6m ovoid mound, 0.5 m high with a scatter of amphorae protruding from its surface, the site was probably damaged by drag nets

Name: Bozburun Julio-Claudian
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/julioclaud.html         J. Royal, IJNA 35 (2006), 195-218
Comments: A large amphora mound measuring 15 x 5m although it is hard to discerna stacking pattern as the upper amphorae are tumbled and there is a large amount of marine growth covering the site.

Name: Bozburun Late Antiquity anchor
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/lateantiquity.html            J. Royal, IJNA 35 (2006), 195-218
Comments: An oval shaped amphora deposit measuring 9 x 3m with 2  collections of anchors about 4m to the west and northwest of the amphorae.
Ship equipment: There are at least 9, and possibly 11, anchors located in 2 deposits suggesting they were in their stowed postitions at the time of sinking. Seven have clearly discernable arms, six of which are of a cruciform shape (cf Dramont F and Yassi Ada wrecks). Only one has a 2m anchor stock

Name: Comlek Burun
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/comlek.html           J. Royal, IJNA 35 (2006), 195-218
Comments: A mound of at least 3 layers of amphorae, 10 x 3m,  with an anchor at one end
Ship equipment: A grapnel anchor about 1.5m long, with large triangular flukes and a crescent-shaped crown that curves downwards towards its arms, typical of C12th AD.

Name: Bozburun Late Republican
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/laterepublicanwreck.htm               J. Royal, IJNA 37 (2008), 88-97
Comments: A badly damaged mound of amphorae measuring 10 x 8m, rising to 0.5-0.75m, although many are still in their upright position in the sand, suggesting that the hull may be preserved underneath.
Hull remains: Probable, still buried underneath the amphorae.

Name: Levanzo I
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/levanzowreck.htm; http://www.rpmnautical.org/egadi08.htm
Comments: The site is orientated E-W, comprising a mound 30-40cm high and 12 x 5 m in dimension. Numerous sherds but few complete amphorae which suggests that fish-net dragging has damaged the site. It appears that the ship was at least c. 15-20m long and 5-6m wide.
Other cargo: Numerous tubi fitilli (vaulting tubes), at least 100 of which were visible on the surface. Shape and sizes are consistent, c. 13.5 x 5.5 cm but  they are crudely formed and produced from poor-quality clay.
Hull remains: Several long, narrow concreted objects have the appearance of hull timbers, 2m long and orientated parallel to the central axis of the site, suggesting that they are stringers. Two other curved concretions are possibly the remains of framing timbers
Shipboard paraphernalia: An intact flacon, a well-preserved plate with a raised rim and a small table amphora.
Ship equipment: Other concretions may well be the remains of ship's fastenings or fragments. Two in  particular may be steelyards as a concreted small chain is wrapped around their length.

Name: Mazotos
Reference: http://www.cyprus-mail.com/news/main.php?id=39503&cat_id=1            http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/66/
Comments: The Antiquities Department said it was one of the very few shipwrecks off Cypriot waters of the Classical period to have been found in such a good state of preservation.

Name: Montalto di Castro
Reference: B. Davidde, IJNA 31 (2002), 84
Comments: A cargo of amphorae that has been covered with sheets of metal and fibre glass to protect it until excavation.

Name: Lerici
Reference: B. Davidde,  IJNA  31 (2002),  86; G. Martino, Archaeologia maritima mediterranea 6 (2009)
Marble type: A cargo of columns.

Name: Santo Stefano al Mare
Reference: G. Martino, Archeologia maritima Mediterranea 2007, 45-51         http://www.nautilustdc.com/?id=31
Comments: A mound of amphorae, 15-20m x 5-8m, marked the site of a medium-sized merchant ship, with the amphorae still in their original upright position. Excavated in 2006.
Hull remains: Hull remains may still be buried underneath the amphorae.

Name: Marciano Marina
Reference: http://www.legambientearcipelagotoscano.it/localmente/storia/scoperte.htm
Comments: Other cargo and the hull are probably still buried underneath, and the ship is estimated to have been between 20 and 30m long.

Name: Sant'Andrea A
Reference: http://www.legambientearcipelagotoscano.it/localmente/storia/archeologia.htm

Name: Sant'Andrea B
Reference: http://www.legambientearcipelagotoscano.it/localmente/storia/archeologia.htm

Name: Punta La Cera
Reference: http://www.legambientearcipelagotoscano.it/localmente/storia/archeologia.htm
Comments: It appears that this wreck was a large ship of 35-40 m long carrying  a total of 5-7000 amphorae.

Name: Porto Palo di Capo Passero
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 458  Basile 1997
Shipboard paraphernalia: A louterion of clay with its stand.

Name: Gela B
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 458; F. Facenna, in  Atti del Convegno Nazionale di Archeologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996, (1997), 143-146.
Comments: Survey of the hull began in 1997.
Hull remains: Mortise and tenon technique seen in the hull construction although there is at least one sewn repair. The hull is protected by ballast stones cf Gela A.

Name: Capo Linaro
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 459; Petriaggi, Naxos 1997.
Comments: Dolia
Hull remains: The hull is about 5m long and in good condition.

Name: Toscana Cala del Barbiere
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 460; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 50
Comments: Discovered by Lamboglia in the 1970s but excavated in the 90s. A large ship with an interesting cargo from diverse parts of the Mediterranean.
Hull remains: Mortise and tenons join the hull planks and are reinforced with nails.

Name: Secche della Meloria
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 460; S. Bargagliotti et al, Atti del Convegno Nazionale di Archeologia Subacquea. Anzio 1996, (1997), 43-53.
Comments: Could be two wrecks, but one is described as being a group of ceramic blocks and concreted amphorae.
Other cargo: Black-glazed pottery

Name: Alghero 1
Reference: C. Beltrame, Vita di Bordo in Eta Romana, 2002, p. 460; P Spanu (personal communication to Beltrame).

Name: Caprara
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html        site 128  area 1
Comments: A Roman wreck from the island of Caprara, Tremiti Islands. Although there are few amphorae, they are close to the piles of tiles suggesting they were part of the cargo
Other cargo: Two piles of tiles still in stacked position. The tiles have a form typical of the Roman period, with the dimensions of approximately 40 cm x 30 cm, with a flat surface and raised edges on the longer two sides. The concretions which cover this material mean it is impossible to identify any stamps.

Name: Napoli A
Reference: D. Giampola et al, Archeologia Maritima Mediterranea (2005), 63-91; C.  Capretti et al, Archaeometry 50 (2008), 855-876
Comments: The 3 Napoli ships, A, B and C were found during construction work for the underground and are well preserved due to their submersion in mud and silt.
Hull remains: Excellent condition. The remains of the hull measure 11.77m by 3.32m wide and were coated in resin. Many repairs can be seen.

Name: Napoli B
Dating: end of C1st- beg C2nd AD
Reference: D. Giampola et al, Archeologia maritima Mediterranea (2005), 63-91; C.  Capretti et al, Archaeometry 50 (2008), 855-876
Comments: Although fairly well preserved, this ship is not as intact as Napoli A.
Hull remains: The intact hull remains measure 8m by 2m.

Name: Napoli C
Reference: D. Giampola et al, Archeologia maritima Mediterranea (2005), 63-91; C.  Capretti et al, Archaeometry 50 (2008), 855-876
Comments: This ship was probably used only for loading and unloading within the port of Naples.
Hull remains: Excellent remains, measuring 13.2m by 3.7m.

Name: Gallipoli (BA)
