Reference: http://www.bertucco.com/le_notizie_complete_di_spiaggia61.htm                                                                                                  http://www.archeosub.it/news2004/news0407.htm#gallipoli                                                                                                                                                                http://www.calypsosub.it/archeorelitti/334-anfore-coprono-relitto-romano
Comments: A mound of concreted amphorae about 8m wide had already been looted by the time the wreck was discovered officially. It is estimated that the ship was carrying more than 30,000 litres of wine.
Hull remains: Hopefully there are hull remains underneath the amphorae.

Name: Punta Penne C
Reference: F. Zongolo, Atti del Convegno Nazionale de Archeologia Subacquea: Antium May-June 1996 (1997), 245-249.
Comments: This may be an anchorage rather than a wreck site.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two bronze lamps, one in the shape of a foot with a satyr (?) playing the flute, the other with handles mounted on a cross and the sides in the shape of a lion
Ship equipment: 300 lead rings; a millstone; a bronze steelyard with a small bronze bust of Minerva.

Name: Grado (2000)
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2000/news0007.htm
Comments: Found near the other Grado wreck, the wreck was carrying Sicilian and central Italian amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Graeco-Italic amphora
Ship equipment: Two lead anchor stocks of 150kg.

Name: Ecueil de Miet 3
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 51; L. Long, P. Pomey and J-C Souriseau, Les Etrusques en Mer (2000)
Comments: Shattered remains of Etruscan amphorae from a site with at least 3 other wrecks.

Name: Bateguier/ Le Batiguier
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1993, 52; S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 104-05.
Comments: A probable cargo of at least 1000 objects first investigated in thee 1970s and re-examined in the 1990s.
Other cargo: An extensive amount of pottery - ewers, water jugs, dishes etc. decorated with a great variety of designs, sometimes with Arabic graffiti. A very rare lamp with 7 openings. Millstones. Copper cauldrons. They seemed to have been transported in large earthenware jars without handles, decorated with digitated friezes.
Hull remains: At least 20 x 6m very well preserved of this flat-bottomed ship, rarely found in the Mediterranean cf Agay and Serce Limani wrecks. Frame-first construction.
Ship equipment: Anchors.

Name: La Mauresque
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1993, 25;

Name: Anse de Montfort 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1995, 35;
Comments: One of several ancient wrecks found in very shallow waters in the northern section of L'Etang de Bages-Sigean, also known as Anse de Montfort.

Name: Anse de Montfort 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1995, 35;
Comments: One of several ancient wrecks found in very shallow waters in the northern section of L'Etang de Bages-Sigean, also known as Anse de Montfort. This deposit of amphorae carrying traces of soot along with blackened fragments of wood suggests  a ship that sank due to fire.

Name: Port Vendres 9 (Redoute Bear 2)
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2000, 40-1; Bilan Scientifique 2001, 4; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 36
Comments: A site comprising 5 layers of which 2 seem to be a shipwreck of the first half of the C5th AD.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Glass ware, eastern Med ceramics
Ship equipment: Ballast stones (siliceous sandstone)

Name: Les Riches Dunes 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 40
Other cargo: 17 lead ingots

Name: Les Riches Dunes 6
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 41

Name: Maguelone
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 56; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 39.
Other cargo: 12 copper ingots and an iron bar stamped with HAEDI cf Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 2.
Ship equipment: An iron anchor

Name: Port Vendres 11
Reference: S. Got Castellvi and M. Amandry, Bilan Scientifique 2005, 33-34
Shipboard paraphernalia: 1100 coins in 3 portions of 471, 249 and 62 pieces, plus 249 scattered coins in various states of preservation. They had probably been contained in material or leather bags which have since disappeared. They were not great value coins so may have belonged to one of the crew. They can be dated to AD 270-274.

Name: Banc du Benedetto
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1997, 86

Name: Les Moines 3
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 77
Comments: Scattered remains of a cargo of Gauloise 4 amphorae.
Other cargo: Three lead ingots (type Domergue 1)were found nearby.

Name: La Vacca, Iles Cerbicales
Reference: H. Bernard, Bilan Scientifique 1999, 77
Other cargo: Millstone.

Name: Coscia
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 96

Name: Punta Vecchia 1
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 96; Bilan Scientifique  2004, 87; Bilan Scientifique  2005, 88
Comments: Scattered sherds from Spanish amphorae

Name: Est Perduto 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique  2005, 96-97
Comments: A site measuring 20 x 12m of various amphorae and ceramics.
Other cargo: A large amount of Campanian ceramics - plates, bowls and cups.

Name: Mazarron 1
Reference: I. Negueruela, J. Pinedo et al, IJNA 24 (1995), 189-197  and 30 (2001); Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 41-45.          http://inadiscover.com/projects/all/southern_europe_mediterranean_aegean/mazarron_timber_study_spain/introduction/            http://www2.rgzm.de/navis/ships/Ship058/Ship058Engl.htm
Comments: A small C 7th BC ship discovered in 1994 during the building of a marina on the Playa de la Isla and excavated in 1999. The ship measured only 5.5 x 1.3m but 7,500 artefacts have been recovered, the majority of which may have been the crew's possessions.  The planks of the hull are joined with pegged mortises and tenons; the frames of the ship, however, are lashed. In addition, the edges of the planks are beveled and sewn. The Mazarrón 1 appears to be an extremely important transitional ship for the study and understanding of shipbuilding evolution in antiquity.
Other cargo: Urns, baskets, mortars, religious objects and carafes.
Hull remains: Well preserved hull buried under a thin layer of sand. Some keel fragments were preserved measuring 4m and 9 planks were attached to the hull by mortise and tenon joints. The hull was coated in resin. Several pieces of petrified rope were also discovered.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Flat and round-bottomed plates, pots and pans. A finely crafted silver scarab ring and a bronze spear.

Name: Mazarron 2
Reference: Master Seafarers: the Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 42-49.    http://www2.rgzm.de/navis/ships/Ship058/Ship058Engl.htm
Comments: The ship was discovered in 1994 near Mazarron 1 during the building of a marina on the Playa de la Isla and examined in 1999, although not fully excavated. A protective covering has been constructed around it.
Other cargo: Lead ingots.
Hull remains: The ship's anchor, rudder and mast housing were brought to the surface, the rest of the well-preserved hull still lies on the sea floor. It was constructed by mortise and tenon joints and the interior was coated with resin.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A wooden-handled basket and 2 pieces of a grinding wheel. Animal bones include those from goats, rabbits and chickens.
Ship equipment: The ship's anchor was found near the the bow together with the rope that once held it.

Name: Alonnisos
Reference: E. Hadjidaki, BCH 120 (1996), 561-593; Master Seafarers: The Phoenicians and the Greeks (Periplus, 2004), 112-113.
Comments: A Classical wreck carrying at least 3 layers of amphorae was found near the island of Peristea.The wreck site covers an a rea 30 x 10m from which more than 4000 well preserved wine amphorae were found. The layering of the cargo gives a good idea of the route taken, Athenina pottery at the bottom, with the amphorae on top. The presence of carbon suggest that the ship sank due to fire, although it may also have been overloaded.
Other cargo: High quality black-glazed pottery, the best of which came from Athens, including skyphoi, cups decorated with petals, drinking vessels. Heavy terracotta mortars with 2 handles, a large base and a thick rounded lip. Bowls with black-glazed bases from southern Italy.
Hull remains: Bronze nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: An elegant pitcher, a chytra and a number of metal objects.
Ship equipment: 2 lead cross bars from an anchor

Name: Ekinlik Adasi Marble wreck
Reference: http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm          INA Quarterly 26 No. 3 (1999), 18-23
Comments: The importance of this find is that it is the first Late Antiquity wreck discovered with a cargo of marble presumably  from the nearby marble quarries of the Marmara Island.
Marble type: At least 17 columns, some broken, presumably from Proconnesus.

Name: Parco di Teodorico, Ravenna
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004),  79, 86-88; R. Petriaggi and B. Davidde, Archeologia Sott'Acqua (2007), 57-8
Comments: The ship was embedded in sand about 8.5m below the modern land level and excavated from 1998. One of the last examples of shell-first ship construction.
Hull remains: A well preserved ship (7.22  x 2.75m preserved out of probable 9 x 3.1m), the mortises were surprisingly cut 80cm apart and were no longer fastened with wooden pegs, thus showing an early move away from edge-joinery. The hull was coated with pitch.

Name: Carmel Coast
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004),  83
Comments: The ship was wrecked with a hoard of early C6 th AD coins minted in Constantinople, Nicomedia and Antioch.
Ship equipment: 2 sounding leads of elongated bell shap with lugs on their apexes designed to take a length of rope. One is 14cm high with a weight of 3.05kg, the other 23cm high, weighing 11kg. Both are incised with a Maltese Christian Cross and the Greek letter 'P', and one also has an assymetrical zigzag shaped engraving, interpreted as a heavenly navigational aid.

Name: Nord-Fouras
Reference: S. Kingsley, Barbarian Seas: Late Rome to Islam (Periplus, 2004), 106
Comments: Excavated in the 1990s, this Islamic ship was carrying only 200-300 trade items.
Other cargo: Millstones
Hull remains: Nails

Name: Ashkelon North Late Roman
Hull remains: Numerous bronze nails
Shipboard paraphernalia: A lead cooking pot with a capacity of about 40l, a marble weight and scales.
Ship equipment: Two anchors bearing Greek inscriptions, one made of stone with 2 perforations and the other of marble with 3 perforations. Three sounding leads

Name: Ashkelon North Byzantine
Other cargo: Handles of lead and bronze vessels soje with incised designs. Dozens of bronze coins of the 40 numia denomination of the Constantinople and Nicomedia mints, bearing the bust of Justin and his wife Sofia.
Hull remains: Iron and bronze nails.
Ship equipment: Iron anchors, 2 sounding leads decorated with crosses.

Name: Tel Ashqelon
Comments: A radiocarbon test on remains of charred wood surviving in one of the ingots dates the wreck.
Other cargo: Lead, including dozens of loaf-shaped ingots (80-100 kg each). Most bear inscriptions that have yet to be deciphered. Next to the ingots were 3 elongated pieces of iron (8 x 10 x 50cm) whose function is unclear.

Name: Tel Ashqelon Byzantine
Comments: There are many wrecks in the area but they are difficult to separate - bronze nails, lead sheathing, amphora sherds from C5th-4th BC to C 4th-6th AD and anchors of different dates have all been found several hundred metres offshore.
Other cargo: Round millstones (diam 0.6m, thickness 0.3m).
Hull remains: Bronze nails, square in section.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coins from the Byzantine period.
Ship equipment: Lead fittings of anchors and lead pipes.

Name: 'Akko West
Comments: A medium-sized vessel. It's not certain whether ceramic remains formed part of the cargo of this ship or another, but include amphorae, everyday pottery and Western Terra Sigillata bowls which are rarely found on land. Many other miscellaneous finds (coins, glass, ceramics, hull remains, metal objects) indicate that many ships were wrecked in the area over many centuries.
Hull remains: Framing timbers, sheathing, various wooden parts and bronze nails with a quare cross section and a flat head were found. Carbon 14 analysis dates the European pine wood to 144-213 AD and 147-250 AD. Mortise and tenon joints were used.

Name: Cape Tiha
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A looted wreck, although dispersed finds are known from private collections.

Name: Cape Borova
Reference: M. Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: Finds from this site are known from illegal exports confiscated by customs officers!
Shipboard paraphernalia: Parts of a loutherion.

Name: Veli Porat
Reference: M . Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: A looted cargo of amphorae with some cabin ware of Eastern Sigilatta A - the only example from the Adriatic.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Eastern Sigilatta A pottery

Name: Le Formiche di Capraia
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 50           http://www.promare.org/project_capraiashipwreck.html
Comments: The  60 x 40 m site is extremely well preserved possibly due to a thick layer of seagrass. The absence of an amphora mound suggests that the main cargo may have been perishable, or else the main part of the wreck is still to be found.
Other cargo: Black-glazed pottery from central Italy, including plates, cups and bowls.
Hull remains: Several copper and iron nails testify to the presence of wooden planks in this spot on the seafloor
Shipboard paraphernalia: Some diagnostic artefacts such as a bronze Roman coin with representation of a ship's bow. dated to the first half of the second century B.C.,  one black-glazed guttus, and a well-preserved oil-lamp  were found also during the 2009 campaign. Two lead fishing-weights (one left on the seafloor), found close to the bronze coin and in association with a little bronze blade might represent evidence of an ancient fishing net lost on this site, with the necessary tools ready to clean the newly-caught fish

Name: Golfo di Follonica
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 51

Name: Siciliano (Porto San Paolo)
Reference: R. D'Oriano, Bollettino di Archaeolgia 46-48 (1997), 81-82; E. Riccardi, Bollettino di Archaeolgia 46-48 (1997), 82-86; G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 104
Other cargo: Ceramics: Ostia III 267 and Ostia I 17 plates
Hull remains: Two sections of the hull are preserved, part of the bottom (5.65m of the keel) and part of the right side; some lead sheathing and repairs. The ship measured between 15 and 20m long and was built with great care.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Part of an oil lamp and a coin dated to the C2nd, pointing to the long history of the ship; ceramics and part of a bronze pin.

Name: Baia Salinedda (San Teodoro)
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 104              http://www.icimar.it/museo/relitto_baia_salinedda.htm
Comments: The remains of a ship and its contents spread over an area approximately 14.7m x 4m excavared in the 1990s.
Other cargo: Ceramics, glass and metal?
Hull remains: Three sections reamin: the larger fragment (4.7 x 1.95 m) consists of nine exterior planks, another fragment comes from the ceiling, while another section is of frames and shell plating covering an area of 2.6 m x 2m.  The predominant species of wood used for the construction are those so-called Mediterranean pines (Pinus pinaster, Pinus halepensis), although oak and olive are also found.

Name: Rena Maiore
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 104
Other cargo: Lead ingots, many of them stamped.

Name: Olbia (statue)
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 104
Comments: Discovered in 1990.
Other cargo: Fragments of a terracotta statue of Hercules.

Name: Cala Gadir II
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 126; P. Selvaggio and S. Tusa, IJNA 38 (2009), 417-420
Comments: Finds have been found over a very wide area down to a depth of 100m. However , this seems to be a wreck site datable to the late C2nd to beginning C1st BC. Two hundred amphorae from this wreck are now exhibited in the Castle of Pantelleria.

Name: Capo Passero II
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 126
Comments: Discovered in 2006
Other cargo: Lead ingots probably from Spain each weighing about 30kg and stamped with the manufacturer's mark

Name: Favignana
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 126
Comments: A rare C 10th Sicilian/Arab shipwreck, practically intact, carrying various amphorae and ceramics, as well as bricks and tiles.
Other cargo: Bricks and tiles "a coppa".

Name: Scauri
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 126                 http://www.regione.sicilia.it/beniculturali/archeologiasottomarina/prod_editoriali/op_scras/Opuscolo%20SCRAS-Pag%2023_31.pdf
Comments: Discovered in 1997 and excavated in 1999, a cargo of ceramics on baord a ship that may have sunk due to an onboard fire.
Other cargo: Ceramics - cylindrical pots, bowls and cups; glass bottles and beakers in fragments. Oil lamps and some Sigillata Africana D
Hull remains: Few remains
Shipboard paraphernalia: Numerous remains of wildlife (especially teeth) including goat. A silver ring decorated with a piece of green glass.

Name: Marausa Lido
Reference: G. Lattanzi, Navi e Citta Sommerse (2007), 127            http://www.infcom.it/subarcheo/marausa.html                              http://www.regione.sicilia.it/beniculturali/archeologiasottomarina/prod_editoriali/op_scras/Opuscolo%20SCRAS-Pag%2023_31.pdf
Hull remains: Extensive hull remains that give the ship's length an estimate of 20-30m.

Name: Ocaklar Burnu
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 310
Comments: Ganos (Gazikoy) on the northern coast of the Propontis produced amphorae in the Byzantine period.

Name: Çihli Burnu
Reference: http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm

Name: Tekmezar Burnu 1
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 311-12;  INA Quarterly 26 No. 3 (1999), 18-23                   http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Comments: A  site covering an area 40m x 20m, this is one of the most important and largest shipwrecks from the Byzantine period. Three layers of amphorae can be clearly seen with 1 sq m containing 27 amphorae leading to an estimated 20,000 amphorae in total. Estimated length of ship, 15.36m.
Other cargo: Three tonnes of glass.
Ship equipment: Six Y type anchors.

Name: Tekmezar Burnu 2
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 311-12;  INA Quarterly 26 No. 3 (1999), 18-23                http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Comments: Over an area of 15 x 12m, 12m west of Tekmezar Burnu were found at least 2 layers of amphorae (total estimate 3000?).
Ship equipment: Two Y type anchors

Name: Kocayemi?ilik
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 312; http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Ship equipment: Two Y type anchors were found in the middle of a small group of amphorae at 35m.

Name: Anata?  Adacik (Palapetra)
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 312         http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Ship equipment: A Y type anchor

Name: Kuyu Burnu Tile wreck
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 312;    http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Comments: A cargo of tiles
Other cargo: Tiles measuring 80 x 45cm x 3cm.
Ship equipment: Two anchors date the site.

Name: Kuçuk Ada
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 312-15           http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Comments: Dated by a single amphora found amongst the tiles.
Other cargo: Terracotta pipes  in 2 piles 38.6 x 5.1m and 26.3 x 20.4m at the 2 different depths.

Name: Ta?ada (Virankoy)
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 315         http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm

Name: Saraylar (E?ek Adalari)
Reference: N. Gunsenin, Archaeonautica 14 (1998), 315                http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two amphorae and a jug.
Ship equipment: A Y type anchor.

Name: Tell Hreiz 1
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 98
Comments: A cargo of large bottle green glass lumps was found.
Other cargo: Glass lumps.

Name: Tell Hreiz II
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 98
Other cargo: About 50 loaf-shaped iron bars.
Hull remains: Wooden keel.
Ship equipment: A 2-armed iron anchor

Name: Atlit North Bay I
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 99
Comments: Two assemblages which may have belonged to a ship which bore the bronze battering ram found in the past (Fig. 196:29; HA 76:43).
Other cargo: Decorated bronze handles of large vessels.
Shipboard paraphernalia: One assemblage - a round basalt millstone with remains of iron and lead attachments, a lead bullet bearing an animal figure in relief (lizard?). The other assemblage - several dozen small Ptolemaic bronze coins, a bronze bracelet,
Ship equipment: A square lead weight (5 x5cm) inscribed in Greek, 2 conical lead weights

Name: Nahal Oren
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 99
Other cargo: Bronze furniture/works of art? - bronze attachments of a bed with remains of wood, a stylized bronze handle of a container and  adecorated gold plaque.

Name: Atlit North Bay II
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 99
Comments: A group of objects stuck together by oxidation.
Hull remains: Iron nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A socketed bronze standard decorated in relief with a trellis of vine tendrils and bunches of grapes on both sides, with an incised 7-branched menora, a shofar, a palm branch and an inscription mentioning the city of Shiqmona. A framed bronze figurine of a woman carrying flowers, bronze parts of a suspension scale.
Ship equipment: Four wooden objects to splice ropes.

Name: Newe Yam Late Bronze Age
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 100
Comments: A large cargo of copper ingots.
Other cargo: 83 loaf-shaped copper bars (3-5kg).
Shipboard paraphernalia: A socketed spearhead with wood remains, bronze tongs
Ship equipment: A series of hematite weights in the shape of wheat grains, a bronze adze. Several stone anchors with one perforation (80-150kg).

Name: Newe Yam Hellenistic
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 100
Shipboard paraphernalia: Several Ptolemaic bronze coins, cylindrical lead bands bearing incised Greek inscriptions. Lead boxes with lids and a bronze figurine of a satyr.
Ship equipment: Two bell-shaped sounding leads, pyramidical lead weights.

Name: Newe Yam Roman
Reference: E. Galili and Y. Sharvit, "Underwater survey in the Mediterranean", ESI vol.19 (1999), 100
Comments: Found near the Hellenistic  wreck
Hull remains: Lead sheathing
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two lead pots with lids.
Ship equipment: Two iron anchors with 2 arms and 2 iron stocks.

Name: Fiumicino 1 (Natante 2)
Reference: G. Boetto, Archaeonautica 15 (2008), 29-62.
Comments: Abandoned in antiquity in a remote part of the port, a heavily repaired navis caudicaria  that has been difficult to date but now looks likely as later, C4th-5th AD?
Hull remains: Preserved length of 13.83m and width of 4,57m and height of 1.45m. 13 outer planks and 42 frames are preserved, hull first with irregular mortise and tenon conctruction. Flat bottomed with a stream-lined prow  and tangential nails, adapted form a sea-going vessel to suit the needs of river haulage. Many repairs had been carried out even to the keel (cf Jules Verne 3 and 4 C1st-2nd AD and Napoli A and C late C1st AD). The mast-step was placed quite far forward towards the prow suggesting mainly river use. Built locally

Name: Okuklje Cove
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 50
Comments: A 'problematical' find, reflecting the widespread vertical distance of the cargo of probable Dr 6 amphorae.

Name: Duboka Cove
Reference: M. Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Shipboard paraphernalia: An oval amphora inscribed with BDEUNOR points towards the presence of African merchants managing the shipment.

Name: Cavtat 2
Reference: M. Jurisic in D. Davison, V. Gaffney and E. Martin (eds.) BAR 2006, 175-192
Comments: Largest cargo  found in the Adriatic now protected by an iron cage.

Name: Mandriola A
Reference: P. Spanu, Tharros Felix-2 (2006), 181ff
Comments: A late Roman Spanish/African cargo, similar to Cala Reale (L'Asinara ) wreck.
Other cargo: Many fragments of African table ware

Name: Cala Su Pallosu
Reference: E. Solinas and I. 147-Sanna, Tharros Felix-2 (2006), 147-151; D Salvi, Tharros Felix-2 (2006), 154-160.
Comments: A cargo of millstones, some glass and cups.
Other cargo: Millstones - 4 lower cone-shaped parts (metae) and 5 upper parts (catilli). Glass. Cups.

Name: Sa Tonnara A
Reference: E. Sechi, Tharros-Felix 2 (2006), 164 ff.
Comments: Amphorae of these types had previously been brought to the surface without excavation of the site in the 1970s and 80s. It seems reasonable to assume that this is a site of a shipwreck.

Name: Ventotene 1
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/italy/ventotene_2009_season.html
Comments: A very well preserved shipwreck with cargo of mixed Spanish amphorae from Baetica carrying garum (Roman fish sauce) measuring approximately 15 metres long by 5 metres wide. The height of the amphorae, many if which are still stacked in their original position, is of just over two metres. One amphora was brought up to the surface.

Name: Ventotene 2
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/italy/ventotene_2009_season.html
Comments: A very well preserved shipwreck with cargo of Italian wine amphorae (from Campania) measuring approximately 18 metres long and 5 metres wide. The height of the amphorae, many if which are still stacked in their original position, is of just over two metres.

Name: Ventotene 3
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/italy/ventotene_2009_season.html
Comments: Shipwreck with mixed cargo of mortaria (mortars) and Italian wine amphorae (from Campania) measuring approximately 13 metres long and 4 metres wide. The height of the mortaria pile is approximately one metre. Some amphorae can be observed emerging from under the pile of mortaria. Although divided into two this site is very well preserved. Four mortaria were brought to the surface.

Name: Ventotene 4
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/italy/ventotene_2009_season.html
Comments: Shipwreck with mixed cargo of Italian wine amphorae, glass frit, metal bars and as yet unidentified cylindrical objects. This site measures approximately 20 metres long and 5 metres wide and is relatively flat (not more that 50 cm off the seabed). Although not as complete as the first three sites the objects from this shipwreck are relatively well preserved.

Name: Ventotene 5
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/italy/ventotene_2009_season.html
Comments: a very well preserved shipwreck with a cargo of North African amphorae (carrying garum) measuring approximately 12 metres long and 4 metres wide. The height of the amphorae, many if which are still stacked in their original position, is of just over two metres.

Name: Cartagena
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/spain/spain_2007_exploration.html
Comments: Pieces of ceramics formed a trail which led to a large homogeneous pile of amphorae stacked over two meters high.

Name: Malta (2006)
Reference: http://www.auroratrust.com/projects/malta/malta_exploration_2008.html
Comments: Scattered remains of a wreck of amphorae

Name: Rodon
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/rodon.htm
Comments: Over 3km from shore

Name: Qefalit Tile wreck
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/qefalit.htm   INA Annual 2008, 23
Comments: A fairly well preserved cargo of roofing tiles found 7km off shore measuring 15m by 6m
Other cargo: The tile cargo is still stacked and forms an interlocking and compacted deposit. Pan and cover tiles are present of Corinthiam manufacture measuring 29 x 20 inches.

Name: Butrint 2
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/butrint2.htm

Name: Butrint 3
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/butrint3.htm
Comments: A badly damaged wreck of Corinthian amphorae

Name: Butrint 1
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/sbutrint1.htm             INA Annual 2008 29-31
Comments: Located about 50m offshore, the cargo of this wreck is scattered and buried down a silt-laden incline, although most of the amphorae are situated at the bottom. Excavation is ongoing.
Ship equipment: A removable lead anchor stock 0.8m is possibly part of the same wreck.

Name: Tilegrafo Bay
Reference: http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?5
Comments: Eight  wrecks were discovered dating to the late Roman and Byzantine periods. One of these, Wreck 7, was considered worth investigating more thoroughly. Wreck 7 is located in Tilegrafo Bay, 5 nautical miles south of Amaliapoli, and dates to the late 4th c. of the Christian era, i.e. the later Roman period. This is a significant wreck, preserved in reasonably good condition, carrying wine amphorae of at least five different types. One of the four  was previously unknown to archaeologists.

Name: Korakia (Porto heli)
Reference: http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?3

Name: Vlychos (Hydra)
Reference: http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?3

Name: Trikeri
Reference: http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?3

Name: Metochi
Reference: http://www.ienae.gr/e107EN/page.php?3

Name: Saranda 1
Reference: http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28963784/
Comments: A 20-inch long pottery jar, or amphora, used to transport wine and olive oil, and a smaller version found 260 feet deep were probably made in the southern Greek city of Corinth, in the 6th or early 5th centuries B.C. Both were recovered from a merchant ship that sank 1.8 miles off shore. Albanian archaeologist Adrian Anastasi said if the 6th century B.C. dating is confirmed, it would be only the fifth of its kind found in the world.

Name: Saranda 2
Reference: http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28963784/
Comments: a 4th century B.C. amphora and roof tiles

Name: Saranda 3
Reference: http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28963784/
Comments: north African jar from the 1st to 3rd centuries A.D.

Name: Saranda 4
Reference: http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/28963784/
Comments: stone ship's anchor of the 2nd-1st century B.C

Name: Boka Kotorska 2
Reference: J. Royal, INA Annual 2008 26-28; http://www.rpmnautical.org/bokakotorska2.htm
Comments: This Roman ship was found over 2km off shore , covering an area 20 x 17m, with many of its amphorae in their original stacked position.

Name: La Yuca Beach
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSP006.htm
Comments:
a Roman trade vessel carrying a cargo of marble statues and architectural elements, sunk off la Yuca beach near Benalmadena (Malaga) between the II and the III Century A.D. The cargo was probably destined to the construction of a temple beyond the Gibraltar Strait. the most interesting findings were the pieces of a  marble sculpture representing Artemis (above): the restored sculpture is now exposed in the Museum of Benalmadena. 
Some remains of the cargo still lie at a depth of -4m, 80m from the coast.

Name: Rompetimones rock
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSP007.htm
Comments: Parts of a  large bronze statue (left), representing the Emperor Augustus have been recovered near the dangerous seiche known as Rompetimones (rudder-breaker), off Sancti Petri Island, near Cadiz. The bust, dressed with a rich armour, a leg and a hand were recovered from a depth of -2m.

Name: Ship of Tarragona
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSP008.htm
Comments:
The ancient Ship of Tarragona was a Roman trade vessel carrying a cargo of marble columns and architectural elements, sunk off "the Miracle Beach" near Tarragona between the first and the second Century A.D. 
The cargo has been recovered and is now exhibited in Tarragona Museum

Name: Sant Jordi
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSP013.htm              M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252         D. Colls, L'Epave de la Colonia de Sant Jordi 1 (Majorque) 1987
Comments: The ancient wreck known as the Ship of Sant Jordi 1 was a Roman trade vessel, carrying a cargo of amphorae, sunk near Sant Jordi (Mallorca Island) possibly between 100 and 80 B.C. Several archaeological campaigns have been brougt on since 1987, and a part of the cargo and fragments of the hull have been recovered.
Hull remains: Fragments
Ship equipment: A bobbin wooden toggle, possibly part of a fishing reel.

Name: Pegli
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksLI002.htm

Name: Seno del Campese
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksTI001.htm
Comments: An Etruscan trade vessel, sunk in Seno del Campese (Giglio Island) during the VII Century B.C. A number of terra-cotta oil lamps  and interesting Etruscan pottery samples  have been recovered from the wreck.

Name: Cala del Diavolo
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksTI002.htm
Comments: A Roman trade vessel carrying a cargo of wine in Lamboglia 2 amphorae, and black Campanian pottery.
Other cargo: Black Campanian pottery
Ship equipment: A beautiful encrusted iron anchor was recovered from the wreck

Name: Polyaigos
Reference: http://www.balkantravellers.com/en/read/article/1720              http://www.in.gr/news/article.asp?IngEntityID=1099326&IngDtrID=253
Comments: The shipwreck, first spotted in 2004, was initially explored by underwater archaeologists in the fall of 2009. These excavations resulted in the discovery of valuable archaeological objects, including amphorae, ceramic vases and fragments of the vessel’s anchor. At least three types of amphorae were identified, one of which originated from ancient Peparithos (the island of Skopelos), while the others were closely identified with Classical Era amphorae workshops of the northern Aegean.
Other cargo: Ceramic vases
Ship equipment: Parts of the ship's anchor were also found

Name: La Manga (Bajo de la Campana)
Reference: http://inadiscover.com/projects/all/southern_europe_mediterranean_aegean/bajo_de_la_campana_wrecks_spain/introduction/    M. Polzer, INA Quarterly 36.3 (2009), 10
Comments: Over 1400 objects have been collected from this wreck between Grosa Island and El Farallon Island. Two other wrecks have also been found at the site, a Punic one  (2nd century B.C.), and a Roman one (1st century A.D.) though Phoenician material predominated
Other cargo: A cargo of ivory, amber and many ceramic objects. The 10 ivory tusks measure between 70 and 150 cm long and are inscribed with Phoenician writing. They have come from a race of elephants now thought to be extinct. Also on board were 28 small tin ingots, 2 copper ingots, hundres of galena (lead ore) nuggets) and stones containing silver and lead, and plates, bowls, several double-sided wooden combs, ivory knife handles, bronze needles and chandeliers.
Hull remains: Some of the hull timbers have been recovered, and the ship is estimated to have been c 15m long
Shipboard paraphernalia: A tiny stone cube that may be a gaming piece and a stone rod that appears to be a whetstone with what looks like Phoenician graffiti scratched onto the surface. Nuts and seeds including an acorn, a hazelnut and an olive pit give some idea of the provisions carried on board. A fluted stone pedestal may have been part of the ship's altar.
Ship equipment: Pine cones and numerous large round ballast stones may come from this wreck or from one of the other 2 wrecks in the area.

Name: Pseira
Reference: http://www.archaeology.org/1001/etc/minoan_shipwreck.html    http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/court_and_social/article7028160.ece
Comments: The first Minoan Shipwreck. Six seasons of exploration, ending in 2009, revealed a narrow trail of pottery about 100 feet long at the northern end of the wreck, according to the US journal Archaeology. This broadened out over an area 65 by 50 feet, and Dr Hadjidaki estimates that the ship itself was between 32 and 50 feet long. It had capsized as it sank, spreading the cargo across the sea-bed. She believes the ship probably looked something like the one shown on a sealstone found on Pseira in 1991, with a beaked prow, high stern, and single mast anchored by ropes. It was probably a coasting vessel, delivering everyday goods to ports along the Cretan shore; whether it used a sails, oars or both is not known. More than 200 pottery vessels have been recovered, about 80 of which are complete enough to be identifiable as amphorae and large jars, used for shipping liquids such as wine and olive oil. Philip Betancourt has dated all the vessels to roughly 1800-1675BC, and the clay from which they were made suggests that the ship took on cargo at two or more locations in eastern Crete.
Other cargo: Ceramics including jugs, cups and cooking pots.

Name: Chios Straits
Reference: B.P.  Foley and M.C. Hansson, Journal of Archaeological Science  35 (2008), 1169?76; Eleutheros Typos, Ta Nea 05/11/2007                           AR 51 (2004?2005), 90; AR 52 (2005?2006), 97    D. Sakellariou et al, IJNA 36 (2007), 365-381    B. Foley et al, Hesperia 78 (2009), 269-305                                                                                         http://www.whoi.edu/sbl/liteSite.do?litesiteid=2740&articleId=5698
Comments: A C4th BC wreck found in the straits between Chios and Oinousses during a 2004 sonar survey by HCMR scientists and Ephorate archaeologists. . Over 400 concentrated artefacts form a longitudinal body of high reflectivity which rises to by 1.5-2m above the sea floor.

Name: Protaras
Reference: http://www.inadiscover.com/cyprus/protaras.html                  http://heritage-key.com/blogs/bija-knowles/roman-shipwreck-coast-cyprus-was-carrying-french-wine         http://minervamagazine.com/news.asp?min_issue=JAN_FEB2010
Comments: A new wreck of the early imperial period was discovered in 2007. The site is badly damaged by wave action and strong currents, but the extent of the scatter and the presence of several interesting amphora types make it worthy of more intensive mapping and study. Dating probably around the very early 2nd century AD, the ship appears to have been carrying a mixed cargo in three or four amphora types. It is the only wreck of its date so far reported off the coast of Cyprus. The cargo’s generally regional character, interspersed with a few long-distance imports that were likely picked up locally at some port in the northeast Mediterranean, fits well with the wreck’s location not far offshore and may indicate an involvement in short-haul coasting commerce. About half the wreck is stil to be investigated.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Storage and cooking items were also found

Name: Polyaigos (marble)
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/544/          Dellaporta, A., Dimitriadou, Th., AD 54 (1999) [2006] B’2, p. 1031.
Marble type: A single column of cipollino from Carystos was found that may come from an otherwise unknown wreck transporting architectural elements.

Name: Agios Petros classical
Reference: F. Haniotis, Archaeologikon Deltion 49 (1994), 862-64; K. Delaporta et al, IJNA 35 (2006), 79-87
Comments: The earliest classical shipwreck found, with a cargo of Mendean amphorae.

Name: Portolafia 1
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/452/                Ethnos 05/11/2007
Comments: One of two shipwrecks 'probably from Pontos'?.

Name: Portolafia 2
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/452/                   Ethnos 05/11/2007
Comments: One of two wrecks found on the site.

Name: Megalo Stironisi
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/451/            Ethnos 05/11/2007
Comments: An antique tile wreck has been reported.
Other cargo: A cargo of tiles in sets of 6 and tied in large piles.

Name: Agios Andreas
Reference: Ethnos 05/11/2007          http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/450/
Comments: A shipwreck was discovered with a cargo of C5th-6th AD amphorae

Name: Petousi
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/449/       Ethnos 5/11/2007
Comments: A Roman shipwreck was found at this islet outside Styra. The cargo contained many 2nd?3rd Ct AD African amphorae for olive oil, of a type probably manufactured in Libya or Tunisia and generally found in the W Mediterranean (this is the first cargo in Greek waters).

Name: Prophete Elie
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/131/                   Spondilis, H., AD 54 (1999) [2006] p. 1024.
Comments: A C2nd AD wreck

Name: Plytra - Xyli Bay
Reference: http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/129/
Comments: A Roman wreck of metal pipes and anchors was discovered to the south-west of Pouda point.
Other cargo: Metal pipes?
Ship equipment: Iron anchors.

Name: Monemvasia - Kremmydi
Reference:
http://chronique.efa.gr/index.php/fiches/voir/127/                   Dellaporta, A., AD 54 (1999) [2006], p. 1023.
Spondilis, H., AD 54 (1999) [2006], p. 1025.
Comments: Three Roman wrecks are reported in the bay of Kremmydi

Name: Ashkelon Hellenistic/Roman
Reference: E. Galili et al, IJNA (2010) 39.1, 125-145
Comments: Discovered about 80-100m off the coast, the site covers an area of 30 x30m although the heavy artefacts were concentrated over an area 15 x 15m. The main cargo of this medium-sized ship must have been perishable as there are no signs of it. An interesting feature is the carpenter's set of new nails (cf a Hellenistic wreck from Apollonia and a Byzantine wreck south of Haifa).
Hull remains: Five broken, twisted and torn fragments of lead sheathing. Planks with a thickness of 4-5cm and the scattered nails indicate that the ship measured 15-25m.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Sixteen lead artefacts definable as fishing gear sinkers, three of which are decorated with patterns and unidentifiable inscriptions. Eight bronze weights with an inner lead core weighing between 0.9kg to 26 kg were also recovered along with three bronze balance scales. A set of bronze vessels were found in a relatively small area 3 x3m comprising an oil lamp, 2 ladles and an (incense?) shovel possibly used as a ceremonial group - other Israeli finds indicate ritual activities were carried out on board Greco-Roman ships. A metre long bronze trumpet was also found, an unusual find on a wreck site but it may well have had a nautical use like the modern fog horn.
Ship equipment: Four iron anchors (1.5-2m long) were found, a pair of 2-armed anchors with their stocks not inserted and two 1-armed anchors with their stocks in place. The 2-armed anchors can be classified as Kapitan intermediate type between A and B, thus dating them to the C2nd-1st BC, whilst 1-armed anchors from antiquity are relatively rare (another was found on the Ma'agan Michael wreck). Both used and unused copper alloy nails with round cross-section were also found - 53 new, straight nails in an area 2m x 2m, probably belonging to the ship's carpenter, whilst the old ones were spread over the site. Generally in Israel, nails of this type come from Hellenistic/Roman ships, cf Megadim wreck. A lead sounding weight was found nearby but its late from means it  may be an intrusion and not from this wreck.

Name: Yenikapi
Reference: U. Kocabas (ed.), The Old ships of the New Gate, vol I (2008)                               http://inadiscover.com/projects/all/southern_europe_mediterranean_aegean/yenikapi_harbor_wrecks_turkey/introduction/
Comments: Thirty-four wrecks have been found in the remains of a former harbour, the Portus Theodosiacus, and are in the process of being excavated. One is a galley and at least 9 are merchant ships measuring from 8m to 19m.
Hull remains: Many of the timbers are well preserved, with original tool marks and intricate detail.

Name: Cala Sant Vicents 2
Reference: X. Nieto and M Santos, El Vaixell Grec Arcaic de Cala Sant Vicenc (2008)
Comments: Excavated in 2002 and 2004, this ship seems to have been sunk when it came loose from its moorings in the bay and hit the submerged rocks. It is the largest wholly-sewn Greek ship yet to be studied at 20-22m long. 6.3m wide and c 2.1m depth of hold.
Other cargo: Bundles of iron tools, some tin ingots, baskets and grain-rubbers.
Hull remains: Only nine pine strakes and four oak frames survive. A false keel was fastened to the bottom of the keel by false tenons and the frames are similar to those of other archaic wrecks.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A necklace of glass beads. A fair amount of tableware, much of it 'Ionian bowls' as well as black-glazed, black-figured (without the figures!), Massiliot etc pottery, various lamps and mortaria. Some cooking ware and a pierced ceramic disc of a widespread type which here mught be a net- rather than a loom- weight. A basekt-lined bronze helmet and a repaired ladle, a goldsmith's mould, a carved wooden box-lid (cf one from Giglio Campse wreck) and a bracelet of lignite were also found.

Name: Porto Palermo
Reference: J. Royal, INA Annual 2008 26-28
Comments: A cargo of mainly African amphorae has been found during an ongoing exploration of the Illyrian coast.

Name: Boka Kotorska  1
Reference: J Royal, INA Annual 2008, 26-28; http://www.rpmnautical.org/bokakotorska1.htm
Comments: A cargo of tiles comprise a large shipment on what must have been a vessel of significant dimensions now spread over an area 25 x 7m
Other cargo: Pan tiles and cover tiles are in several stacks, many of which are now postitioned vertically. The pan tiles measure c 65 x 45 cm with flanges angled at 90 degrees and are characteristic of Roman manufacture during the Imperial period.

Name: Kekova Adasi
Reference: E. Greene et al, INA Annual 2008, 65-68
Comments: The wreck was first discovered in 1983 and has been recently revisited by INA. Its cargo was primarily held in basket-handle amphorae from the Cypro-Levantine coast, along with a number of SE Aegean and Corinthian amphorae.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Coarse ware includes large fragments of 2 mortaria and a roof tile.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones of round rivertine rocks

Name: Arapya Gulf
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Other cargo: Table ceramics, glass pots
Shipboard paraphernalia: Two coins

Name: Ropotamo River
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Other cargo: Luxury ceramics from Asia Minor

Name: Sozopol
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Pomorie 1-5
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: Five wrecks of cargoes of amphorae

Name: Pomorie 6
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: A cargo of tiles
Other cargo: Tiles

Name: Ravda
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Nesebar 1
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Nesebar 2
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Cape Cherni nos 1
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Varna
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: A cargo of amphorae was found 100-150m east of the shipyard of Vanya

Name: Lazuran bryag
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: Cargo has been found from 2 ships.

Name: Cape Chirakman, Kaliakra 1-2
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: The cargoes of two Hellenistic wrecks have been found.

Name: Cape Chirakman, Kaliakra 3-5
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: Cargoes from 3 early Byzantine wrecks have been found.

Name: Port Kavarna
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Cape Kaliakra
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34
Comments: A cargo of amphorae has been found 100m from the shore

Name: Cape Cherni nos 2
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Cape Cherni nos 3
Reference: S. Stanimirov, Archaeologia Bulgarica 7 (2003), 1-34

Name: Kekova Oludeniz
Reference: S. Kingsley, 46

Name: Cap de Volt
Reference: C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369
Hull remains: A mast-step coin, a bronze of Saguntum, was found.

Name: Chretienne H
Reference: J.-P. Joncheray, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 13 (1997), 137-164; C. Carreras Montfort and P. Berni Millet in Rivet and Sciallano (eds), Vivre, Produire et Echanger: Reflets Mediterraneans. Melanges offerts a Bernard Liou (2002), 359-369
Comments: This is probably the best known shipwreck carrying Tarraconense amphorae, containing both Pascual 1 and Dr 2-4

Name: Bozburun tile wreck
Reference: http://www.rpmnautical.org/tilewreck.htm           J. Royal, IJNA 37 (2008), 88-97
Comments: The site is a small mound measuring c 21 x 10m comprising both cover and pan tiles still in their stacked positions. A trail of amphorae starting about 10m from the site and continuing 600m away contains at least 3 concentrated depostis of numerous large body sherds and upper portions, a formation possibly caused by drag nets.
Other cargo: Roof tiles, both cover and pan: over 10 of red fabric with white inclusions have been exposed possibly by an octupus (!). The cover tiles are about 1m long and 0.2-0.3m  wide, and slightly rounded to form a convex shape that is more acute at their edges than at the centre, stacked one upon the other and lying on their sides.

Name: Çamalti Burnu 2
Reference: http://www.nautarch.org/sites.htm

Name: Sette Fratelli
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSI005.htm
Ship equipment: A large volcanic-stone anchor (left), about 1m long, was recovered from the wreck: this kind of anchor was successive to the ancient "three holes" lithic anchors, and represent an evolution to the form and the function of the lead ones.

Name: Les Catalans 2
Reference: L. Long and A. Hermary, Cahiers d'Archeologie Subaquatique 16 (2007), 117-130
Comments: A small bronze statue, fragments of 2 marble statues and a great number of unfinished architectural pieces were found 2001-2004. They may come from one wreck.
Marble type: The remains of 2 white marble statues.  One of the statues (46cm high) ressembles an Apollo although there is no head, datable to mid C1st AD, whilst the other is simply part of a female foot with a sandal. A great number of unfinished architectural pieces - columns, architraves, capitals, slabs - may or may not be from the same wreck.
Other cargo: The small bronze statue represents Apollo as well and is 12cm high, found 138m away from the marble statues. It is of mediocre quality and is datable to the Roman Imperial period.

Name: Golfo di Porto Azzurro
Reference: http://www.elba-vacanze.net/pagina.php?ling=i&rif_pagina=127&rif_argo=69&rif_tema=2&rif_cap=&rif_cap=41&p=0#
Comments: An unexplored Roman wreck with a cargo of tubi fittili per condutture

Name: Aci Trezza 1
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSI015.htm
Hull remains: Tiles from the cabin.
Ship equipment: Lead and iron anchors

Name: Aci Trezza 2
Reference: http://www.sportesport.it/wrecksSI015.htm
Comments: This second ship was found near the harbour of the Southern rock of Ciclopi Islets.
Other cargo: A cargo of millstones, of which 20 have been recovered and are now exhibited at Naxos Antiquarium.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A beautiful lead  "Romano da Stadera",  (a balance weight) representing Athena  was found between two rocks: it was probably used as a sound.

Name: Isola Rossa 2
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/678/1/trovati-due-relitti-nei-fondali-del-golfo-dellasinara.html
Comments: A Roman wreck found during a deep marine survey in 2007.

Name: Isola Rossa 3
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/678/1/trovati-due-relitti-nei-fondali-del-golfo-dellasinara.html
Comments: The second ancient wreck found during a deep marine survey in 2007
Other cargo: A concretion probably of metal

Name: Pisa Hellenistic ship
Reference: S. Bruni (ed.), Le Navi Antichi di Pisa: ad un Anno dall'Inizio delle Ricerche (2000);  G. Belluomini et al, Science and Technology for Cultural Heritage 11 (2002); M. Colombini et al, Archaeolmetry 45 (2003), 659-674; A. Camilli, Archaeologia Maritima Mediterranea 1 (2004), 53-75; E. Pecchioni et al, Arcaeometry 49 (2007), 1-22                           http://www.cantierenavipisa.it/Scavo_NaveEllenistica.html
Comments: One of nineteen well-preserved ancient ships found during construction work in San Rossore railway station, Pisa. A medium-sized merchant ship from Spain, with an estimated half of its cargo still on board. It had broken up as a result of a violent crash against the quayside, probably caused by a huge flood.
Hull remains: A few remains, indicating medium-sized vessel.
Shipboard paraphernalia: Ceramics including numerous kalathoi from southern Spain. An Iberian area origin is also given to the thymiateria, while some unguentari  seem of a massaliota production and one, of remarkable dimensions, seems to have been produced in Ampurias. Bones including the front shoulders of a pig were also found.
Ship equipment: Ballast stones.

Name: Comacchio
Reference: F. Berti (ed), Fortuna Maris: la nave romana di Comacchio (1990); M. Polzer, IJNA 37 (2008), 225-252.            http://www2.rgzm.de/Navis/Ships/Ship050/RelittoDiComacchio.htm                          http://www.sullacrestadellonda.it/archeo/comacchio.htm
Ship equipment: Wooden toggle

Name: Cape Zevgari
Reference: J. Leidwanger, IJNA 36 (2007), 308-316
Comments: Discovered during an INA underwater survey in 2003, one of two Late Roman wrecks found near Kourion. The site measures 35 x 15m
Ship equipment: A small rectangular blick of lead, pierced twice, apparently to be fixed with square nails cf C7th Yassi Ada with 4 of them - possibly some part of the galley or steering-oar complex.

Name: Avidmou Bay
Reference: J. Leidwanger, IJNA 36 (2007), 308-316
Comments: One of two Late Roman wrecks found in an INA underwater survey in 2004 near Kourion. Amphora numbers are uncertain as the site suffers from shifting sands and the amphorae may have been being recycled in which case the ship's final journey would have started in Cyprus, returning to the Gaza area for refilling.
Other cargo: Millstones
Ship equipment: Eleven stone anchors may or may not be part of this wreck.

Name: Skerki Bank Keith Reef 2
Reference: C. Weitmeyer and H. Dohler, IJNA 38 (2009), 254-280
Comments: Only a small number of amphorae were found which suggests that the ship's main cargo was organic, ie grain
Shipboard paraphernalia: The neck of a Beltran 2b amphora, abig flat-based amphora, a tile and an oil lamp with the inscription IVNDRA. .

Name: Skerki Bank Keith Reef 3
Reference: C. Weitmeyer and H. Dohler, IJNA 38 (2009), 254-280
Comments: A cargo of Late Roman amphorae and amphorettas
Other cargo: Seven mortaria, a rare find in late Roman wrecks, cf Ustica wreck

Name: Skerki Bank Keith Reef 4
Reference: C. Weitmeyer and H. Dohler, IJNA 38 (2009), 254-280
Comments: Several pieces of raw glass were found together with ceramic sherds too small to be datable. It is probable that they formed the cargo of a Roman wreck.
Other cargo: Pieces of raw glass, yellow, green and blue in colour, and weighing between 24 and 126gm. Analysis suggests that are ancient since they consist of sodium silicate which is typical of Roman glass.

Name: Skerki Bank Keith Reef 5
Reference: C. Weitmeyer and H. Dohler, IJNA 38 (2009), 254-280
Comments: At least 5 lead ingots weighing between 20 and 25kg were found together, presumably part of a Roman cargo.
Other cargo: At least 5 lead ingots, weighing between 20 and 25kg, some of which bear stamps.

Name: Vasiliko Bay Byzantine wrecks
Reference: K. Delaporta et al, IJNA 35 (2006), 79-88
Comments: Two large Byzantine shipwreck amphora mounds lie close to one another; a third was found a few hundred metres away in 2001 by the Greek-Norwegian deep-water archaeological survey team.Several hundred amphorae form a mound 17.5m long.

Name: Cape Glavat/Mljet B
Reference: M. Jurisic, Ancient Shipwrecks of the Adriatic (2000), no. 10
Comments: Dating of this wreck may be adjusted to 40-80 AD on the basis of the Italian terra sigillata Drag, 24/25?
Other cargo: Southern Italian pottery, 'orlo bifido' dishes with the plates/ lids (more than 500) and 15 Pompeian red plates. Great quantities of rough glass clumps.
Hull remains: Well preserved parts of the hull were found (7m long).
Shipboard paraphernalia: Italian terra sigillata Drag, 24/25 bearing the stamps PESCECLE and C.IUL.FIR (Pescenius Clemens and Caius Iulius Firmus) and  some eastern ware Five oil lamps and 2 glass vessels were of western origin. A few necks of Cretan amphorae, a number of  ECW pottery (mugs, jugs, dishes and lids) were of eastern origin.
Ship equipment: A lead anchor stock of  so-called movable model with astragali relief, 6 braces and part of a bronze steelyard were found.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 9
Reference: L. Long, Bilan Scientifique 1996, 75; Bilan Scientifique 1998, 34-35; Bilan Scientifique, 2002, 43; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 50-51
Comments: Another wreck of iron ingots
Other cargo: Hundreds of iron ingots of differing sizes in 4 rows and at least 2 layers in concreted masses, some stamped. A piece of ceramic?
Hull remains: A few planks, copper nails.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A Mayence type sword which dates the wreck to C1st AD.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 11
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998, 36
Other cargo: Iron ingots amalgamated with fragments of amphorae.
Hull remains: Some frames
Ship equipment: An iron anchor.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 13
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1998, 36
Comments: Another shipwreck of iron ingots.
Other cargo: Iron ingots
Hull remains: Fragments of wood.
Ship equipment: An iron anchor was found 20m away

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-mer 23
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2001, 50; Bilan Scientifique 2003, 65
Comments: Another wreck of iron ingots
Other cargo: Iron ingots in mass concretions, 3m x 2m
Shipboard paraphernalia: A basket/ container of small iron nails.

Name: Saintes-Maries-de-la-Mer 25
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 2003, 65-66; Bilan Scientifique 2005, 48
Comments: Another wreck of iron ingots
Other cargo: About 50 tons of iron bars and ingots in concretion.
Ship equipment: A stockless lead anchor, 2.65m long, and an iron anchor

Name: La Plage d'Argent 2
Reference: Bilan Scientifique 1999, 62-63

Name: Camarina bronzes
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2000/news0011.htm#camarina
Comments: A cargo of bronzes discovered in 2000.
Other cargo: Bronze objects including oil lamps, bronzes similar to those found in the noble houses of Pompeii and Herculaneum, decorative pots, braziers, chandeliers and parts of statuettes of Mercury.
Shipboard paraphernalia: A 35 cm section of a small altar.

Name: Mezzaluna
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: The hull of this medieval ship whose cargo was amphorae is currently covered by sand.
Hull remains: At the time of survey (1989) the shell of this 18-20m long ship was exposed and between the frames were the remains of two boxes of iron about. 2 x 1m each, covered by concretions.

Name: East Porto Pino
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: The remains of a cargo vessel which extends over an area of about 20 x 20m.
Hull remains: None.

Name: Porto Pino
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: A 10m long site of Afircan amphorae

Name: Punta Tonnara
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html

Name: Guardia de su Turcu
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/2/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html

Name: Cala del Falco 2
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/115/3/rinvenimenti-archeologici-subacquei-in-sardegna-sud-occ.html
Comments: A second Roman wreck in the bay
Ship equipment: Two lead anchor stocks.

Name: L'Asinara 1
Reference: http://www.archaeogate.org/subacquea/article/678/1/trovati-due-relitti-nei-fondali-del-golfo-dellasinara.html
Comments: A very deep wreck examined by ROV in 2007.

Name: Olbia Late Roman 2
Reference: R. D'Oriano, Archeologia in Sardegna, 2007,  98-103
Comments: Three other C5th AD wrecks found during construction works in Olbia and excavated between 1999 and 2001.

Name: Olbia medieval
Reference: R. D'Oriano, Archeologia in Sardegna, 2007,  98-103
Comments: Five small wrecks from the eleventh, fourteenth and fifteenth centuries have been found during construction work in Olbia and excavated between 1999 and 2001.

Name: Isola della Gallinara (Savona)
Reference: http://www.archeosub.it/news2003/news0311.htm#savona
Comments: A mound of intact Dr 1 amphorae and 'other cargo'  filmed in 2003 covers an area 20 x 10m.

Name: San Vito Lo Capo
Reference: F. Faccenna, Il Relitto di San Vito Lo Capo (2006)
Comments: A local Sicilian ship carrying amphorae and jars cf Marsala A and B wrecks.

Name: Capo Colonna and Capo Alfieri
Reference: http://www.archeomar.it/templates/archeomar/atlante/player_atlante_en.html         site 18, area 14
Comments: A probable Late Roman shipwreck of amphorae.
